{"title_page": "Bobby Richardson", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{about|the baseball player|the football player|Bobby Richardson (American football)|the North Carolina politician|Bobbie Richardson}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Bobby Richardson\n|image=Bobby Richardson - New York Yankees.jpg\n|caption=Richardson, circa 1964\u201366\n|position=[[Second baseman]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1935|8|19}}\n|birth_place=[[Sumter, South Carolina]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=August 5\n|debutyear=1955\n|debutteam=New York Yankees\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=October 2\n|finalyear=1966\n|finalteam=New York Yankees\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.266\n|stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat2value=34\n|stat3label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value=390\n|teams=\n* [[New York Yankees]] ({{mlby|1955}}\u2013{{mlby|1966}})\n|highlights=\n* 8\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1957 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1957]], [[1959 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (second game)|1959\u00b2]], [[1962 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|1962]]\u2013[[1966 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1966]])\n* 3\u00d7 [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|1958}}, {{wsy|1961}}, {{wsy|1962}})\n* [[World Series MVP]] (1960)\n* 5\u00d7 [[Gold Glove Award]] (1961\u20131965)\n}}\n'''Robert Clinton Richardson, Jr.''' (born August 19, 1935) is an American former professional baseball [[second baseman]]. He played in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) for the [[New York Yankees]] from 1955 through 1966. Batting and throwing right-handed, he formed a top double play combination with fellow Yankee [[infielder]]s [[Clete Boyer]] and [[Tony Kubek]]. In 1962, he led the [[American League]] (AL) in [[Hit (baseball)|hits]] with 209 and snared a [[line drive]] off the bat of [[Willie McCovey]] to win the [[1962 World Series]] for the Yankees. He is the only [[World Series MVP Award|World Series Most Valuable Player]] ever to be selected from the losing team.\n\nBorn in [[Sumter, South Carolina]], Richardson grew up desiring to play for the Yankees after seeing the 1942 film ''[[Pride of the Yankees]]''. Drawing interest from 11 out of 16 MLB teams, he signed with the Yankees and made his debut for them two years later. Earning a regular spot on the roster in 1957, Richardson reached his first [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] that year, though it was not until 1959 that he would become a regular at second base. In 1960, he was named the World Series MVP. Though the Yankees lost the Series in seven games to the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]], Richardson [[Batting average|batted]] .367 with 12 [[runs batted in]] (RBI). He won the next two World Series, ending the 1962 series by catching McCovey's line drive in what ''[[The Sporting News]]'' called baseball's 13th most memorable play. Richardson led the AL in hits that year, with 209.\n\nFrom 1961 to 1965, Richardson won five straight [[Gold Glove Award]]s at second base. He played in the All-Star Game every year from 1962 through 1966. In 1963, he won the [[Lou Gehrig Memorial Award]], and he played in the World Series in 1963 and 1964. His last two years in the major leagues, he had 164 and 153 hits, respectively. Though only 31 after the 1966 season, Richardson retired to spend more time with his family. The Yankees held a special day for him towards the end of the season, making Richardson the 10th Yankee to be so honored.\n\nAfter his playing career, Richardson [[Coach (baseball)|coached]] college teams for several years. He led the [[University of South Carolina]] to its first [[College World Series]] in 1975 and laid the groundwork for their later success. In 1986, he led [[Coastal Carolina University]]'s baseball team to a [[Big South Conference]] championship, and he coached at [[Liberty University]] from 1987 through 1990. Richardson ran for the [[United States House of Representatives]] in [[South Carolina's 5th congressional district]] as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] in 1976 but lost to incumbent [[Kenneth Lamar Holland|Kenneth Holland]]. A [[born-again Christian]], Richardson was involved in many Christian organizations during and after his career. He spoke at the [[White House]] in 1970 as a representative of the [[Fellowship of Christian Athletes]], appeared in five [[Billy Graham Crusade]]s, and frequently speaks at churches and other organizations.\n\n==Early life==\nRichardson was the middle child of Robert Sr. and Debbie Richardson of [[Sumter, South Carolina]]. He had two sisters, Inez (older) and Willie Ann (younger).<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Richardson Marble and Granite Works in Sumter was managed by Robert Sr., who also owned some of the interest in the company.<ref name=\"Richardson's father\">{{cite web|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1963/06/18/80711961.html?pageNumber=37|title=Bobby Richardson's Father, 57|work=The New York Times|date=June 18, 1963|accessdate=April 10, 2020|page=37}}</ref>\n\nEver since seeing ''[[Pride of the Yankees]]'', released in 1942, Richardson had dreamed of playing for the [[New York Yankees]]. Growing up, he practiced his baseball skills with Harry Stokes, a boy in his neighborhood seven years his senior who would play catch with him. Richardson played on a local [[YMCA]]/[[Salvation Army]] team at the age of ten. Later, he played on ballclubs sponsored by the local [[Kiwanis Club]] and [[American Legion]]. On the American Legion team, Richardson's coach was [[Fred Hutchinson]], who would later manage the [[Cincinnati Reds]] when Richardson faced them in the [[1961 World Series]]. Hutchinson and Richardson became American Legion champions in 1952, Richardson's junior year of high school. Hutchinson also coached Richardson at Edmunds High School.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\n11 out of 16 [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) teams showed interest in Richardson, as well as the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] and [[Georgia Tech University]], which offered baseball scholarships. [[Mayo Smith]], manager of the [[Norfolk Tars]], a team in the [[Class B (baseball)|Class B]] [[Piedmont League]] and an affiliate of the [[New York Yankees]], scouted Richardson for New York, as did Bill Harris. Ultimately, Richardson decided to forgo college and sign with the Yankees out of high school (though he later earned a degree in accounting).<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"Sunday Conversation\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===1953-56: Playing in the minor leagues, debuting with the Yankees===\nRichardson started his [[Minor league baseball|minor league]] career in 1953 with the [[Norfolk Tars]] of the [[Class B (baseball)|Class B]] [[Piedmont League]], travelling by bus to Norfolk from Sumter with $85 in coins friends and family had given him.<ref name=\"SABR\">{{cite web|last=Pasculli|first=Len|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/47363efd|title=Bobby Richardson|work=SABR|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> After Richardson [[Batting average|batted]] just .211 in his first 27 games with the Tars, the Yankees assigned him to a [[Class D (baseball)|Class D]] team, the [[Olean Yankees]] of the [[New York\u2013Penn League|PONY League]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"minors\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=richar007rob|title=Bobby Richardson Minor League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> With Olean, he batted .412 in 32 games and hit his first [[home run]].<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\nIn 1954, Richardson was promoted, heading up to the [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] [[Binghamton Triplets]] of the [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] without having to return to Norfolk. Spending the whole year in Binghamton, he ranked among the Eastern League leaders in games (141, tied for first), [[Runs scored|runs]] (81, fifth), 171 [[Hit (baseball)|hits]] (first), [[Double (baseball)|doubles]] (29, second to Clyde Parris's 40), and batting average (.310, second to Parris's .313).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=af825f91|title=1954 Eastern League Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> For his contributions, Richardson was named the Eastern League's [[Most Valuable Player]] (MVP).<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\nRichardson spent most of [[spring training]] with the Yankees in 1955 but was sent to the [[Class AAA (baseball)|Class AAA]] [[Denver Bears]] of the [[American Association (20th Century)|American Assocation]] to start the year.<ref>{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|page=31|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1955/04/01/85690101.html?pageNumber=31|title=Five Players Cut From Squad Before Yanks Start Northward|work=The New York Times|date=April 1, 1955|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> In 119 games with the Bears, he batted .296 with 146 hits, 99 runs scord, 21 doubles, 12 [[Triple (baseball)|triples]], six home runs, and 59 RBI.<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\nWhen [[Gil McDougald]] found himself on the receiving end of a [[line drive]] during [[batting practice]] in August of 1955, the Yankees called up Richardson.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> He debuted on August 5, 1955, getting his first hit against [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Famer]] [[Jim Bunning]] in a 3\u20130 victory over the [[Detroit Tigers]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In the field, he was a \"nervous wreck\" as he later described, but no balls were hit to him.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Bobby Richardson Story|first=Bobby |last=Richardson |location=Old Tappan, New Jersey|publisher=Fleming H. Revell Co.|year=1965|page=84}}</ref> He started four games at second base in three days (including an August 7 [[Doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]]), then entered three games in the late innings at [[shortstop]] before getting sent to the minor leagues on August 15 to make room for a [[pitcher]] returning from the [[disabled list]].<ref name=\"1955 Richardson\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Drebinger|first=John|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1955/08/16/79451253.html?pageNumber=26|title=Home Runs Mark 5\u20134, 12\u20136 Triumphs|work=The New York Times|date=August 16, 1955|accessdate=April 10, 2020|page=26}}</ref> For some reason, he was sent to the [[Richmond Virginians]] of the Class AAA [[International League]] this time, with whom he finished the season.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Called up again in [[September call-up|September]], he appeared in four more games for the Yankees before the end of the year.<ref name=\"1955 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1955|title=Bobby Richardson 1955 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1956, Richardson started the season with the Yankees. However, he only appeared in five games for them, batting .143 before getting sent back to Denver May 13.<ref>{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|page=42|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1956/05/14/93203323.html?pageNumber=42|title=Bombers Win, 11\u20132; Drop 5\u20131 Decision|work=The New York Times|date=May 14, 1956|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> With the Bears, he ranked among the American Association leaders in batting average (.328, third), runs scored (102, sixth), hits (175, fourth), doubles (30, ninth), and triples (12, tied with [[Willie Kirkland]] for second behind [[Larry Raines]]'s 14).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=62cbeec8|title=1956 American Association Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===1957-59: Becoming a full-time player===\nRichardson made the team in 1957 and took over the second base job from [[Billy Martin]], the Yankees' volatile infielder who injured himself in a deliberate golf cart collision with [[Mickey Mantle]] in spring training, then got into a highly-publicized brawl at the [[Copacabana (nightclub)|Copacabana Club]] in May before getting traded to the [[Kansas City Athletics]] in June.<ref name=\"Silence\">{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|page=34|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1957/06/25/84738480.html?pageNumber=34|title=Silence! Bobby Richardson at Work|work=The New York Times|date=June 25, 1957|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Golenbock|first=Peter|origyear=1994|title=Wild, High and Tight: The Life and Death of Billy Martin|publisher=Antenna Books|edition=Kindle version of Antenna Books ebook |page=2631\u20132644 |location=New York|year=2014|isbn=978-1-62306-022-0|ref={{sfnRef|Golenbock}}}}</ref> Richardson proved a quieter sort of character, if not a great hitter in 1957; manager [[Casey Stengel]] said, \"Look at him. He doesn't drink, he doesn't smoke, he doesn't chew, he doesn't stay out late, and he still can't hit .250.\"<ref name=\"SABR\"/> His fielding was better; [[Louis Effrat]] of ''The New York Times'' wrote June 25, \"He has thrilled the fans with his great stops and catches...no one gets rid of the ball quicker [on [[double play]]s].\"<ref name=\"Silence\"/> Actually, Richardson's .331 average trailed only Mantle among the Yankees on June 25,<ref name=\"Silence\"/> and he made his first appearance in the [[1957 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] that year.<ref name=\"reference\"/> However, he batted .188 over the rest of the year, finishing the season with a .256 mark and 78 hits in 305 [[at bat]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1957|title=Bobby Richardson 1957 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy September, Richardson was losing a lot of starts to [[Jerry Coleman]] at second base.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=colemje01&t=b&year=1957|title=Jerry Coleman 1957 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Even so, Stengel waited until the last minute to decide whether Coleman or Richardson would start at second base in the [[1957 World Series]] against the [[Milwaukee Braves]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1957/10/01/91165032.html?pageNumber=54|title=Mantle's Status Remains in Doubt|work=The New York Times|date=October 1, 1957|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Ultimately, Stengel chose Coleman, who started all seven games for the Yankees as Richardson was limited to two appearances as a [[pinch-runner]] and [[defensive replacement]].<ref name=\"reference\"/><ref name=\"Postseason Coleman\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=colemje01&t=b&year=0&post=1|title=Jerry Coleman Postseason Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The Yankees lost the Series in seven games.<ref name=\"Postseason Coleman\"/>\n\nColeman retired following the 1957 season, and Richardson began 1958 as the Yankees' starting second baseman.<ref>{{cite web|last=McGowen|first=Roscoe|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1957/11/22/90856130.html?pageNumber=38|page=38|title=Coleman Retires as Player After Nine Years with Yankees|work=The New York Times|date=November 22, 1957|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> After batting .203 through the Yankees' first 18 games, he missed 20 in a row as McDougald began getting the starts at second.<ref name=\"1958 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1958|title=Bobby Richardson 1958 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=mcdougi01&t=b&year=1958|title=Gil McDougald 1958 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Richardson started at second from June 5 through June 12 but thereafter spent most of the season on the bench until September, when he again got a few starts at second base.<ref name=\"1958 Richardson\"/> In 73 games (182 at bats), he batted .247 with 18 runs scored and 45 hits.<ref name=\"reference\"/> Richardson considered quitting baseball that season because of his struggles, but [[Ralph Houk]], the Yankees' [[General manager (baseball)|general manager]] and Richardson's former manager at Denver, convinced him to keep playing.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In the [[1958 World Series]], again against the Braves, Richardson finished three games for the Yankees at [[third base]] and also started Game 4 at third, though he was hitless in two at bats before getting pinch-hit for in the seventh by [[Elston Howard]].<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=0&post=1|title=Bobby Richardson Postseason Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA195810050.shtml|title=1958 World Series Game 4, Braves at Yankees, October 5|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> However, he became a World Series champion for the first time as this year, the Yankees defeated the Braves in seven games.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/>\n\nRichardson began 1959 as the Yankees' shortstop; Effrat wrote, \"[Richardson] is a tremendous fielder no matter where [the Yankees] play him.\"<ref name=\"Kiely\">{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1959/04/20/89183045.html?pageNumber=37|title=Kiely Is Credited with 5\u20134 Victory|work=The New York Times|page=37|date=April 20, 1959|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> He moved to second base on April 18 after McDougald suffered cracked knuckles, then returned to shortstop on April 29 when McDougald returned to the lineup.<ref name=\"Kiely\"/><ref name=\"1959 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1959|title=Bobby Richardson 1959 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Only batting .232 through the season's first twenty games, he was benched after May 5 in favor of [[Tony Kubek]].<ref name=\"1959 Richardson\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=kubekto01&t=b&year=1959|title=Tony Kubek 1959 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Bill Dickey]], the [[hitting coach]] for the Yankees, worked with Richardson to improve his hitting. In 1959, Richardson switched to a heavier bat and tried swinging harder at pitches.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Given the chance to start at second base again in mid-June, Richardson raised his batting average from .232 to .300 over six games with 11 hits in 18 at bats.<ref name=\"1959 Richardson\"/> He was on the roster for the [[1959 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (second game)|second All-Star Game]] of the year and remained the starting second baseman the rest of the season.<ref name=\"1959 Richardson\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Becker|first=Bill|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1959/08/03/88805148.html?pageNumber=31|title=Walker and Drysdale Expected to Start in Second All-Star Game|work=The New York TImes|page=31|date=August 3, 1959|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> On July 25, 1959, Richardson and [[Fritz Brickell]] both hit their first major league home runs, Richardson's coming against [[Paul Foytack]] in a 9\u20138 victory over the Tigers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1959/07/26/110087361.html?pageNumber=166|page=166|title=Homer Is Decisive|work=The New York Times|date=July 26, 1959|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Batting .298 coming into the final game of the year, Richardson was the only Yankee with a chance at hitting .300. Stengel promised to remove him from the game if he got a hit in his first at bat (moving his batting average to .300). Richardson flew out to [[Albie Pearson]] in his first at bat but got hits in his next two at bats to move his average to .301, then was pinch-hit for in the eighth, preserving the mark.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In 134 games (469 at bats), he had 53 runs scored, 141 hits, 18 doubles, six triples, two home runs (both against Foytack), and 33 RBI.<ref name=\"reference\"/><ref name=\"Shared Hero\">{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1960/10/09/99878556.html?pageNumber=276|page=276|title=Batting in 6 Runs, He Shares Role of Hero With Ford|work=The New York Times|date=October 9, 1960|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> His .301 average topped the Yankees and ranked sixth in the [[American League]] (AL),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1959-batting-leaders.shtml|title=1959 AL Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> and he finished 18th in AL [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player (MVP)]] voting after the season.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===1960-62: Starring in the World Series===\nIn 1960, Richardson remained the Yankees' starting second baseman all season.<ref name=\"1960 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1960|title=Bobby Richardson 1960 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> On April 30, June 30, and July 18, he had a season-high three hits.<ref name=\"1960 Richardson\"/> One of those hits on April 30 was his only home run of the year, against [[Arnie Portocarrero]], in a 16\u20130 victory over the [[Baltimore Orioles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/BAL/BAL196004300.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Baltimore Orioles Box Score, April 30, 1960|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> With the Yankees and Athletics tied 7\u20137 on May 6, Richardson singled against [[Bob Trowbridge]], stole second base, moved to third on a groundout by [[Ryne Duren]], then scored the winning run on a single by McDougald.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196005060.shtml|title=Kansas City Athletics at New York Yankees Box Score, May 6, 1960|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Batting .208 through June 17, he hit .370 from June 18 through July 23, raising his season average to .273. Thereafter, he batted .215 to finish the year with a .252 mark.<ref name=\"1960 Richardson\"/> In 150 games (460 at bats), he had 45 runs scored, 116 hits, 12 doubles, three triples, and 26 RBI.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nThe Yankees faced the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] in the [[1960 World Series]]. Richardson went hitless in Game 1 but contributed three in Game 2, scoring three runs as well as the Yankees won 16\u20133.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/> In Game 3, he came to bat in the first inning with the bases loaded against [[Clem Labine]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Terrell|first=Roy|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1960/10/17/the-knife-and-the-hammer|title=The Knife and the Hammer|work=Sports Illustrated|date=October 17, 1960|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Third base coach [[Frank Crosetti]] signaled him to [[Bunt (baseball)|bunt]], but after running the count to two strikes, Richardson cancelled the plan.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>{{efn|A bunt that goes [[Foul ball|foul]] with two strikes is considered the third strike to complete the strikeout.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.closecallsports.com/2013/07/case-play-2013-06-foul-bunt-with-two.html|title=Case Play 2013-06:Foul Bunt with Two Strikes (Completed)|date=10 July 2013|accessdate=28 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029021300/http://www.closecallsports.com/2013/07/case-play-2013-06-foul-bunt-with-two.html|archivedate=29 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>}} He remained at the plate long enough to run the at bat to a [[full count]], then hit a [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] to put the Yankees ahead 6\u20130. Up to bat with the bases loaded again in the fourth inning, he had a two-RBI single against [[Red Witt]]. His six RBI set a new record for most in a single World Series game.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In Game 4, he had two hits and drove in another run, but the Yankees lost this one 3\u20132.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/> After going hitless in Game 5, he hit two triples in Game 6, drove in three runs, and scored one in the Yankees' 12\u20130 rout of the Pirates to force Game 7.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/> He scored a run in the sixth inning, led off the ninth with a single against [[Harvey Haddix]], and scored another run, but New York lost the game 10\u20139.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PIT/PIT196010130.shtml|title=1960 World Series Game 7, Yankees at Pirates, October 13|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Though Pittsburgh second baseman [[Bill Mazeroski]] hit a [[walk-off home run]] in the bottom of the ninth to win the Series for Pittsburgh,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com/mlb/story/world-series-history-bill-mazeroski-s-home-run-to-win-1960-world-series-100616|title=World Series History: Bill Mazeroski\u2019s Home Run to Win 1960 World Series|work=Fox Sports|date=June 30, 2017|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> it was Richardson who would be named the [[World Series Most Valuable Player Award|World Series MVP]] after hitting .367 with 12 RBI.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/> He is the only World Series MVP who was playing for the losing team when he won the award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://baseball-almanac.com/awards/aw_mvpw.shtml|title=World Series Most Valuable Player Award|work=Baseball Almanac|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Sport Magazine gave him a new Corvette for his efforts.<ref name=\"Sunday Conversation\">{{cite web|last=Glover|first=Emery|url=https://thetandd.com/sports/t-d-sunday-conversation-with-bobby-richardson/article_378fc5f2-52ab-11e0-815b-001cc4c03286.html|title=T&D Sunday Conversation with...Bobby Richardson|work=The Times & Democrat|date=March 20, 2011|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Since he had a growing family, Richardson traded the car for a Jeep. His son was very disappointed he decided to do that<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\nHouk took over from Stengel as the Yankee manager in 1961; he inserted Richardson either first or second into the [[Batting order (baseball)|batting order]] each game.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> On June 15, he had three hits and four RBI, including a three-run home run against [[Johnny Antonelli]] as the Yankees beat the [[Cleveland Indians]] 11\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|page=54|last=Drebinger|first=John|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1961/06/15/issue.html|title=Yankees Crush Indians|work=The New York Times|date=June 15, 1961|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> He had four RBI again in the second game of a doubleheader on July 9, including a three-run home run against [[Don Schwall]], but the Yankees lost that game 9\u20136 to the [[Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196107092.shtml|title=Boston Red Sox at New York Yankees Box Score, July 9, 1961|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> On August 17, he had three hits and scored three runs in a 5\u20133 victory over the [[Chicago White Sox]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196108170.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at New York Yankees Box Score, August 17, 1961|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> The Yankees lost 6\u20134 to the [[Los Angeles Angels]] on August 26, but Richardson had five hits in the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/LAA/LAA196108240.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Los Angeles Angels Box Score, August 24, 1961|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> Playing all 162 games for the Yankees, Richardson batted .261 with 80 runs scored, 17 doubles, five triples, three home runs, and 49 RBI.<ref name=\"reference\"/> His 662 at bats were third in the AL (behind [[Brooks Robinson]]'s 668 and [[Jake Wood (baseball)|Jake Wood]]'s 663), and his 173 hits were fifth in the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1961-batting-leaders.shtml|title=1961 AL Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2010}}</ref> Defensively, he led the AL with 413 [[putout]]s and 136 double plays assisted in.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Richardson finished 24th in MVP voting and won the [[List of Gold Glove Award winners at second base|Gold Glove at second base]], the first of five straight he would win at the position.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nRichardson had no RBI in the [[1961 World Series]] against the [[Cincinnati Reds]] but did bat .391, with nine hits in 23 at bats. He had three hits apiece in Games 1 and 4.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/> In Game 4, he led off the seventh inning with a single against [[Jim Brosnan]], advanced to second when [[Vada Pinson]] misplayed the ball, moved to third base on a [[wild pitch]] by Brosnan, and scored on a single by [[H\u00e9ctor L\u00f3pez]] as the Yankees won 7\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CIN/CIN196110080.shtml|title=1961 World Series Game 4, Yankees at Reds, October 8|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> The Yankees defeated the Reds in five games, making Richardson a World Series champion for the second time.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/>\n\nOn June 9, 1962, against the Orioles, Richardson had four hits, including a two-run home run against [[Steve Barber]] that tied the game at two in the seventh; the Yankees went on to win 7\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196206090.shtml|title=Baltimore Orioles at New York Yankees Box Score, June 9, 1962|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> He was selected to both of the All-Star Games in 1962.<ref name=\"reference\"/> With the Yankees trailing the [[Minnesota Twins]] 7\u20134 in the ninth inning on August 16, 1962, at [[Metropolitan Stadium]], Richardson came up to the plate with the bases loaded. Before the at bat, Mantle told him, \"See if you can hit one out. I'm not feeling too good today.\"<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Richardson hit a home run to left field against [[Dick Stigman]], the only grand slam of his career besides his one in the 1960 World Series. Though the hit put the Yankees ahead 8\u20137, they would lose the lead in the bottom of the ninth and lose in [[extra innings]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Two days later, he had three hits and two runs scored, including a three-run home run against [[Orlando Pe\u00f1a]] in an 11\u20137 victory over the Athletics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/KC1/KC1196208182.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Kansas City Athletics Box Score, August 18, 1962|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> Against the [[Washington Senators (1960-1971)|Washington Senators]] on September 19, he had four hits, two runs scored, and an RBI in an 8\u20135 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/WS2/WS2196209190.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Washington Senators Box Score, September 19, 1962|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> The [[Society for American Baseball Research]] called 1962 his most productive year, as he batted .302 with eight home runs, 59 RBI, and 11 stolen bases in 161 games.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"reference\"/> He led the AL in hits (209) and at bats (692). Richardson also ranked among the league leaders in runs scored (99, tied for fourth with [[Carl Yastrzemski]]), batting average (.302, seventh), and doubles (38, fourth).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1962-batting-leaders.shtml|title=1962 AL Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> He finished second to Mantle in AL MVP voting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/awards_1962.shtml|title=1962 Awards Voting|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Yankees faced the [[San Francisco Giants]] in the [[1962 World Series]]. Richardson batted a mere .148 in this Series,<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/> though he did have two hits and two runs scored in the Yankees' 5\u20133 triumph of Game 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196210100.shtml|title=1962 World Series Game 5, Giants at Yankees, October 10|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>  However, his glove would provide one of the most famous memories of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/25138329/willie-mccovey-san-francisco-giants-legend-dies-80|title=Willie McCovey, Hall of Famer and Giants legend, dies at age 80|work=ESPN|date=October 31, 2018|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> In Game 7, the Yankees had the only run of the game going into the bottom of the ninth inning, needing three outs to win the series. [[Matty Alou]] led off with a single, however, and after two strikeouts, Mays doubled to put the tying run (Alou) at third with future Hall of Famer [[Willie McCovey]] coming to bat. If Mays scored, the Giants would win the series.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> McCovey hit a screaming line drive up the middle which likely would have scored both runs had it made it out of the infield. Hardly moving from his position, Richardson snared the ball for the third out, winning the Series for the Yankees.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> \"People often suggest that I was out of position on that play,\" Richardson remembered later. \"But McCovey hit two hard ground balls to me earlier in the Series, so I played where I thought he would hit the ball.\"<ref name=\"SABR\"/> McCovey still had bad memories of it years later. \"I broke in with a 4-for-4 my rookie year against a Hall of Fame pitcher, [[Robin Roberts (baseball)|Robin Roberts]],\" he recalled. \"I hit more grand slams [18] than anybody in [[National League]] history. I hit more home runs [521] than any lefthanded hitter in the National League. But that out is what many people remember about me....I would rather be remembered as the guy who hit the ball six inches over Bobby Richardson's head.\"<ref name=\"SABR\"/> ''Sporting News'' ranked the catch the 13th most memorable moment in baseball history,<ref name=\"SABR\"/> and [[Charles Schulz]] famously referenced it in a ''[[Peanuts]]'' comic strip, where [[Charlie Brown]] yells, \"Why couldn\u2019t McCovey have hit the ball just three feet higher?\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Bush|first=Frederick C.|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/charlie-brown|title=Charlie Brown|work=SABR|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===1963-66: Extending his streaks===\n[[File:Bobby Richardson 1963.JPG|thumb|left|180px|Richardson in 1963.]]\nOn April 23, 1963, Richardson had three hits, two RBI, and two runs scored in a 7\u20136 victory over the Senators.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/WS2/WS2196304210.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Washington Senators Box Score, April 21, 1963|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> During the season, his father suffered a stroke in May, then died on July 17. Richardson missed 11 games during the year visiting him and helping get his affairs in order.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"Richardson's father\"/> He had a season high of four hits in a game twice in quick succession, on July 4 in the first game of a doubleheader and on July 6.<ref name=\"1963 Richardson\"/> He again represented the Yankees in the [[1963 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]].<ref name=\"reference\"/> On September 5, he singled against [[Steve Ridzik]], stole second base, and scored on a [[Roger Maris]] hit due to an error by shortstop [[Ed Brinkman]] to tie a game with the Senators at 2 in the sixth inning. The Yankees went on to win 3\u20132 in 12 innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196309050.shtml|title=Washington Senators at New York Yankees Box Score, September 5, 1963|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> After setting a career high with eight home runs the year before, Richardson hit three in 1963, all in Yankee losses.<ref name=\"1963 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1963|title=Bobby Richardson 1963 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> In 151 games, Richardson batted .265 with 72 runs scored and 48 RBI.<ref name=\"reference\"/> He led the league in at bats (630) for the second year in a row, finished seventh with 167 hits and tied three other players for seventh with 15 stolen bases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1963-batting-leaders.shtml|title=1963 AL Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Richardson again garnered AL MVP votes, finishing tenth this time.<ref name=\"reference\"/> He won the [[Lou Gehrig Memorial Award]], given by Gehrig's [[Columbia University]] fraternity to the [[Major League Baseball|major leaguer]] who best demonstrates Gehrig's character.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\nIn Game 1 of the [[1963 World Series]], which the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] swept in four games, Richardson struck out three times against [[Sandy Koufax]]\u2014his only three-strikeout game in 1,448 regular-season/World Series games.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=richabo01|title=Bobby Richardson Stats|work=Baseball Almanac|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> (Koufax would finish with 15 strikeouts, then a World Series single-game record.) Just that regular season, Richardson had struck out only 22 times in 630 at-bats.<ref name=\"reference\"/> He had a mere three hits in the World Series but played each game; Richardson had now played in 23 straight World Series games dating back to 1960.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/>\n\nOn May 10, 1964, Richardson had five hits and scored three runs in a 12\u20132 victory over the Indians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE196405101.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Cleveland Indians Box Score, May 10, 1964|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Less than a month later, he had five hits on June 4 in a 9\u20137 victory over the Twins.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/MIN/MIN196406040.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Minnesota Twins Box Score, June 4, 1964|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He picked up his 1,000th hit on June 12 with a [[line drive]] to left field against [[Frank Baumann (baseball)|Frank Baumann]] in a 6\u20131 victory over the White Sox in the first game of a doubleheader. The hit had proved difficult to come by for Richardson, who had put the ball in play seven times in his last two games without reaching base safely.<ref>{{cite web|last=Durso|first=Joseph|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1964/06/13/97397828.html?pageNumber=16|title=Yanks Beat White Sox 6\u20131 |work=The New York Times|page=16|date=June 13, 1964|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Once again, he was selected to the [[1964 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]].<ref name=\"reference\"/> In the first game of a doubleheader on July 26, he had three hits, including a two-RBI single against [[Mickey Lolich]] and a solo home run against [[Terry Fox (baseball)|Terry Fox]] in an 11\u20136 victory over the Tigers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/DET/DET196407261.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Detroit Tigers Box Score, July 26, 1964|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> In 159 games, he batted .267 with four home runs, 50 RBI, and 11 stolen bases.<ref name=\"reference\"/> For the third year in the row, he led the AL in at bats with 679. He also led the league with 148 singles, ranked third in the league with 181 hits (behind [[Tony Oliva]]'s 217 and B. Robinson's 294), and tied [[Bob Allison]] for ninth in the AL with 90 runs scored.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1964-batting-leaders.shtml|title=1964 AL Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He finished 17th in AL MVP voting after the season.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nIn the [[1964 World Series|World Series]] against the [[St. Louis Cardinals]], Richardson set a World Series record with 13 hits; this record has since been tied by [[Lou Brock]] and [[Marty Barrett (second baseman)|Marty Barrett]] in the [[1968 World Series|1968]] and [[1986 World Series]], respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-almanac.com/rb_ws3.shtml|title=World Series Hitting Records|work=Baseball Almanac|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> However, batting against Cardinal ace [[Bob Gibson]] with the Yankees trailing 7\u20135 in the ninth inning of Game 7, he popped out to [[Dal Maxvill]] for the final out of the Series. Richardson also had the dubious distinction of committing errors that affected the outcome of two games in the Series. In the sixth inning of Game 4, he mishandled [[Dick Groat]]'s ground ball for a double play that would have ended the inning with no runs scoring; the error was followed one batter later by [[Ken Boyer]]'s grand slam\u2014the four runs the Cardinals needed in defeating the Yankees 4\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196410110.shtml|title=1964 World Series Game 4, Cardinals at Yankees, October 11|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> In the fifth inning of Game 5, he bobbled [[Curt Flood]]'s double play ground ball, which also would have ended that inning without any damage. The Cardinals eventually scored twice in the inning, then won the game 5\u20132 on [[Tim McCarver]]'s 10th inning, three-run home run.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196410120.shtml|title=1964 World Series Game 5, Cardinals at Yankees, October 12|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> This was Richardson's final (of seven) World Series; he played all 30 World Series games from 1960 through 1964.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/>\n\nOn May 24, 1965, he had three hits, drove in two runs, and scored two more times in a 15\u20135 victory over Cleveland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196505240.shtml|title=Cleveland Indians at New York Yankees Box Score, May 24, 1965|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> After hitting into a [[fielder's choice]] on June 15, Richardson stole second base, then scored on a Maris single to put the Yankees up 1\u20130; however, the Yankees would lose the game 2\u20131 in the 10th inning.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196506150.shtml|title=Baltimore Orioles at New York Yankees Box Score, June 15, 1965|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He was selected to the [[1965 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] once again.<ref name=\"reference\"/> On July 17, he had four hits and scored twice in a 5\u20134 victory over Washington.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196507170.shtml|title=Washington Senators at New York Yankees Box Score, July 17, 1965|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Five days later, his home run against [[Gary Peters]] put the Yankees ahead to stay in a 2\u20131 victory over the White Sox.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196507220.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at New York Yankees Box Score, July 22, 1965|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> On August 8, [[Ray Barker (baseball)|Ray Barker]] and Richardson hit back-to-back home runs against [[Denny McLain]] in a 6\u20135 victory over the Tigers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/DET/DET196508080.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Detroit Tigers Box Score, August 8, 1965|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> In 160 games, Richardson batted .247 with 76 runs scored, 164 hits, 28 doubles, six home runs, and 47 RBI.<ref name=\"reference\"/> He finished 20th in AL MVP voting.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nRichardson had three hits and scored three times on May 25 in an 11\u20136 victory over the Angels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196605250.shtml|title=California Angels at New York Yankees Box Score, May 25, 1966|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He hit a three-run double against [[Tommy John]] on June 2 to turn a 3\u20132 deficit into a 5\u20133 lead for the Yankees, who defeated the White Sox.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA196606020.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Chicago White Sox Box Score, June 2, 1966|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Five days later, he had three hits, three runs scored, and three RBI, including a home run against [[John O'Donoghue (1960s pitcher)|John O'Donoghue]] in a 7\u20132 victory over the Indians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE196606070.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Cleveland Indians Box Score, June 7, 1966|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> On June 29, he had five hits, one of which was a home run against [[Rollie Sheldon]] and was followed by two more by Mantle and [[Joe Pepitone]] in a 6\u20135 victory over the Red Sox.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/BOS/BOS196606290.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Boston Red Sox Box Score, June 29, 1966|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Richardson made the [[1966 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] for the fifth year in a row, his seventh and final selection.<ref name=\"reference\"/> He had four hits on August 15, including a home run against Lolich, as the Yankees defeated the Tigers 6\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/DET/DET196608150.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Detroit Tigers Box Score, August 15, 1966|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> On September 11, he hit his last major league home run against [[John Wyatt (baseball)|John Wyatt]] in the 10th inning of a 4\u20132 victory over the Red Sox.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> He played in his final game on October 2, recording a hit and an RBI in a 2\u20130 victory over the White Sox.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In 149 games, he batted .251 with 71 runs scored, 153 hits, 21 doubles, seven home runs, and 42 RBI.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nThough he was just 31 following the 1966 season, Richardson retired following the year. He had decided to retire after the 1965 season, but the Yankees convinced him to play one more season since Kubek had to retire due to injuries after the 1965 campaign.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> \u201cI wanted to take the kids to school, help them with homework and watch or help coach their teams,\u201d he explained.<ref name=\"Baptist Courier\"/> The Yankees honored him by declaring September 17 \"Bobby Richardson Day,\" making Richardson the tenth Yankee to be honored at the stadium with a special day. \u201cHow lucky it has been for me to have been a Yankee. To God be the glory,\" he addressed the fans.<ref name=\"Baptist Courier\"/>\n\n===Legacy===\nRichardson racked up 1,432 hits in his career, with a lifetime batting average of .266, 34 home runs and 390 RBIs. Over his 12-year major league career, he scored 643 runs and stole 73 stolen bases. He also had 196 doubles and 37 triples. Defensively, he had an all-time [[fielding percentage]] of .979 at second base, and six seasons with 100 or more double plays turned.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nFrom 1961 to 1965, Richardson won five straight Gold Gloves at second base (not until [[Robinson Can\u00f3]] in 2010 would another Yankee second baseman win a Gold Glove)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-almanac.com/awards/aw_gg2b.shtml|title=Gold Glove Second Basemen|work=Baseball Almanac|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> while forming a top double play combination with shortstop and roommate Kubek. With the light-hitting but superb-fielding Yankee [[third baseman]] [[Clete Boyer]], Richardson and Kubek gave the Yankees arguably the best defensive infield in baseball in the early 1960s.<ref>{{cite web|last=Madden|first=Bill|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/clete-boyer-yanks-3rd-man-article-1.221914|title=Clete Boyer, Yanks' 3rd man|work=The New York Daily News|date=June 5, 2007|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Walker|first=Ben|agency=Associated Press|url=http://archive.boston.com/news/globe/obituaries/articles/2007/06/05/clete_boyer_at_70_3d_baseman_for_yanks_was_brilliant_fielder/|title=Clete Boyer, at 70; 3d baseman for Yanks was brilliant fielder|work=boston.com|date=June 5, 2007|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRichardson was also known for his ability to [[Contact hitter|make contact]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hoch|first=Bryan|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/best-second-basemen-in-yankees-history|title=Yankees' Top 5 second basemen: Hoch's take|work=MLB.com|date=April 6, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He struck out just 243 times, less than 5% of his [[plate appearance]]s.<ref name=\"reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/richabo01.shtml|title=Bobby Richardson Stats|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> A leadoff hitter who rarely missed a game, Richardson led the league in at bats three times.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"reference\"/> Following Martin's trade, he wore the uniform number 1 for the majority of his career (1958\u20131966).<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"reference\"/> He led the league in at bats per strikeout three times during his career, 1964\u20131966.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/at_bats_per_strikeout_leagues.shtml|title=Yearly League Leaders & Records for AB per SO|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> A skilled bunter, he led the league in [[sacrifice bunt|sacrifice hits]] in 1962 and 1964.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===Coaching===\nIn the late 1960s, [[Paul Dietzel]] asked Richardson if he would become the head baseball coach for the [[South Carolina Gamecocks|University of South Carolina Gamecocks]]. Richardson told him no twice, as he was under a personal services contract with the Yankees. However, after Dietzel asked him a third time, Richardson secured permission from the Yankees to take the job, assuming the role in 1970.<ref name=\"The Item\">{{cite web|last=Brunson|first=Dennis|url=https://www.theitem.com/stories/the-sumter-items-top-125-sports-figures-no-1-bobby-richardson,338621|title=The Sumter Item's Top 125 Sports Figures: No. 1 - Bobby Richardson|work=The Sumter Item|date=December 26, 2019|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He would often pitch batting practice and drive the team bus for events. Richardson also tried to perform recruiting for the school but delegated the responsibility to others after he figured out \"I wasn't going after the good players.\"<ref name=\"finah\">{{cite web|last=Keith|first=Larry|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1975/06/02/nothin-could-be-finah|title=Nothin', could be finah|work=Sports Illustrated|date=June 2, 1975|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Under Richardson, Larry Keith of ''Sports Illustrated'' wrote, \"South Carolina rarely bunts, often hits-and-runs and is always looking for the big inning.\"<ref name=\"finah\"/> Richardson led the Gamecocks to their first [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) Tournament appearance in 1974, which set the stage for what would happen a year later in 1975 when South Carolina posted a 51\u20136\u20131 record and made the [[1975 College World Series|College World Series]] for the first time ever.  They advanced all the way to the national championship game against Texas before losing 5\u20131 to the Longhorns. Richardson left South Carolina after the 1976 season, finishing his tenure with a 221\u201392\u20131 record and three NCAA Tournament appearances.<ref name=\"The Item\"/>  Dennis Brunson of ''The Item'' said of Richardson's contributions, \"Richardson had laid the groundwork for a program that would participate in the regionals in nine of the first 13 years under [new head coach [June] Raines and would play in the CWS four times.\"<ref name=\"The Item\"/> In the 1980s, Richardson served as the baseball coach for two seasons (1985\u201386) at [[Coastal Carolina University]] in [[Conway, South Carolina]], where he compiled a record of (61\u201338) and led the team to the [[Big South Conference]] championship in 1968.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://goccusports.com/story.aspx?filename=Baseball_Hosts_IMIChotels_com_INN_vitational_This_Weekend&file_date=2/15/2006|title=Baseball Hosts IMIChotels.com INN-vitational This Weekend|work=goccusports.com|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=February 15, 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420231139/https://goccusports.com/story.aspx?filename=Baseball_Hosts_IMIChotels_com_INN_vitational_This_Weekend&file_date=2%2F15%2F2006|archivedate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> After the 1986 season, he resigned as head coach at Coastal Carolina to replace [[Al Worthington]] as the baseball coach at [[Liberty University]]. \"I came here as athletic director under a different administration and [Chancellor] Ron [Eaglin] felt I should resign as athletic director and focus on baseball,\" Richardson explained the decision to resign, with Eaglin saying the two had disagreed on a budget for the next season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/10/sports/sports-people-richardson-moves-on.html?searchResultPosition=5|title=Sports People; Richardson Moves On|work=The New York Times|page=D-31|date=April 10, 1986|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Worthington, who had become Liberty's athletic director, served as pitching coach under Richardson, who coached the Flames for the next four seasons before retiring in 1990.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Jacobs|first=Barry|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/03/21/sports/building-from-the-ground-up-falwell-sees-liberty-as-an-athletic-powerhouse.html|title=Building From the Ground Up; Falwell Sees Liberty as an Athletic Powerhouse|work=The New York Times|page=B9|date=March 21, 1989|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==1976 political campaign==\nIn 1974, Nixon tried to convince Richardson to run as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] for the [[United States House of Representatives]] in [[South Carolina's 5th congressional district]]. Later, a private poll indicated he would have been the favorite had he run.<ref name=\"finah\"/> Two years later, President [[Gerald Ford]] succeeded in convincing Richardson to resign from his coaching position at the University of South Carolina to run for the seat.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"The Item\"/> Richardson lost to incumbent [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Kenneth Lamar Holland|Kenneth Holland]] by a narrow margin. Holland was aided by the strength of [[Jimmy Carter]]'s winning campaign in South Carolina to hold off Richardson by a tally of 66,073 (51.4%) to 62,095 (48.3%). His campaign was supported by former baseball players [[Joe DiMaggio]], [[Ted Williams]], [[Bob Feller]], and [[Wilmer Mizell|Wilmer \"Vinegar Bend\" Mizell]] among others, though former roommate Kubek declined to campaign for him because Kubek was a Democrat.<ref>{{cite book |title=October 1964 |last= Halberstam |first=David |authorlink= |year=1995 |publisher=Random House Digital, Inc. |location= |isbn= 0-449-98367-6 |pages=366\u2013367 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sZ7sUkp5eBcC&lpg=PP1&dq=october%201964&pg=PA366#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBetsy Dobson, Richardson's future spouse, met him at Grace Baptist Church of Sumter.<ref name=\"Baptist Courier\">{{cite web|last=Gray|first=Rudy|url=https://baptistcourier.com/2016/07/christian-faith-marks-yankee-legend-bobby-richardsons-career-home-life/|title=Christian faith marks Yankee legend Bobby Richardson\u2019s career, home life|work=Baptist Courier|date=July 5, 2016|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> In 1954, they went to a [[miniature golf]] course on their first date. Two years later, they were married. In an unusual move, Houk granted Richardson permission to leave the Denver Bears midseason to get married.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> The couple had three sons\u2013Robbie (born 7/2/57), Ron (7/13/58), and Rich (8/27/68)\u2013and two daughters\u2013Christie (12/30/60) and Jeannie (1/21/64).<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In 1960, the Richardsons were renting a house in [[Ridgewood, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/> They lived Sumter during offseasons, where Richardson was a general secretary for the local [[Young Men's Christian Association]] and host for a radio sports show.<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/> Hunting is one of his favorite hobbies.<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/> He and teammate [[Bobby Shantz]] went gun shopping together in Kansas City in 1959,<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/> and fellow major-leaguer [[Billy O'Dell]] used to hunt with him in the offseason.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> His roommates when travelling with the Yankees at various times included Kubek and Shantz.<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/>\n\nRichardson is a [[born-again Christian]]. During his time with the Yankees, he would organize church services for the team when they were travelling. Friend and teammate [[Mickey Mantle]] described him as a \"clean-living, practicing Christian.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Mantle|first=Mickey|title=The Mick|location=New York|publisher=Jove Books|year=1985|page=220|isbn=978-0385194563}}</ref> He was involved with the [[Fellowship of Christian Athletes]] (FCA) and the [[American Tract Society]] (ATS) during his career, as well as many charities.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> After his career, he continued to be involved with those organizations. He served as the president of the Baseball Chapel for 10 years, served on the President's Council for Physical Fitness, and earned the Golden Gavel Award from [[Toastmasters International]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/> President [[Richard Nixon]], who hosted church services at the [[White House]] each week of his presidency, invited the FCA to speak on October 18, 1970. One of four representatives, Richardson spoke on [[Jesus and the rich young man]] from [[Gospel of Mark|Mark]], Chapter 10. Concerning the young man's search for guidance, Richardson said, \"He didn't go to India and ask a guru; he didn't get caught up in the younger generation, but he went to God's son, Jesus Christ, the Messiah, with his question.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|last=Fiske|first=Edward B.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/08/08/archives/praying-with-the-president-in-the-white-house-praying-with-the.html|page=SM-14|title=Praying With the President In the White House|work=The New York Times|date=August 8, 1971|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> He has spoken at five [[Billy Graham Crusade]]s, as well as at various churches.<ref name=\"Baptist Courier\"/> Today, he is a speaker with Christian Speakers 360, available to appear at events.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianspeakers360.com/speaker/bobby-richardson.php|title=Bobby Richardson Speaker Information|work=Christian Speakers 360|accessdate=April 16, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813113113/http://www.christianspeakers360.com/speaker/bobby-richardson.php|archivedate=August 13, 2016}}</ref> Several of his Yankee teammates requested that he preside at their funerals, most notably Mickey Mantle. Speaking to an audience of 2,000 (plus television viewers) at Mantle's interment, Richardson said there were two types of people in this world, those who said yes to Christ and those who said no. Shortly before Mantle's death, as Richardson had visited Mantle in a Dallas hospital, Mantle had told Richardson that he had become a Christian.<ref name=\"The Item\"/>\n\nIn 1965, Richardson released his autobiography, ''The Bobby Richardson Story''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Richardson|first1=Bobby|title=The Bobby Richardson Story|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17332889-the-bobby-richardson-story|website=Goodreads|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The story became a movie in 1968.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1968/04/24/77085708.html?pageNumber=35|title=Bobby Richardson Film To Be Shown Saturday|work=The New York Times|page=35|date=April 24, 1968|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Excerpts from the film's audio track were available on an [[LP record]] titled: ''The Bobby Richardson Story: The Exciting First-Person Account of His Own Life, By the Yankees' Famous Second Baseman''.<ref>{{cite AV media|people=Richardson, Bobby (author and narrator)|date=1968|title=The Bobby Richardson Story: The Exciting First-Person Account of His Own Life, By the Yankees' Famous Second Baseman|medium=LP record|location=Waco, TX|publisher=Word Records Inc.}}</ref> He released a new autobiography in 2012 called ''Impact Player''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Freeze|first=Trevor|url=https://billygraham.org/story/bobby-richardson-leaving-a-legacy/|title=Bobby Richardson Leaving a Legacy|work=Billy Graham Evangelistic Association|date=January 9, 2012|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Major League Baseball players who spent their entire career with one franchise]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Baseballstats|mlb=121161|espn=26747|br=r/richabo01|fangraphs=1010903|brm=richar007rob}}\n\n{{1958 New York Yankees}}\n{{1961 New York Yankees}}\n{{1962 New York Yankees}}\n{{World Series MVPs}}\n{{Lou Gehrig Memorial Award}}\n{{AL 2B Gold Glove Award}}\n{{South Carolina Gamecocks head baseball coaches}}\n{{Liberty Flames baseball coach navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richardson, Bobby}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball second basemen]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees players]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees scouts]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Gold Glove Award winners]]\n[[Category:Olean Yankees players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Fellowship of Christian Athletes]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Republicans]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Gamecocks baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Liberty Flames baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Coastal Carolina Chanticleers baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:American athlete-politicians]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sumter, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:World Series Most Valuable Player Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{about|the baseball player|the football player|Bobby Richardson (American football)|the North Carolina politician|Bobbie Richardson}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Bobby Richardson\n|image=Bobby Richardson - New York Yankees.jpg\n|caption=Richardson, circa 1964\u201366\n|position=[[Second baseman]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1935|8|19}}\n|birth_place=[[Sumter, South Carolina]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=August 5\n|debutyear=1955\n|debutteam=New York Yankees\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=October 2\n|finalyear=1966\n|finalteam=New York Yankees\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.266\n|stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat2value=34\n|stat3label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value=390\n|teams=\n* [[New York Yankees]] ({{mlby|1955}}\u2013{{mlby|1966}})\n|highlights=\n* 8\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1957 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1957]], [[1959 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (second game)|1959\u00b2]], [[1962 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|1962]]\u2013[[1966 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1966]])\n* 3\u00d7 [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|1958}}, {{wsy|1961}}, {{wsy|1962}})\n* [[World Series MVP]] (1960)\n* 5\u00d7 [[Gold Glove Award]] (1961\u20131965)\n}}\n'''Robert Clinton Richardson, Jr.''' (born August 19, 1935) is an American former professional baseball [[second baseman]]. He played in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) for the [[New York Yankees]] from 1955 through 1966. Batting and throwing right-handed, he formed a top double play combination with fellow Yankee [[infielder]]s [[Clete Boyer]] and [[Tony Kubek]]. In 1962, he led the [[American League]] (AL) in [[Hit (baseball)|hits]] with 209 and snared a [[line drive]] off the bat of [[Willie McCovey]] to win the [[1962 World Series]] for the Yankees. He is the only [[World Series MVP Award|World Series Most Valuable Player]] ever to be selected from the losing team.\n\nBorn in [[Sumter, South Carolina]], Richardson grew up desiring to play for the Yankees after seeing the 1942 film ''[[Pride of the Yankees]]''. Drawing interest from 11 out of 16 MLB teams, he signed with the Yankees and made his debut for them two years later. Earning a regular spot on the roster in 1957, Richardson reached his first [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] that year, though it was not until 1959 that he would become a regular at second base. In 1960, he was named the World Series MVP. Though the Yankees lost the Series in seven games to the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]], Richardson [[Batting average|batted]] .367 with 12 [[runs batted in]] (RBI). He won the next two World Series, ending the 1962 series by catching McCovey's line drive in what ''[[The Sporting News]]'' called baseball's 13th most memorable play. Richardson led the AL in hits that year, with 209.\n\nFrom 1961 to 1965, Richardson won five straight [[Gold Glove Award]]s at second base. He played in the All-Star Game every year from 1962 through 1966. In 1963, he won the [[Lou Gehrig Memorial Award]], and he played in the World Series in 1963 and 1964. His last two years in the major leagues, he had 164 and 153 hits, respectively. Though only 31 after the 1966 season, Richardson retired to spend more time with his family. The Yankees held a special day for him towards the end of the season, making Richardson the 10th Yankee to be so honored.\n\nAfter his playing career, Richardson [[Coach (baseball)|coached]] college teams for several years. He led the [[University of South Carolina]] to its first [[College World Series]] in 1975 and laid the groundwork for their later success. In 1986, he led [[Coastal Carolina University]]'s baseball team to a [[Big South Conference]] championship, and he coached at [[Liberty University]] from 1987 through 1990. Richardson ran for the [[United States House of Representatives]] in [[South Carolina's 5th congressional district]] as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] in 1976 but lost to incumbent [[Kenneth Lamar Holland|Kenneth Holland]]. A [[born-again Christian]], Richardson was involved in many Christian organizations during and after his career. He spoke at the [[White House]] in 1970 as a representative of the [[Fellowship of Christian Athletes]], appeared in five [[Billy Graham Crusade]]s, and frequently speaks at churches and other organizations.\n\n==Early life==\nRichardson was the middle child of Robert Sr. and Debbie Richardson of [[Sumter, South Carolina]]. He had two sisters, Inez (older) and Willie Ann (younger).<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Richardson Marble and Granite Works in Sumter was managed by Robert Sr., who also owned some of the interest in the company.<ref name=\"Richardson's father\">{{cite web|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1963/06/18/80711961.html?pageNumber=37|title=Bobby Richardson's Father, 57|work=The New York Times|date=June 18, 1963|accessdate=April 10, 2020|page=37}}</ref>\n\nEver since seeing ''[[Pride of the Yankees]]'', released in 1942, Richardson had dreamed of playing for the [[New York Yankees]]. Growing up, he practiced his baseball skills with Harry Stokes, a boy in his neighborhood seven years his senior who would play catch with him. Richardson played on a local [[YMCA]]/[[Salvation Army]] team at the age of ten. Later, he played on ballclubs sponsored by the local [[Kiwanis Club]] and [[American Legion]]. On the American Legion team, Richardson's coach was [[Fred Hutchinson]], who would later manage the [[Cincinnati Reds]] when Richardson faced them in the [[1961 World Series]]. Hutchinson and Richardson became American Legion champions in 1952, Richardson's junior year of high school. Hutchinson also coached Richardson at Edmunds High School.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\n11 out of 16 [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) teams showed interest in Richardson, as well as the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] and [[Georgia Tech University]], which offered baseball scholarships. [[Mayo Smith]], manager of the [[Norfolk Tars]], a team in the [[Class B (baseball)|Class B]] [[Piedmont League]] and an affiliate of the [[New York Yankees]], scouted Richardson for New York, as did Bill Harris. Ultimately, Richardson decided to forgo college and sign with the Yankees out of high school (though he later earned a degree in accounting).<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"Sunday Conversation\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===1953-56: Playing in the minor leagues, debuting with the Yankees===\nRichardson started his [[Minor league baseball|minor league]] career in 1953 with the [[Norfolk Tars]] of the [[Class B (baseball)|Class B]] [[Piedmont League]], travelling by bus to Norfolk from Sumter with $85 in coins friends and family had given him.<ref name=\"SABR\">{{cite web|last=Pasculli|first=Len|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/47363efd|title=Bobby Richardson|work=SABR|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> After Richardson [[Batting average|batted]] just .211 in his first 27 games with the Tars, the Yankees assigned him to a [[Class D (baseball)|Class D]] team, the [[Olean Yankees]] of the [[New York\u2013Penn League|PONY League]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"minors\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=richar007rob|title=Bobby Richardson Minor League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> With Olean, he batted .412 in 32 games and hit his first [[home run]].<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\nIn 1954, Richardson was promoted, heading up to the [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] [[Binghamton Triplets]] of the [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] without having to return to Norfolk. Spending the whole year in Binghamton, he ranked among the Eastern League leaders in games (141, tied for first), [[Runs scored|runs]] (81, fifth), 171 [[Hit (baseball)|hits]] (first), [[Double (baseball)|doubles]] (29, second to Clyde Parris's 40), and batting average (.310, second to Parris's .313).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=af825f91|title=1954 Eastern League Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> For his contributions, Richardson was named the Eastern League's [[Most Valuable Player]] (MVP).<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\nRichardson spent most of [[spring training]] with the Yankees in 1955 but was sent to the [[Class AAA (baseball)|Class AAA]] [[Denver Bears]] of the [[American Association (20th Century)|American Assocation]] to start the year.<ref>{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|page=31|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1955/04/01/85690101.html?pageNumber=31|title=Five Players Cut From Squad Before Yanks Start Northward|work=The New York Times|date=April 1, 1955|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> In 119 games with the Bears, he batted .296 with 146 hits, 99 runs scord, 21 doubles, 12 [[Triple (baseball)|triples]], six home runs, and 59 RBI.<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\nWhen [[Gil McDougald]] found himself on the receiving end of a [[line drive]] during [[batting practice]] in August of 1955, the Yankees called up Richardson.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> He debuted on August 5, 1955, getting his first hit against [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Famer]] [[Jim Bunning]] in a 3\u20130 victory over the [[Detroit Tigers]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In the field, he was a \"nervous wreck\" as he later described, but no balls were hit to him.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Bobby Richardson Story|first=Bobby |last=Richardson |location=Old Tappan, New Jersey|publisher=Fleming H. Revell Co.|year=1965|page=84}}</ref> He started four games at second base in three days (including an August 7 [[Doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]]), then entered three games in the late innings at [[shortstop]] before getting sent to the minor leagues on August 15 to make room for a [[pitcher]] returning from the [[disabled list]].<ref name=\"1955 Richardson\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Drebinger|first=John|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1955/08/16/79451253.html?pageNumber=26|title=Home Runs Mark 5\u20134, 12\u20136 Triumphs|work=The New York Times|date=August 16, 1955|accessdate=April 10, 2020|page=26}}</ref> For some reason, he was sent to the [[Richmond Virginians]] of the Class AAA [[International League]] this time, with whom he finished the season.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Called up again in [[September call-up|September]], he appeared in four more games for the Yankees before the end of the year.<ref name=\"1955 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1955|title=Bobby Richardson 1955 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1956, Richardson started the season with the Yankees. However, he only appeared in five games for them, batting .143 before getting sent back to Denver May 13.<ref>{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|page=42|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1956/05/14/93203323.html?pageNumber=42|title=Bombers Win, 11\u20132; Drop 5\u20131 Decision|work=The New York Times|date=May 14, 1956|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> With the Bears, he ranked among the American Association leaders in batting average (.328, third), runs scored (102, sixth), hits (175, fourth), doubles (30, ninth), and triples (12, tied with [[Willie Kirkland]] for second behind [[Larry Raines]]'s 14).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=62cbeec8|title=1956 American Association Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===1957-59: Becoming a full-time player===\nRichardson made the team in 1957 and took over the second base job from [[Billy Martin]], the Yankees' volatile infielder who injured himself in a deliberate golf cart collision with [[Mickey Mantle]] in spring training, then got into a highly-publicized brawl at the [[Copacabana (nightclub)|Copacabana Club]] in May before getting traded to the [[Kansas City Athletics]] in June.<ref name=\"Silence\">{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|page=34|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1957/06/25/84738480.html?pageNumber=34|title=Silence! Bobby Richardson at Work|work=The New York Times|date=June 25, 1957|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Golenbock|first=Peter|origyear=1994|title=Wild, High and Tight: The Life and Death of Billy Martin|publisher=Antenna Books|edition=Kindle version of Antenna Books ebook |page=2631\u20132644 |location=New York|year=2014|isbn=978-1-62306-022-0|ref={{sfnRef|Golenbock}}}}</ref> Richardson proved a quieter sort of character, if not a great hitter in 1957; manager [[Casey Stengel]] said, \"Look at him. He doesn't drink, he doesn't smoke, he doesn't chew, he doesn't stay out late, and he still can't hit .250.\"<ref name=\"SABR\"/> His fielding was better; [[Louis Effrat]] of ''The New York Times'' wrote June 25, \"He has thrilled the fans with his great stops and catches...no one gets rid of the ball quicker [on [[double play]]s].\"<ref name=\"Silence\"/> Actually, Richardson's .331 average trailed only Mantle among the Yankees on June 25,<ref name=\"Silence\"/> and he made his first appearance in the [[1957 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] that year.<ref name=\"reference\"/> However, he batted .188 over the rest of the year, finishing the season with a .256 mark and 78 hits in 305 [[at bat]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1957|title=Bobby Richardson 1957 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy September, Richardson was losing a lot of starts to [[Jerry Coleman]] at second base.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=colemje01&t=b&year=1957|title=Jerry Coleman 1957 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Even so, Stengel waited until the last minute to decide whether Coleman or Richardson would start at second base in the [[1957 World Series]] against the [[Milwaukee Braves]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1957/10/01/91165032.html?pageNumber=54|title=Mantle's Status Remains in Doubt|work=The New York Times|date=October 1, 1957|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Ultimately, Stengel chose Coleman, who started all seven games for the Yankees as Richardson was limited to two appearances as a [[pinch-runner]] and [[defensive replacement]].<ref name=\"reference\"/><ref name=\"Postseason Coleman\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=colemje01&t=b&year=0&post=1|title=Jerry Coleman Postseason Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The Yankees lost the Series in seven games.<ref name=\"Postseason Coleman\"/>\n\nColeman retired following the 1957 season, and Richardson began 1958 as the Yankees' starting second baseman.<ref>{{cite web|last=McGowen|first=Roscoe|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1957/11/22/90856130.html?pageNumber=38|page=38|title=Coleman Retires as Player After Nine Years with Yankees|work=The New York Times|date=November 22, 1957|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> After batting .203 through the Yankees' first 18 games, he missed 20 in a row as McDougald began getting the starts at second.<ref name=\"1958 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1958|title=Bobby Richardson 1958 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=mcdougi01&t=b&year=1958|title=Gil McDougald 1958 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Richardson started at second from June 5 through June 12 but thereafter spent most of the season on the bench until September, when he again got a few starts at second base.<ref name=\"1958 Richardson\"/> In 73 games (182 at bats), he batted .247 with 18 runs scored and 45 hits.<ref name=\"reference\"/> Richardson considered quitting baseball that season because of his struggles, but [[Ralph Houk]], the Yankees' [[General manager (baseball)|general manager]] and Richardson's former manager at Denver, convinced him to keep playing.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In the [[1958 World Series]], again against the Braves, Richardson finished three games for the Yankees at [[third base]] and also started Game 4 at third, though he was hitless in two at bats before getting pinch-hit for in the seventh by [[Elston Howard]].<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=0&post=1|title=Bobby Richardson Postseason Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA195810050.shtml|title=1958 World Series Game 4, Braves at Yankees, October 5|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> However, he became a World Series champion for the first time as this year, the Yankees defeated the Braves in seven games.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/>\n\nRichardson began 1959 as the Yankees' shortstop; Effrat wrote, \"[Richardson] is a tremendous fielder no matter where [the Yankees] play him.\"<ref name=\"Kiely\">{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1959/04/20/89183045.html?pageNumber=37|title=Kiely Is Credited with 5\u20134 Victory|work=The New York Times|page=37|date=April 20, 1959|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> He moved to second base on April 18 after McDougald suffered cracked knuckles, then returned to shortstop on April 29 when McDougald returned to the lineup.<ref name=\"Kiely\"/><ref name=\"1959 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1959|title=Bobby Richardson 1959 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Only batting .232 through the season's first twenty games, he was benched after May 5 in favor of [[Tony Kubek]].<ref name=\"1959 Richardson\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=kubekto01&t=b&year=1959|title=Tony Kubek 1959 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Bill Dickey]], the [[hitting coach]] for the Yankees, worked with Richardson to improve his hitting. In 1959, Richardson switched to a heavier bat and tried swinging harder at pitches.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Given the chance to start at second base again in mid-June, Richardson raised his batting average from .232 to .300 over six games with 11 hits in 18 at bats.<ref name=\"1959 Richardson\"/> He was on the roster for the [[1959 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (second game)|second All-Star Game]] of the year and remained the starting second baseman the rest of the season.<ref name=\"1959 Richardson\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Becker|first=Bill|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1959/08/03/88805148.html?pageNumber=31|title=Walker and Drysdale Expected to Start in Second All-Star Game|work=The New York TImes|page=31|date=August 3, 1959|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> On July 25, 1959, Richardson and [[Fritz Brickell]] both hit their first major league home runs, Richardson's coming against [[Paul Foytack]] in a 9\u20138 victory over the Tigers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1959/07/26/110087361.html?pageNumber=166|page=166|title=Homer Is Decisive|work=The New York Times|date=July 26, 1959|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Batting .298 coming into the final game of the year, Richardson was the only Yankee with a chance at hitting .300. Stengel promised to remove him from the game if he got a hit in his first at bat (moving his batting average to .300). Richardson flew out to [[Albie Pearson]] in his first at bat but got hits in his next two at bats to move his average to .301, then was pinch-hit for in the eighth, preserving the mark.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In 134 games (469 at bats), he had 53 runs scored, 141 hits, 18 doubles, six triples, two home runs (both against Foytack), and 33 RBI.<ref name=\"reference\"/><ref name=\"Shared Hero\">{{cite web|last=Effrat|first=Louis|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1960/10/09/99878556.html?pageNumber=276|page=276|title=Batting in 6 Runs, He Shares Role of Hero With Ford|work=The New York Times|date=October 9, 1960|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> His .301 average topped the Yankees and ranked sixth in the [[American League]] (AL),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1959-batting-leaders.shtml|title=1959 AL Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> and he finished 18th in AL [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player (MVP)]] voting after the season.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===1960-62: Starring in the World Series===\nIn 1960, Richardson remained the Yankees' starting second baseman all season.<ref name=\"1960 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1960|title=Bobby Richardson 1960 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> On April 30, June 30, and July 18, he had a season-high three hits.<ref name=\"1960 Richardson\"/> One of those hits on April 30 was his only home run of the year, against [[Arnie Portocarrero]], in a 16\u20130 victory over the [[Baltimore Orioles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/BAL/BAL196004300.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Baltimore Orioles Box Score, April 30, 1960|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> With the Yankees and Athletics tied 7\u20137 on May 6, Richardson singled against [[Bob Trowbridge]], stole second base, moved to third on a groundout by [[Ryne Duren]], then scored the winning run on a single by McDougald.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196005060.shtml|title=Kansas City Athletics at New York Yankees Box Score, May 6, 1960|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Batting .208 through June 17, he hit .370 from June 18 through July 23, raising his season average to .273. Thereafter, he batted .215 to finish the year with a .252 mark.<ref name=\"1960 Richardson\"/> In 150 games (460 at bats), he had 45 runs scored, 116 hits, 12 doubles, three triples, and 26 RBI.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nThe Yankees faced the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] in the [[1960 World Series]]. Richardson went hitless in Game 1 but contributed three in Game 2, scoring three runs as well as the Yankees won 16\u20133.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/> In Game 3, he came to bat in the first inning with the bases loaded against [[Clem Labine]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Terrell|first=Roy|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1960/10/17/the-knife-and-the-hammer|title=The Knife and the Hammer|work=Sports Illustrated|date=October 17, 1960|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Third base coach [[Frank Crosetti]] signaled him to [[Bunt (baseball)|bunt]], but after running the count to two strikes, Richardson cancelled the plan.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>{{efn|A bunt that goes [[Foul ball|foul]] with two strikes is considered the third strike to complete the strikeout.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.closecallsports.com/2013/07/case-play-2013-06-foul-bunt-with-two.html|title=Case Play 2013-06:Foul Bunt with Two Strikes (Completed)|date=10 July 2013|accessdate=28 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029021300/http://www.closecallsports.com/2013/07/case-play-2013-06-foul-bunt-with-two.html|archivedate=29 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>}} He remained at the plate long enough to run the at bat to a [[full count]], then hit a [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] to put the Yankees ahead 6\u20130. Up to bat with the bases loaded again in the fourth inning, he had a two-RBI single against [[Red Witt]]. His six RBI set a new record for most in a single World Series game.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In Game 4, he had two hits and drove in another run, but the Yankees lost this one 3\u20132.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/> After going hitless in Game 5, he hit two triples in Game 6, drove in three runs, and scored one in the Yankees' 12\u20130 rout of the Pirates to force Game 7.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/> He scored a run in the sixth inning, led off the ninth with a single against [[Harvey Haddix]], and scored another run, but New York lost the game 10\u20139.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/PIT/PIT196010130.shtml|title=1960 World Series Game 7, Yankees at Pirates, October 13|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Though Pittsburgh second baseman [[Bill Mazeroski]] hit a [[walk-off home run]] in the bottom of the ninth to win the Series for Pittsburgh,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com/mlb/story/world-series-history-bill-mazeroski-s-home-run-to-win-1960-world-series-100616|title=World Series History: Bill Mazeroski\u2019s Home Run to Win 1960 World Series|work=Fox Sports|date=June 30, 2017|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> it was Richardson who would be named the [[World Series Most Valuable Player Award|World Series MVP]] after hitting .367 with 12 RBI.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/> He is the only World Series MVP who was playing for the losing team when he won the award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://baseball-almanac.com/awards/aw_mvpw.shtml|title=World Series Most Valuable Player Award|work=Baseball Almanac|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Sport Magazine gave him a new Corvette for his efforts.<ref name=\"Sunday Conversation\">{{cite web|last=Glover|first=Emery|url=https://thetandd.com/sports/t-d-sunday-conversation-with-bobby-richardson/article_378fc5f2-52ab-11e0-815b-001cc4c03286.html|title=T&D Sunday Conversation with...Bobby Richardson|work=The Times & Democrat|date=March 20, 2011|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Since he had a growing family, Richardson traded the car for a Jeep. His son was very disappointed he decided to do that<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\nHouk took over from Stengel as the Yankee manager in 1961; he inserted Richardson either first or second into the [[Batting order (baseball)|batting order]] each game.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> On June 15, he had three hits and four RBI, including a three-run home run against [[Johnny Antonelli]] as the Yankees beat the [[Cleveland Indians]] 11\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|page=54|last=Drebinger|first=John|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1961/06/15/issue.html|title=Yankees Crush Indians|work=The New York Times|date=June 15, 1961|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> He had four RBI again in the second game of a doubleheader on July 9, including a three-run home run against [[Don Schwall]], but the Yankees lost that game 9\u20136 to the [[Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196107092.shtml|title=Boston Red Sox at New York Yankees Box Score, July 9, 1961|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> On August 17, he had three hits and scored three runs in a 5\u20133 victory over the [[Chicago White Sox]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196108170.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at New York Yankees Box Score, August 17, 1961|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> The Yankees lost 6\u20134 to the [[Los Angeles Angels]] on August 26, but Richardson had five hits in the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/LAA/LAA196108240.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Los Angeles Angels Box Score, August 24, 1961|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> Playing all 162 games for the Yankees, Richardson batted .261 with 80 runs scored, 17 doubles, five triples, three home runs, and 49 RBI.<ref name=\"reference\"/> His 662 at bats were third in the AL (behind [[Brooks Robinson]]'s 668 and [[Jake Wood (baseball)|Jake Wood]]'s 663), and his 173 hits were fifth in the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1961-batting-leaders.shtml|title=1961 AL Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2010}}</ref> Defensively, he led the AL with 413 [[putout]]s and 136 double plays assisted in.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Richardson finished 24th in MVP voting and won the [[List of Gold Glove Award winners at second base|Gold Glove at second base]], the first of five straight he would win at the position.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nRichardson had no RBI in the [[1961 World Series]] against the [[Cincinnati Reds]] but did bat .391, with nine hits in 23 at bats. He had three hits apiece in Games 1 and 4.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/> In Game 4, he led off the seventh inning with a single against [[Jim Brosnan]], advanced to second when [[Vada Pinson]] misplayed the ball, moved to third base on a [[wild pitch]] by Brosnan, and scored on a single by [[H\u00e9ctor L\u00f3pez]] as the Yankees won 7\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CIN/CIN196110080.shtml|title=1961 World Series Game 4, Yankees at Reds, October 8|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> The Yankees defeated the Reds in five games, making Richardson a World Series champion for the second time.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/>\n\nOn June 9, 1962, against the Orioles, Richardson had four hits, including a two-run home run against [[Steve Barber]] that tied the game at two in the seventh; the Yankees went on to win 7\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196206090.shtml|title=Baltimore Orioles at New York Yankees Box Score, June 9, 1962|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> He was selected to both of the All-Star Games in 1962.<ref name=\"reference\"/> With the Yankees trailing the [[Minnesota Twins]] 7\u20134 in the ninth inning on August 16, 1962, at [[Metropolitan Stadium]], Richardson came up to the plate with the bases loaded. Before the at bat, Mantle told him, \"See if you can hit one out. I'm not feeling too good today.\"<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Richardson hit a home run to left field against [[Dick Stigman]], the only grand slam of his career besides his one in the 1960 World Series. Though the hit put the Yankees ahead 8\u20137, they would lose the lead in the bottom of the ninth and lose in [[extra innings]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Two days later, he had three hits and two runs scored, including a three-run home run against [[Orlando Pe\u00f1a]] in an 11\u20137 victory over the Athletics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/KC1/KC1196208182.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Kansas City Athletics Box Score, August 18, 1962|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> Against the [[Washington Senators (1960-1971)|Washington Senators]] on September 19, he had four hits, two runs scored, and an RBI in an 8\u20135 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/WS2/WS2196209190.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Washington Senators Box Score, September 19, 1962|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> The [[Society for American Baseball Research]] called 1962 his most productive year, as he batted .302 with eight home runs, 59 RBI, and 11 stolen bases in 161 games.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"reference\"/> He led the AL in hits (209) and at bats (692). Richardson also ranked among the league leaders in runs scored (99, tied for fourth with [[Carl Yastrzemski]]), batting average (.302, seventh), and doubles (38, fourth).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1962-batting-leaders.shtml|title=1962 AL Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> He finished second to Mantle in AL MVP voting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/awards_1962.shtml|title=1962 Awards Voting|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Yankees faced the [[San Francisco Giants]] in the [[1962 World Series]]. Richardson batted a mere .148 in this Series,<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/> though he did have two hits and two runs scored in the Yankees' 5\u20133 triumph of Game 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196210100.shtml|title=1962 World Series Game 5, Giants at Yankees, October 10|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>  However, his glove would provide one of the most famous memories of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/25138329/willie-mccovey-san-francisco-giants-legend-dies-80|title=Willie McCovey, Hall of Famer and Giants legend, dies at age 80|work=ESPN|date=October 31, 2018|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> In Game 7, the Yankees had the only run of the game going into the bottom of the ninth inning, needing three outs to win the series. [[Matty Alou]] led off with a single, however, and after two strikeouts, Mays doubled to put the tying run (Alou) at third with future Hall of Famer [[Willie McCovey]] coming to bat. If Mays scored, the Giants would win the series.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> McCovey hit a screaming line drive up the middle which likely would have scored both runs had it made it out of the infield. Hardly moving from his position, Richardson snared the ball for the third out, winning the Series for the Yankees.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> \"People often suggest that I was out of position on that play,\" Richardson remembered later. \"But McCovey hit two hard ground balls to me earlier in the Series, so I played where I thought he would hit the ball.\"<ref name=\"SABR\"/> McCovey still had bad memories of it years later. \"I broke in with a 4-for-4 my rookie year against a Hall of Fame pitcher, [[Robin Roberts]],\" he recalled. \"I hit more grand slams [18] than anybody in [[National League]] history. I hit more home runs [521] than any lefthanded hitter in the National League. But that out is what many people remember about me....I would rather be remembered as the guy who hit the ball six inches over Bobby Richardson's head.\"<ref name=\"SABR\"/> ''Sporting News'' ranked the catch the 13th most memorable moment in baseball history,<ref name=\"SABR\"/> and [[Charles Schulz]] famously referenced it in a ''[[Peanuts]]'' comic strip, where [[Charlie Brown]] yells, \"Why couldn\u2019t McCovey have hit the ball just three feet higher?\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Bush|first=Frederick C.|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/charlie-brown|title=Charlie Brown|work=SABR|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===1963-66: Extending his streaks===\n[[File:Bobby Richardson 1963.JPG|thumb|left|180px|Richardson in 1963.]]\nOn April 23, 1963, Richardson had three hits, two RBI, and two runs scored in a 7\u20136 victory over the Senators.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/WS2/WS2196304210.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Washington Senators Box Score, April 21, 1963|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> During the season, his father suffered a stroke in May, then died on July 17. Richardson missed 11 games during the year visiting him and helping get his affairs in order.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"Richardson's father\"/> He had a season high of four hits in a game twice in quick succession, on July 4 in the first game of a doubleheader and on July 6.<ref name=\"1963 Richardson\"/> He again represented the Yankees in the [[1963 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]].<ref name=\"reference\"/> On September 5, he singled against [[Steve Ridzik]], stole second base, and scored on a [[Roger Maris]] hit due to an error by shortstop [[Ed Brinkman]] to tie a game with the Senators at 2 in the sixth inning. The Yankees went on to win 3\u20132 in 12 innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196309050.shtml|title=Washington Senators at New York Yankees Box Score, September 5, 1963|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> After setting a career high with eight home runs the year before, Richardson hit three in 1963, all in Yankee losses.<ref name=\"1963 Richardson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=richabo01&t=b&year=1963|title=Bobby Richardson 1963 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref> In 151 games, Richardson batted .265 with 72 runs scored and 48 RBI.<ref name=\"reference\"/> He led the league in at bats (630) for the second year in a row, finished seventh with 167 hits and tied three other players for seventh with 15 stolen bases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1963-batting-leaders.shtml|title=1963 AL Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Richardson again garnered AL MVP votes, finishing tenth this time.<ref name=\"reference\"/> He won the [[Lou Gehrig Memorial Award]], given by Gehrig's [[Columbia University]] fraternity to the [[Major League Baseball|major leaguer]] who best demonstrates Gehrig's character.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\nIn Game 1 of the [[1963 World Series]], which the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] swept in four games, Richardson struck out three times against [[Sandy Koufax]]\u2014his only three-strikeout game in 1,448 regular-season/World Series games.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=richabo01|title=Bobby Richardson Stats|work=Baseball Almanac|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> (Koufax would finish with 15 strikeouts, then a World Series single-game record.) Just that regular season, Richardson had struck out only 22 times in 630 at-bats.<ref name=\"reference\"/> He had a mere three hits in the World Series but played each game; Richardson had now played in 23 straight World Series games dating back to 1960.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/>\n\nOn May 10, 1964, Richardson had five hits and scored three runs in a 12\u20132 victory over the Indians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE196405101.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Cleveland Indians Box Score, May 10, 1964|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Less than a month later, he had five hits on June 4 in a 9\u20137 victory over the Twins.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/MIN/MIN196406040.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Minnesota Twins Box Score, June 4, 1964|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He picked up his 1,000th hit on June 12 with a [[line drive]] to left field against [[Frank Baumann (baseball)|Frank Baumann]] in a 6\u20131 victory over the White Sox in the first game of a doubleheader. The hit had proved difficult to come by for Richardson, who had put the ball in play seven times in his last two games without reaching base safely.<ref>{{cite web|last=Durso|first=Joseph|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1964/06/13/97397828.html?pageNumber=16|title=Yanks Beat White Sox 6\u20131 |work=The New York Times|page=16|date=June 13, 1964|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Once again, he was selected to the [[1964 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]].<ref name=\"reference\"/> In the first game of a doubleheader on July 26, he had three hits, including a two-RBI single against [[Mickey Lolich]] and a solo home run against [[Terry Fox (baseball)|Terry Fox]] in an 11\u20136 victory over the Tigers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/DET/DET196407261.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Detroit Tigers Box Score, July 26, 1964|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> In 159 games, he batted .267 with four home runs, 50 RBI, and 11 stolen bases.<ref name=\"reference\"/> For the third year in the row, he led the AL in at bats with 679. He also led the league with 148 singles, ranked third in the league with 181 hits (behind [[Tony Oliva]]'s 217 and B. Robinson's 294), and tied [[Bob Allison]] for ninth in the AL with 90 runs scored.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1964-batting-leaders.shtml|title=1964 AL Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He finished 17th in AL MVP voting after the season.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nIn the [[1964 World Series|World Series]] against the [[St. Louis Cardinals]], Richardson set a World Series record with 13 hits; this record has since been tied by [[Lou Brock]] and [[Marty Barrett (second baseman)|Marty Barrett]] in the [[1968 World Series|1968]] and [[1986 World Series]], respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-almanac.com/rb_ws3.shtml|title=World Series Hitting Records|work=Baseball Almanac|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> However, batting against Cardinal ace [[Bob Gibson]] with the Yankees trailing 7\u20135 in the ninth inning of Game 7, he popped out to [[Dal Maxvill]] for the final out of the Series. Richardson also had the dubious distinction of committing errors that affected the outcome of two games in the Series. In the sixth inning of Game 4, he mishandled [[Dick Groat]]'s ground ball for a double play that would have ended the inning with no runs scoring; the error was followed one batter later by [[Ken Boyer]]'s grand slam\u2014the four runs the Cardinals needed in defeating the Yankees 4\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196410110.shtml|title=1964 World Series Game 4, Cardinals at Yankees, October 11|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> In the fifth inning of Game 5, he bobbled [[Curt Flood]]'s double play ground ball, which also would have ended that inning without any damage. The Cardinals eventually scored twice in the inning, then won the game 5\u20132 on [[Tim McCarver]]'s 10th inning, three-run home run.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196410120.shtml|title=1964 World Series Game 5, Cardinals at Yankees, October 12|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> This was Richardson's final (of seven) World Series; he played all 30 World Series games from 1960 through 1964.<ref name=\"Postseason Richardson\"/>\n\nOn May 24, 1965, he had three hits, drove in two runs, and scored two more times in a 15\u20135 victory over Cleveland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196505240.shtml|title=Cleveland Indians at New York Yankees Box Score, May 24, 1965|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> After hitting into a [[fielder's choice]] on June 15, Richardson stole second base, then scored on a Maris single to put the Yankees up 1\u20130; however, the Yankees would lose the game 2\u20131 in the 10th inning.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196506150.shtml|title=Baltimore Orioles at New York Yankees Box Score, June 15, 1965|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He was selected to the [[1965 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] once again.<ref name=\"reference\"/> On July 17, he had four hits and scored twice in a 5\u20134 victory over Washington.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196507170.shtml|title=Washington Senators at New York Yankees Box Score, July 17, 1965|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Five days later, his home run against [[Gary Peters]] put the Yankees ahead to stay in a 2\u20131 victory over the White Sox.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196507220.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at New York Yankees Box Score, July 22, 1965|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> On August 8, [[Ray Barker (baseball)|Ray Barker]] and Richardson hit back-to-back home runs against [[Denny McLain]] in a 6\u20135 victory over the Tigers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/DET/DET196508080.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Detroit Tigers Box Score, August 8, 1965|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> In 160 games, Richardson batted .247 with 76 runs scored, 164 hits, 28 doubles, six home runs, and 47 RBI.<ref name=\"reference\"/> He finished 20th in AL MVP voting.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nRichardson had three hits and scored three times on May 25 in an 11\u20136 victory over the Angels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NYA/NYA196605250.shtml|title=California Angels at New York Yankees Box Score, May 25, 1966|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He hit a three-run double against [[Tommy John]] on June 2 to turn a 3\u20132 deficit into a 5\u20133 lead for the Yankees, who defeated the White Sox.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA196606020.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Chicago White Sox Box Score, June 2, 1966|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Five days later, he had three hits, three runs scored, and three RBI, including a home run against [[John O'Donoghue (1960s pitcher)|John O'Donoghue]] in a 7\u20132 victory over the Indians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE196606070.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Cleveland Indians Box Score, June 7, 1966|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> On June 29, he had five hits, one of which was a home run against [[Rollie Sheldon]] and was followed by two more by Mantle and [[Joe Pepitone]] in a 6\u20135 victory over the Red Sox.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/BOS/BOS196606290.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Boston Red Sox Box Score, June 29, 1966|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Richardson made the [[1966 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] for the fifth year in a row, his seventh and final selection.<ref name=\"reference\"/> He had four hits on August 15, including a home run against Lolich, as the Yankees defeated the Tigers 6\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/DET/DET196608150.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Detroit Tigers Box Score, August 15, 1966|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> On September 11, he hit his last major league home run against [[John Wyatt (baseball)|John Wyatt]] in the 10th inning of a 4\u20132 victory over the Red Sox.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> He played in his final game on October 2, recording a hit and an RBI in a 2\u20130 victory over the White Sox.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In 149 games, he batted .251 with 71 runs scored, 153 hits, 21 doubles, seven home runs, and 42 RBI.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nThough he was just 31 following the 1966 season, Richardson retired following the year. He had decided to retire after the 1965 season, but the Yankees convinced him to play one more season since Kubek had to retire due to injuries after the 1965 campaign.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> \u201cI wanted to take the kids to school, help them with homework and watch or help coach their teams,\u201d he explained.<ref name=\"Baptist Courier\"/> The Yankees honored him by declaring September 17 \"Bobby Richardson Day,\" making Richardson the tenth Yankee to be honored at the stadium with a special day. \u201cHow lucky it has been for me to have been a Yankee. To God be the glory,\" he addressed the fans.<ref name=\"Baptist Courier\"/>\n\n===Legacy===\nRichardson racked up 1,432 hits in his career, with a lifetime batting average of .266, 34 home runs and 390 RBIs. Over his 12-year major league career, he scored 643 runs and stole 73 stolen bases. He also had 196 doubles and 37 triples. Defensively, he had an all-time [[fielding percentage]] of .979 at second base, and six seasons with 100 or more double plays turned.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nFrom 1961 to 1965, Richardson won five straight Gold Gloves at second base (not until [[Robinson Can\u00f3]] in 2010 would another Yankee second baseman win a Gold Glove)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-almanac.com/awards/aw_gg2b.shtml|title=Gold Glove Second Basemen|work=Baseball Almanac|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> while forming a top double play combination with shortstop and roommate Kubek. With the light-hitting but superb-fielding Yankee [[third baseman]] [[Clete Boyer]], Richardson and Kubek gave the Yankees arguably the best defensive infield in baseball in the early 1960s.<ref>{{cite web|last=Madden|first=Bill|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/clete-boyer-yanks-3rd-man-article-1.221914|title=Clete Boyer, Yanks' 3rd man|work=The New York Daily News|date=June 5, 2007|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Walker|first=Ben|agency=Associated Press|url=http://archive.boston.com/news/globe/obituaries/articles/2007/06/05/clete_boyer_at_70_3d_baseman_for_yanks_was_brilliant_fielder/|title=Clete Boyer, at 70; 3d baseman for Yanks was brilliant fielder|work=boston.com|date=June 5, 2007|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRichardson was also known for his ability to [[Contact hitter|make contact]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hoch|first=Bryan|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/best-second-basemen-in-yankees-history|title=Yankees' Top 5 second basemen: Hoch's take|work=MLB.com|date=April 6, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He struck out just 243 times, less than 5% of his [[plate appearance]]s.<ref name=\"reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/richabo01.shtml|title=Bobby Richardson Stats|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> A leadoff hitter who rarely missed a game, Richardson led the league in at bats three times.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"reference\"/> Following Martin's trade, he wore the uniform number 1 for the majority of his career (1958\u20131966).<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"reference\"/> He led the league in at bats per strikeout three times during his career, 1964\u20131966.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/at_bats_per_strikeout_leagues.shtml|title=Yearly League Leaders & Records for AB per SO|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> A skilled bunter, he led the league in [[sacrifice bunt|sacrifice hits]] in 1962 and 1964.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===Coaching===\nIn the late 1960s, [[Paul Dietzel]] asked Richardson if he would become the head baseball coach for the [[South Carolina Gamecocks|University of South Carolina Gamecocks]]. Richardson told him no twice, as he was under a personal services contract with the Yankees. However, after Dietzel asked him a third time, Richardson secured permission from the Yankees to take the job, assuming the role in 1970.<ref name=\"The Item\">{{cite web|last=Brunson|first=Dennis|url=https://www.theitem.com/stories/the-sumter-items-top-125-sports-figures-no-1-bobby-richardson,338621|title=The Sumter Item's Top 125 Sports Figures: No. 1 - Bobby Richardson|work=The Sumter Item|date=December 26, 2019|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He would often pitch batting practice and drive the team bus for events. Richardson also tried to perform recruiting for the school but delegated the responsibility to others after he figured out \"I wasn't going after the good players.\"<ref name=\"finah\">{{cite web|last=Keith|first=Larry|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1975/06/02/nothin-could-be-finah|title=Nothin', could be finah|work=Sports Illustrated|date=June 2, 1975|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Under Richardson, Larry Keith of ''Sports Illustrated'' wrote, \"South Carolina rarely bunts, often hits-and-runs and is always looking for the big inning.\"<ref name=\"finah\"/> Richardson led the Gamecocks to their first [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) Tournament appearance in 1974, which set the stage for what would happen a year later in 1975 when South Carolina posted a 51\u20136\u20131 record and made the [[1975 College World Series|College World Series]] for the first time ever.  They advanced all the way to the national championship game against Texas before losing 5\u20131 to the Longhorns. Richardson left South Carolina after the 1976 season, finishing his tenure with a 221\u201392\u20131 record and three NCAA Tournament appearances.<ref name=\"The Item\"/>  Dennis Brunson of ''The Item'' said of Richardson's contributions, \"Richardson had laid the groundwork for a program that would participate in the regionals in nine of the first 13 years under [new head coach [June] Raines and would play in the CWS four times.\"<ref name=\"The Item\"/> In the 1980s, Richardson served as the baseball coach for two seasons (1985\u201386) at [[Coastal Carolina University]] in [[Conway, South Carolina]], where he compiled a record of (61\u201338) and led the team to the [[Big South Conference]] championship in 1968.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://goccusports.com/story.aspx?filename=Baseball_Hosts_IMIChotels_com_INN_vitational_This_Weekend&file_date=2/15/2006|title=Baseball Hosts IMIChotels.com INN-vitational This Weekend|work=goccusports.com|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=February 15, 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420231139/https://goccusports.com/story.aspx?filename=Baseball_Hosts_IMIChotels_com_INN_vitational_This_Weekend&file_date=2%2F15%2F2006|archivedate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> After the 1986 season, he resigned as head coach at Coastal Carolina to replace [[Al Worthington]] as the baseball coach at [[Liberty University]]. \"I came here as athletic director under a different administration and [Chancellor] Ron [Eaglin] felt I should resign as athletic director and focus on baseball,\" Richardson explained the decision to resign, with Eaglin saying the two had disagreed on a budget for the next season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/10/sports/sports-people-richardson-moves-on.html?searchResultPosition=5|title=Sports People; Richardson Moves On|work=The New York Times|page=D-31|date=April 10, 1986|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Worthington, who had become Liberty's athletic director, served as pitching coach under Richardson, who coached the Flames for the next four seasons before retiring in 1990.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Jacobs|first=Barry|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/03/21/sports/building-from-the-ground-up-falwell-sees-liberty-as-an-athletic-powerhouse.html|title=Building From the Ground Up; Falwell Sees Liberty as an Athletic Powerhouse|work=The New York Times|page=B9|date=March 21, 1989|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==1976 political campaign==\nIn 1974, Nixon tried to convince Richardson to run as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] for the [[United States House of Representatives]] in [[South Carolina's 5th congressional district]]. Later, a private poll indicated he would have been the favorite had he run.<ref name=\"finah\"/> Two years later, President [[Gerald Ford]] succeeded in convincing Richardson to resign from his coaching position at the University of South Carolina to run for the seat.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"The Item\"/> Richardson lost to incumbent [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Kenneth Lamar Holland|Kenneth Holland]] by a narrow margin. Holland was aided by the strength of [[Jimmy Carter]]'s winning campaign in South Carolina to hold off Richardson by a tally of 66,073 (51.4%) to 62,095 (48.3%). His campaign was supported by former baseball players [[Joe DiMaggio]], [[Ted Williams]], [[Bob Feller]], and [[Wilmer Mizell|Wilmer \"Vinegar Bend\" Mizell]] among others, though former roommate Kubek declined to campaign for him because Kubek was a Democrat.<ref>{{cite book |title=October 1964 |last= Halberstam |first=David |authorlink= |year=1995 |publisher=Random House Digital, Inc. |location= |isbn= 0-449-98367-6 |pages=366\u2013367 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sZ7sUkp5eBcC&lpg=PP1&dq=october%201964&pg=PA366#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBetsy Dobson, Richardson's future spouse, met him at Grace Baptist Church of Sumter.<ref name=\"Baptist Courier\">{{cite web|last=Gray|first=Rudy|url=https://baptistcourier.com/2016/07/christian-faith-marks-yankee-legend-bobby-richardsons-career-home-life/|title=Christian faith marks Yankee legend Bobby Richardson\u2019s career, home life|work=Baptist Courier|date=July 5, 2016|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> In 1954, they went to a [[miniature golf]] course on their first date. Two years later, they were married. In an unusual move, Houk granted Richardson permission to leave the Denver Bears midseason to get married.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> The couple had three sons\u2013Robbie (born 7/2/57), Ron (7/13/58), and Rich (8/27/68)\u2013and two daughters\u2013Christie (12/30/60) and Jeannie (1/21/64).<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In 1960, the Richardsons were renting a house in [[Ridgewood, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/> They lived Sumter during offseasons, where Richardson was a general secretary for the local [[Young Men's Christian Association]] and host for a radio sports show.<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/> Hunting is one of his favorite hobbies.<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/> He and teammate [[Bobby Shantz]] went gun shopping together in Kansas City in 1959,<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/> and fellow major-leaguer [[Billy O'Dell]] used to hunt with him in the offseason.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> His roommates when travelling with the Yankees at various times included Kubek and Shantz.<ref name=\"Shared Hero\"/>\n\nRichardson is a [[born-again Christian]]. During his time with the Yankees, he would organize church services for the team when they were travelling. Friend and teammate [[Mickey Mantle]] described him as a \"clean-living, practicing Christian.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Mantle|first=Mickey|title=The Mick|location=New York|publisher=Jove Books|year=1985|page=220|isbn=978-0385194563}}</ref> He was involved with the [[Fellowship of Christian Athletes]] (FCA) and the [[American Tract Society]] (ATS) during his career, as well as many charities.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> After his career, he continued to be involved with those organizations. He served as the president of the Baseball Chapel for 10 years, served on the President's Council for Physical Fitness, and earned the Golden Gavel Award from [[Toastmasters International]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/> President [[Richard Nixon]], who hosted church services at the [[White House]] each week of his presidency, invited the FCA to speak on October 18, 1970. One of four representatives, Richardson spoke on [[Jesus and the rich young man]] from [[Gospel of Mark|Mark]], Chapter 10. Concerning the young man's search for guidance, Richardson said, \"He didn't go to India and ask a guru; he didn't get caught up in the younger generation, but he went to God's son, Jesus Christ, the Messiah, with his question.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|last=Fiske|first=Edward B.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/08/08/archives/praying-with-the-president-in-the-white-house-praying-with-the.html|page=SM-14|title=Praying With the President In the White House|work=The New York Times|date=August 8, 1971|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> He has spoken at five [[Billy Graham Crusade]]s, as well as at various churches.<ref name=\"Baptist Courier\"/> Today, he is a speaker with Christian Speakers 360, available to appear at events.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianspeakers360.com/speaker/bobby-richardson.php|title=Bobby Richardson Speaker Information|work=Christian Speakers 360|accessdate=April 16, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813113113/http://www.christianspeakers360.com/speaker/bobby-richardson.php|archivedate=August 13, 2016}}</ref> Several of his Yankee teammates requested that he preside at their funerals, most notably Mickey Mantle. Speaking to an audience of 2,000 (plus television viewers) at Mantle's interment, Richardson said there were two types of people in this world, those who said yes to Christ and those who said no. Shortly before Mantle's death, as Richardson had visited Mantle in a Dallas hospital, Mantle had told Richardson that he had become a Christian.<ref name=\"The Item\"/>\n\nIn 1965, Richardson released his autobiography, ''The Bobby Richardson Story''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Richardson|first1=Bobby|title=The Bobby Richardson Story|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17332889-the-bobby-richardson-story|website=Goodreads|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The story became a movie in 1968.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1968/04/24/77085708.html?pageNumber=35|title=Bobby Richardson Film To Be Shown Saturday|work=The New York Times|page=35|date=April 24, 1968|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Excerpts from the film's audio track were available on an [[LP record]] titled: ''The Bobby Richardson Story: The Exciting First-Person Account of His Own Life, By the Yankees' Famous Second Baseman''.<ref>{{cite AV media|people=Richardson, Bobby (author and narrator)|date=1968|title=The Bobby Richardson Story: The Exciting First-Person Account of His Own Life, By the Yankees' Famous Second Baseman|medium=LP record|location=Waco, TX|publisher=Word Records Inc.}}</ref> He released a new autobiography in 2012 called ''Impact Player''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Freeze|first=Trevor|url=https://billygraham.org/story/bobby-richardson-leaving-a-legacy/|title=Bobby Richardson Leaving a Legacy|work=Billy Graham Evangelistic Association|date=January 9, 2012|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Major League Baseball players who spent their entire career with one franchise]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Baseballstats|mlb=121161|espn=26747|br=r/richabo01|fangraphs=1010903|brm=richar007rob}}\n\n{{1958 New York Yankees}}\n{{1961 New York Yankees}}\n{{1962 New York Yankees}}\n{{World Series MVPs}}\n{{Lou Gehrig Memorial Award}}\n{{AL 2B Gold Glove Award}}\n{{South Carolina Gamecocks head baseball coaches}}\n{{Liberty Flames baseball coach navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richardson, Bobby}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball second basemen]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees players]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees scouts]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Gold Glove Award winners]]\n[[Category:Olean Yankees players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Fellowship of Christian Athletes]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Republicans]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Gamecocks baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Liberty Flames baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Coastal Carolina Chanticleers baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:American athlete-politicians]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sumter, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:World Series Most Valuable Player Award winners]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toRobin Roberts(link changed toRobin Roberts (baseball)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bobby_Richardson"}
{"title_page": "Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Vietnamese name|Ho\u00e0ng|Hoang|Th\u00e1i}}\n{{Infobox Minister\n|name          = <big>'''Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i'''</big><br><small>'''Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Xi\u00eam'''</small>\n|office        = 1st Chairman of the [[Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism (Vietnam)|Committee of Physical Training and Sports of Vietnam]]\n|president     = [[H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh]]\n|primeminister = [[Ph\u1ea1m V\u0103n \u0110\u1ed3ng]]\n|term_start    = 1960\n|term_end      = 1965\n|predecessor   = None\n|successor     = [[H\u00e0 Quang D\u1ef1]]\n|office1       = Deputy Minister of [[Ministry of Defence (Vietnam)|Ministry of Defence]]\n|president1    = [[T\u00f4n \u0110\u1ee9c Th\u1eafng]]<br>[[Tr\u01b0\u1eddng Chinh]]\n|minister1     = [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]]<br>[[V\u0103n Ti\u1ebfn D\u0169ng]]\n|term_start1   = 1974\n|term_end1     = 1986\n|predecessor1  =\n|successor1    =\n|office2       = 1st [[General Staff of the Vietnam People's Army#List of Chiefs of General Staff|Chief of General Staff]]\n|president2    = [[H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh]]\n|term_start2   = 7 September 1945\n|term_end2     = 1953\n|predecessor2  = None\n|successor2    = [[V\u0103n Ti\u1ebfn D\u0169ng]]\n|term_start3   = 1954\n|term_end3     = 1954\n|predecessor3  = [[V\u0103n Ti\u1ebfn D\u0169ng]]\n|successor3    = [[V\u0103n Ti\u1ebfn D\u0169ng]]\n|term_start4   = 1975\n|term_end4     = 1975 (acting)\n|office5       = Commander of the [[People's Liberation Armed Forces of South Vietnam|PLAF]]\n|predecessor5  = [[Tr\u1ea7n V\u0103n Tr\u00e0]]\n|successor5    = [[Tr\u1ea7n V\u0103n Tr\u00e0]]\n|term_start5   = 1967\n|term_end5     = 1973\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1915|5|1|df=y}}\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1986|7|2|1915|5|1|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = An Khang, [[Ti\u1ec1n H\u1ea3i]], [[Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province]], [[French Indochina]]\n|death_place   = [[108 Hospital]], [[Hanoi]], [[Vietnam]]\n|allegiance    = {{flagdeco|North Vietnam|1945}} [[Vi\u1ec7t Minh]]<br>{{flag|Vietnam}}\n|branch        = {{flagicon image|Flag of the People's Army of Vietnam.svg}} [[Vietnam People's Army]]<br>{{flagicon image|FNL Flag.svg}} [[Viet Cong]]\n|image         = \u0110\u1ea1i t\u01b0\u1edbng Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i.jpg\n|caption       = Portrait of General ''Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i'' (1986)\n|nickname      = Qu\u1ed1c B\u00ecnh (1941\u20131944 in China)<br>M\u01b0\u1eddi Khang (1965\u20131973 as Viet Cong commander)<br>Th\u00e0nh\n|serviceyears  = 1941\u201386\n|rank          = [[File:Vietnam People's Army General.jpg|20px]] [[General officer|General]]\n|commands      = [[Vi\u1ec7t Minh]]<br />[[Vietnam People's Army]]<br>[[People's Liberation Armed Forces]]\n|battles       = [[First Indochina War]]<br />[[Battle of Dien Bien Phu|Battle of \u0110i\u1ec7n Bi\u00ean Ph\u1ee7]]<br>[[Vietnam War]]<br>[[Tet Offensive|T\u1ebft Offensive]]\n|awards=[[File:Vietnam Gold Star ribbon.png|30px]] [[Gold Star Order (Vietnam)|Gold Star Order]] (posthumously)<br><br />See [[Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i#Vietnam Orders and Decorations|full list below]] for details of orders and commemorative medals awarded\n|spouse        = {{plainlist|\n* {{marriage|L\u01b0\u01a1ng Th\u1ecb Thanh B\u00ecnh<br>|1939|1986|end=his death}}\n* {{marriage|[[\u0110\u00e0m Th\u1ecb Loan]]<br>|1945|1986|end=his death}}\n}}\n|signature=\n}}\n\n'''Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i''' (1 May 1915 \u2013 2 July 1986), born '''Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Xi\u00eam''', was a Vietnamese Army General and a communist political figure. His hometown was T\u00e2y An, [[Ti\u1ec1n H\u1ea3i District]], [[Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province]].<ref>Ronald B. Frankum Jr. ''Historical Dictionary of the War in Vietnam'', 2011 p.207. \"Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i\"</ref>  During the [[Tet Offensive|T\u1ebft Offensive]], he was the highest senior North Vietnamese officer in South Vietnam.<ref name=\"Ford p. 87\">{{Harvnb|Ford|1995|p=87}}</ref> He was [[General Staff of the Vietnam People's Army#List of Chiefs of General Staff|the first chief of staff of the Vietnam People's Army]], and was responsible for key military forces in North Vietnam.<ref>{{cite web\n| author = AP\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1986/07/05/obituaries/hoang-van-thai-71-a-vietnamese-general.html\n| title = Hoang Van Thai, 71; A Vietnamese General\n| work=The New York Times\n| number =\n| pages =\n| page = \n| date = 5 July 1986\n| accessdate =\n| language = english\n| citations =\n}}</ref> He was also Chief of Staff in the [[Battle of \u0110i\u1ec7n Bi\u00ean Ph\u1ee7]].\n\n== Early life ==\nHo\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i was born Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Xi\u00eam, on 1 May 1915 (or 1917 since his older brother was born in 1915), in the village of [[An Khang]] (now [[Tay An]], [[Tien Hai District]], [[Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province]]). His father, Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Thu\u1eadt, was a [[Han Nom]] teacher.\n\nThe third born of seven siblings, Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i was dedicated to studying and graduated from a French-Vietnamese colonial elementary school, however, he dropped out of school at the age of 13 because of financial difficulties; '''Xi\u00eam''' had to work as a barber. At the age of 15, he was influenced by a Communist movement.\n\nAt the age 18, Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i worked in a mine in [[H\u1ed3ng Gai]] in [[Qu\u1ea3ng Ninh Province]], he attended movements against the unfairness of the mine owners and returned to his hometown in 1936.\n\nIn 1938 he joined the [[Communist Party of Indochina]]. Trailed by the colonial authorities, he fled to the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]] in 1941. There, he was educated at a military academy in Guilin. In 1944 he returned to [[Vietnam]] where he was employed for propaganda and intelligence purposes of the forming [[Vi\u1ec7t Minh]]. In December 1945 he became Chief of Staff of the Vi\u1ec7t Minh forces. In 1948 he was promoted to major general. Hoang Van Thai was dismissed as Chief of Staff shortly before the beginning of the Battle of \u0110i\u1ec7n Bi\u00ean Ph\u1ee7. His successor was [[Van Tien Dung]].<ref>Christopher E. Goscha : ''Historical Dictionary of the Indochina War (1945\u20131954)'', Kopenhagen, 2011, S. 216</ref>\n\nIn January 1948 Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i was promoted to one of the first generals of Vietnam. On August 31, 1959, he was promoted to the rank of lieutenant general. In 1966 he was assigned as Commander and Political Commissar to the Military Region V. From 1967 to 1973, when he was assigned to the south, he was commander of the South Vietnamese Liberation Army and the deputy COSVN. At the Battle of Loc Ninh he was Commanding Officer (27 October 1967 \u2013 10 December 1967), also during the [[Tet Offensive]] in January 1968. In April 1974 he was promoted to the rank of colonel general. He was appointed Deputy Minister of Defense, First Deputy Chief of the General Staff and permanent member of the Central Military Committee. In January 1980 he was promoted to general. He was a member of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of Vietnam and delegate of the 7th Party Congress. On July 2, 1986, he died suddenly after a heart attack in Army Hospital 108.\n\nHe opened a music class to organise young men to participate in rebellious activities. After few months, students were numbered to 170 members with himself as a secretary. Through experiences gained from secret activities, he spread leaflets on the sly in order to encourage people to get involved against high taxes, struggling for democratic freedom.\n\n== Early service in military ==\nIn 1941, [[Vi\u1ec7t Minh]] was founded, he became  a commander of the squad [[Vietnamese People's National Salvation Army|National Salvation Army]] [[B\u1eafc S\u01a1n District|B\u1eafc S\u01a1n]] ([[L\u1ea1ng S\u01a1n]]). Under the name of '''Quoc Binh''', meaning \"peaceful country\", several comrades and he left for military training in [[Liuzhou]], China.\n\nIn late 1943, he met with [[Ho Chi Minh]], then released by the [[Chiang Kai-shek]] government. After military school he returned to Vietnam with a new assumed name '''Hoang Van Thai''' (Thai stems from his hometown [[Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province|Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh]], also meaning \"peaceful\"), joined the resistance against Japan and then joined the [[August Revolution]] against France in 1945.  He also was one of 34 soldiers led by [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]] that met on 22 December 1944 to found the Armed Propaganda Unit for National Liberation that later became the [[Vietnam People's Army]]. Thai was assigned to be in charge of propaganda and agitation of the newly organisation. \n[[File:Vietnam People's Army date establishment.gif|left|thumb|200px|The PAVN's establishment in 1944.  Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i wearing a pith helmet and holding the flag.]]\n\nIn March 1945, he commanded a group of 100 members to advance to [[Cho Don District]] to form a foundation in the area. In the meantime, the Japanese led a coup d'\u00e9tat against the French authority. French units dispersed and fled to China later on. [[Vi\u1ec7t Minh]] cadres with the help of the PAVN quickly formed a new authority and established training. Thai, subsequently, took order from [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]] to hand over the area to the local Vi\u1ec7t Minh cadres and continued to lead members down to [[Cho Chu]], [[Tuy\u00ean Quang]], supporting as well as training self-defence units and political cadre groups.\n\nIn April 1945, the Northern Military Meeting determined the merging of several groups, including the Vietnam People's Army, into the ''Vietnam Liberation Army''  (Vi\u1ec7t Nam Gi\u1ea3i Ph\u00f3ng Qu\u00e2n). Vietnam Liberation Army was considered as the main force of Vi\u1ec7t Minh. At the same time, the ''Political-Military Japanese Resistance school'' (Tr\u01b0\u1eddng Qu\u00e2n ch\u00ednh kh\u00e1ng Nh\u1eadt) was established in [[Tan Trao]]. Thai was assigned as the principal in charge of educating army staffs for the Vietnam Liberation Army.\n\n== The First Indochina War ==\nOn 7 September 1945, The President of the Provisional Government of Democratic Republic of Vietnam, [[Ho Chi Minh]] mandated the foundation of a [[General Staff of the Vietnam People's Army|General Staff]] and appointed Thai as the Chief of General Staff. Under this mandate,  Thai was assigned as the first Chief of General Staff of the Vietnam People's Army. (1945\u20131953), by President [[Ho Chi Minh]] of the [[Government of Vietnam|Provisional Government]] at the age of 30.\n\nOn 22 May 1946, the [[Vietnamese National Guard|National Guard]] was renamed as [[Vietnamese National Army]], officially becoming a regular army placed under the control of the [[General Staff of the Vietnam People's Army|General Staff]]. In the meantime, although [[Ho\u2013Sainteny agreement]] and Provisional 14 September agreement were signed and being active, but the French put pressure by force on the newly government to reattain [[French Indochina]]. As the Chief of General Staff of the Vietnamese National Army, Thai organised the army personnel and established armed forces as well as paramilitaries in countrysides and defence forces in cities. By the end of 1946, approximately 1 million militias were organised and trained in preparation for war while every diplomatic means failed.\n\nWhen French troops provoked in [[Hai Phong]], Thai directly commanded the front in Hai Phong from the 20th to 27th in November 1947. [[Vietnamese Nationwide Resistance]] broke out in [[Hanoi]], Thai and [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]] were the ones that approved operational plans of the Hanoi front leader [[Vuong Thua Vu]]. The plans proposed a firm deployment restraining the French from moving forward as well as decreasing the number of French troops in the city within 2 months.\n\nAfter baffling the French attempt, on 26 August 1947, a major [[Division (military)|Division]] regarded as [[Independence Division]] was created. Chief of General Staff Hoang Van Thai was assigned as a commander. However, on 7 October, the French launched the [[Operation Lea]] attacking [[Vi\u1ec7t B\u1eafc]] base. Units that had been organised to form Division previously had to disperse into small fronts. Thai was assigned to play a role as the commander of the Route Coloniale 3 front. Eventually, the Operation Lea resulted in French limited success and Vietnamese strategic victory.\n\nIn January 1948, he was promoted as one of the first Generals of Vietnam, along with: [[General]] [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]], Lieutenant General [[Nguy\u1ec5n B\u00ecnh]], and [[Major General]]s: [[Nguyen Son]], [[Chu V\u0103n T\u1ea5n]], [[Hoang Sam]], [[Tr\u1ea7n \u0110\u1ea1i Ngh\u0129a]], [[Le Hien Mai]], [[V\u0103n Ti\u1ebfn D\u0169ng]], [[Tr\u1ea7n T\u1eed B\u00ecnh]], [[Le Thiet Hung]], [[Duong Van Duong]] (died in 1946).\n\nIn 1950, he was Chief of Staff of [[Battle of Route Coloniale 4|Borders campaign]] and the Commanding Officer in the [[Battle of \u0110\u00f4ng Kh\u00ea]], which opened the campaign.\n\n=== Campaign in First Indochina War ===\nCampaigns that Thai participated in as the Chief of General Staff (with [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]] playing the role of a commander) in the [[First Indochina War]]:\n# [[Operation Lea]], autumn-winter 1947.\n# [[Battle of Route Coloniale 4]], September\u2013October 1950.\n# [[Battle of V\u0129nh Y\u00ean]], December 1950.\n# [[Battle of Hoang Hoa Tham]], 1951.\n# [[Battle of H\u00e0 Nam Ninh]], May 1951.\n# [[Battle of H\u00f2a B\u00ecnh]], December 1951.\n# [[Battle of Northwest]], September 1952.\n# [[Battle of Upper Laos]], April 1953.\n# [[Battle of Dien Bien Phu]], March to May 1954.\n\n=== Battle of Dien Bien Phu ===\nIn 1953, Major General [[Van Tien Dung]], then Commander of [[320th Division (Vietnam)|320th Division]], was recalled to [[Vi\u1ec7t B\u1eafc]] to assume the [[General Staff of the Vietnam People's Army|Chief of General Staff]] position. Thai was assigned as Deputy Chief of General Staff. In fact, he was appointed as Special Campaign Chief of Staff [[Battle of Dien Bien Phu|\u0110i\u1ec7n Bi\u00ean Ph\u1ee7]], assistant to the Commander in Chief [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]]. On 26 November 1953, he led a group of General Staff cadres to [[T\u00e2y B\u1eafc]].\n\nOn 30 November 1953, the group arrived in [[Battle of N\u00e0 S\u1ea3n|N\u00e0 S\u1ea3n]], he ordered the group to halt to investigate entrenched fortifications that the French had left earlier in August. The group began making operational plans in a bit later on. On 12 January 1954, V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p's group arrived.\n\nFollowing the victory of [[Vi\u1ec7t Minh]] in Dien Bien Phu, [[Geneva Conference (1954)|Geneva Conference]] was signed, ending 80 years of French presence in Vietnam.\n\n== In Vietnam War ==\n\nOn 31 August 1959, he was one of four people to be proposed for [[Colonel General]] rank, but he refused. He eventually was promoted to the rank of [[Lieutenant General]].\n\nIn 1960 to 1965, he held the position of chairman of the Committee for Physical Training and Sports of the Government, which was involved in military training.\n<ref>Ronald B. Frankum Jr. Historical Dictionary of the War in Vietnam. p. 206.</ref>\n\nIn March 1965, the first US troops were sent to [[\u0110\u00e0 N\u1eb5ng]], marked the official appearance of the Americans in [[South Vietnam]]. [[North Vietnam]] decided to send one of its most important seniors to the south, trying to balance the difficulty. Thai was assigned as Commander and Political Commissar of the [[5th Military Region (Vietnam People's Army)|5th Military Region]] in 1966.\n\nFrom 1967 to 1973, he was assigned to the South, made Commander of the [[Viet Cong|People's Liberation Armed Forces]] and Deputy Secretary of [[COSVN]]. The US army called him as a \"3 legged tiger\", the highest Northern commander in the South during the war years under the name of '''Muoi Khang'''.<ref>The Vietnam War, edited by Peter Lowe 1998, p.70</ref>\n\nDuring the time, he was the leader of [[First Battle of Loc Ninh]] Commanding Officer (27 October 1967 \u2013 10 December 1967). Also on 30 January 1968, he was the main commander of events during the Tet offensive throughout South Vietnam under instructions from the North.\n\n=== After the war ===\nIn 1974, he was promoted to the rank of [[colonel general]] and was appointed Deputy Minister of Defense, and First Deputy Chief of the General Staff, Standing member of the Central Military Committee. After 1975, he was also proposed to be a member of the [[Politburo of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Politburo]]; however, he refused.\n\nIn January 1980, he was promoted to full Army General.\n\nHe was a member of III, IV, and V Central Committee of the Communist Party of Vietnam, and a member of the VII Congress.\n\nOn 2 July 1986, he died suddenly of a heart attack at the Army Medical Institute 108 before he would have been promoted as the Minister of Defense, the first chairman of the Vietnam National Security Council (responsible for national security, home affair, and foreign policy matters. However, the position was rejected and has never been active since his death), some considered this event as an assassination as well as general [[L\u00ea Tr\u1ecdng T\u1ea5n]]'s death in the same year of 1986.<ref name=\"Bee\">{{cite web\n |author     = Tran Kien Quoc\n |url        = http://bee.net.vn/channel/1988/200912/Tuong-Hoang-Van-Thai-co-duyen-voi-la-Quoc-ky-1732603/\n |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091218080849/http://bee.net.vn/channel/1988/200912/Tuong-Hoang-Van-Thai-co-duyen-voi-la-Quoc-ky-1732603/\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 18 December 2009\n |title      = General Hoang Van Thai coast with a national flag\n |publisher  = Life Science News Online\n |date       = 15 December 2009\n |accessdate = 4 February 2011\n}}\n</ref><ref name=\"PLXH\">{{cite web\n |author      = Col: Bui Dinh Nguyen\n |url         = http://phapluatxahoi.vn/20100907102045416p1004c1028/dai-tuong-hoang-van-thai-vi-tong-tham-muu-truong-dau-tien-cua-quan-doi.htm\n |title       = Senior General Hoang Van Thai: The first Chief of General Staff of the army\n |publisher   = News Electronic Law and Society\n |date        = 7 September 2010\n |accessdate  = 4 February 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110824091423/http://phapluatxahoi.vn/20100907102045416p1004c1028/dai-tuong-hoang-van-thai-vi-tong-tham-muu-truong-dau-tien-cua-quan-doi.htm\n |archivedate = 24 August 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref> Although he did not officially become the 7th minister of defence,  Thai, in fact had been the acting minister before the transition of power that should have occurred in December 1986.\n\n== Awards and honours ==\nStreets that are named after Hoang Van Thai are in\n* [[Thanh Xu\u00e2n District|Thanh Xu\u00e2n District, Hanoi]]\n* [[\u0110i\u1ec7n Bi\u00ean Ph\u1ee7|\u0110i\u1ec7n Bi\u00ean Ph\u1ee7, \u0110i\u1ec7n Bi\u00ean Province]]\n* [[Ph\u00fa Th\u1ecd Province]]\n* [[Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh|Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh, Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province]]\n* [[Ti\u1ec1n H\u1ea3i District|Ti\u1ec1n H\u1ea3i District, Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province]]\n* [[Li\u00ean Chi\u1ec3u District|Li\u00ean Chi\u1ec3u District, Da Nang]]\n* [[Nha Trang|Nha Trang, Kh\u00e1nh H\u00f2a Province]]\n* [[Pleiku|Pleiku, Gia Lai Province]]\n* [[\u0110\u1ed3ng Xo\u00e0i|\u0110\u1ed3ng Xo\u00e0i, B\u00ecnh Ph\u01b0\u1edbc Province]]\n* [[T\u00e2n Ch\u00e2u District, T\u00e2y Ninh|T\u00e2n Ch\u00e2u District, T\u00e2y Ninh Province]]\n* [[District 7, Ho Chi Minh City]]\n\n=== Vietnam Orders and Decorations ===\n[[File:Vietnam Gold Star ribbon.png|50px]] [[Gold Star Order (Vietnam)|Gold Star Order]] (posthumously)<br>\n[[File:Vietnam Hochiminh Order ribbon.png|50px]] [[Ho Chi Minh Order]]<br>\n[[File:Vietnam Military Exploit Order ribbon.png|50px]] [[Military Exploit Order]] (2)<br>\n[[File:Resolution for Victory Order ribbon.png|50px]] [[Resolution for Victory Order]]<br>\n[[File:Resistance Order ribbon.png|50px]] [[Resistance Order]] (2)<br>\n[[File:Liberation Order ribbon.png|50px]] [[Liberation Order]] (3)<br>\n[[File:Vietnam Hochiminh Order ribbon.png|50px]] [[Glorious Fighter Medal]] (3)<br>\n[[File:Vietnam Friendship Order ribbon.png|50px]] [[Determined-to-Win Military Flag Medal]]\n\n=== Vietnam Badges ===\n* 40 Years Communist Party Membership Medal (1938\u20131978)\n* \"Dien Bien soldiers\" badges\n\n=== Foreign Orders and Decorations ===\n[[File:Order of Red Banner ribbon bar.png|50px]] [[Order of the Red Banner]]<br>\n[[File:CombatCooperationRibbon.png|50px]] [[Medal \"For Strengthening of Brotherhood in Arms\"|USSR Brotherhood in Arms Medal]]<br>\n[[File:40 years of victory rib.png|50px]] [[Jubilee Medal \"Forty Years of Victory in the Great Patriotic War 1941\u20131945\"|USSR Jubilee Medal]]<br>\n[[File:Order of merits for the people with silver star RIB.gif|50px]] [[Czechoslovak Meritorious Fighters against Fascism Medal]]<br>\n[[File:Brotherhood in Arms, Gr\u00fcnwald-Berlin.gif|50px]] [[Polish Brotherhood in Arms Medal]]<br>\n[[File:Order of merits for the people with silver star RIB.gif|50px]] [[Laos Freedom Medal]]\n\n=== Foreign Badges ===\n* [[Badges and decorations of the Soviet Union#Military badges|50th Anniversary Of The D.O.S.A.A.F.]]\n* USSR 40 years of the Great Victory on 9 May\n* [[60 Years of the Armed Forces of the Mongolian People's Republic]]\n* [[People's Republic of Kampuchea]]'s [[Fifth Anniversary of the Seventh of January Badge]]\n\n== Personal life ==\nHo\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i's first wife was L\u01b0\u01a1ng Th\u1ecb Thanh B\u00ecnh, a native of [[Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province]], who was involved in revolutionary activities with Thai. They were married in 1939. In the middle of 1940, Thai was captured and taken into custody. He escaped later on with helps from his wife, he then fled to [[B\u1eafc Giang]] and used an assumed name to conceal himself. They lost touch with each other until 1946. They had 2 children.\n\nHis second wife was [[\u0110\u00e0m Th\u1ecb Loan]], a former [[Tay people|Tay]] Lieutenant Colonel in the People's Army of Vietnam. She was one of three female soldiers in the original Vietnam Armed Propaganda Unit for National Liberation and was in the honour guard hoisting the flag of the new independent country in the Independence ceremony held at  Ba Dinh Square on 2 September 1945.<ref name=\"Bee\"/> They married on 15 September 1945. They had 6 children.\n\nThai was fluent in Mandarin, as well as proficient in writing [[Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m|N\u00f4m]], and was known to have a good command of  [[T\u00e0y language|T\u00e0y]], and [[Nung language (Tai)|N\u00f9ng]]. He knew a little French, Russian and English.\n\nThai's height was 1.75 meters (approx. 5&nbsp;ft 9), higher than the average height of Vietnamese people in the 20th century.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = No\n| title = [[Chief of General Staff of Vietnam People's Army]]\n| years = 1945\u20131953\n| after = [[Major General]] [[V\u0103n Ti\u1ebfn D\u0169ng]]}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = [[Major General]] [[V\u0103n Ti\u1ebfn D\u0169ng]]\n| title = [[Chief of General Staff of Vietnam People's Army]]\n| years = 1954\n| after = [[Major General]] [[V\u0103n Ti\u1ebfn D\u0169ng]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Vietnam People's Army Generals}}\n{{Vietnam People's Army Chief of Staff}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoang Van Thai}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of Vietnam politicians]]\n[[Category:Generals of the People's Army of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Guerrilla warfare theorists]]\n[[Category:North Vietnamese military personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:People from Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province]]\n[[Category:People from Qu\u1ea3ng B\u00ecnh Province]]\n[[Category:People of the First Indochina War]]\n[[Category:Viet Minh members]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese people of World War II]]\n[[Category:World War II resistance members]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Ho Chi Minh]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese nationalists]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Red Banner]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Vietnamese name|Ho\u00e0ng|Hoang|Th\u00e1i}}\n{{Infobox Minister\n|name          = <big>'''Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i'''</big><br><small>'''Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Xi\u00eam'''</small>\n|office        = 1st Chairman of the [[Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism (Vietnam)|Committee of Physical Training and Sports of Vietnam]]\n|president     = [[H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh]]\n|primeminister = [[Ph\u1ea1m V\u0103n \u0110\u1ed3ng]]\n|term_start    = 1960\n|term_end      = 1965\n|predecessor   = None\n|successor     = [[H\u00e0 Quang D\u1ef1]]\n|office1       = Deputy Minister of [[Ministry of Defence (Vietnam)|Ministry of Defence]]\n|president1    = [[T\u00f4n \u0110\u1ee9c Th\u1eafng]]<br>[[Tr\u01b0\u1eddng Chinh]]\n|minister1     = [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]]<br>[[V\u0103n Ti\u1ebfn D\u0169ng]]\n|term_start1   = 1974\n|term_end1     = 1986\n|predecessor1  =\n|successor1    =\n|office2       = 1st [[General Staff of the Vietnam People's Army#List of Chiefs of General Staff|Chief of General Staff]]\n|president2    = [[H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh]]\n|term_start2   = 7 September 1945\n|term_end2     = 1953\n|predecessor2  = None\n|successor2    = [[V\u0103n Ti\u1ebfn D\u0169ng]]\n|term_start3   = 1954\n|term_end3     = 1954\n|predecessor3  = [[V\u0103n Ti\u1ebfn D\u0169ng]]\n|successor3    = [[V\u0103n Ti\u1ebfn D\u0169ng]]\n|term_start4   = 1975\n|term_end4     = 1975 (acting)\n|office5       = Commander of the [[People's Liberation Armed Forces of South Vietnam|PLAF]]\n|predecessor5  = [[Tr\u1ea7n V\u0103n Tr\u00e0]]\n|successor5    = [[Tr\u1ea7n V\u0103n Tr\u00e0]]\n|term_start5   = 1967\n|term_end5     = 1973\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1915|5|1|df=y}}\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1986|7|2|1915|5|1|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = An Khang, [[Ti\u1ec1n H\u1ea3i]], [[Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province]], [[French Indochina]]\n|death_place   = [[108 Hospital]], [[Hanoi]], [[Vietnam]]\n|allegiance    = {{flagdeco|North Vietnam|1945}} [[Vi\u1ec7t Minh]]<br>{{flag|Vietnam}}\n|branch        = {{flagicon image|Flag of the People's Army of Vietnam.svg}} [[Vietnam People's Army]]<br>{{flagicon image|FNL Flag.svg}} [[Viet Cong]]\n|image         = \u0110\u1ea1i t\u01b0\u1edbng Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i.jpg\n|caption       = Portrait of General ''Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i'' (1986)\n|nickname      = Qu\u1ed1c B\u00ecnh (1941\u20131944 in China)<br>M\u01b0\u1eddi Khang (1965\u20131973 as Viet Cong commander)<br>Th\u00e0nh\n|serviceyears  = 1941\u201386\n|rank          = [[File:Vietnam People's Army General.jpg|20px]] [[General officer|General]]\n|commands      = [[Vi\u1ec7t Minh]]<br />[[Vietnam People's Army]]<br>[[People's Liberation Armed Forces]]\n|battles       = [[First Indochina War]]<br />[[Battle of Dien Bien Phu|Battle of \u0110i\u1ec7n Bi\u00ean Ph\u1ee7]]<br>[[Vietnam War]]<br>[[Tet Offensive|T\u1ebft Offensive]]\n|awards=[[File:Vietnam Gold Star ribbon.png|30px]] [[Gold Star Order (Vietnam)|Gold Star Order]] (posthumously)<br><br />See [[Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i#Vietnam Orders and Decorations|full list below]] for details of orders and commemorative medals awarded\n|spouse        = {{plainlist|\n* {{marriage|L\u01b0\u01a1ng Th\u1ecb Thanh B\u00ecnh<br>|1939|1986|end=his death}}\n* {{marriage|[[\u0110\u00e0m Th\u1ecb Loan]]<br>|1945|1986|end=his death}}\n}}\n|signature=\n}}\n\n'''Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i''' (1 May 1915 \u2013 2 July 1986), born '''Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Xi\u00eam''', was a Vietnamese Army General and a communist political figure. His hometown was T\u00e2y An, [[Ti\u1ec1n H\u1ea3i District]], [[Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province]].<ref>Ronald B. Frankum Jr. ''Historical Dictionary of the War in Vietnam'', 2011 p.207. \"Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i\"</ref>  During the [[Tet Offensive|T\u1ebft Offensive]], he was the highest senior North Vietnamese officer in South Vietnam.<ref name=\"Ford p. 87\">{{Harvnb|Ford|1995|p=87}}</ref> He was [[General Staff of the Vietnam People's Army#List of Chiefs of General Staff|the first chief of staff of the Vietnam People's Army]], and was responsible for key military forces in North Vietnam.<ref>{{cite web\n| author = AP\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1986/07/05/obituaries/hoang-van-thai-71-a-vietnamese-general.html\n| title = Hoang Van Thai, 71; A Vietnamese General\n| work=The New York Times\n| number =\n| pages =\n| page = \n| date = 5 July 1986\n| accessdate =\n| language = english\n| citations =\n}}</ref> He was also Chief of Staff in the [[Battle of \u0110i\u1ec7n Bi\u00ean Ph\u1ee7]].\n\n== Early life ==\nHo\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i was born Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Xi\u00eam, on 1 May 1915 (or 1917 since his older brother was born in 1915), in the village of [[An Khang]] (now [[Tay An]], [[Tien Hai District]], [[Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province]]). His father, Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Thu\u1eadt, was a [[Han Nom]] teacher. He had 7 siblings, he was the third child.\n\nHo\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i was dedicated to studying and graduated from a French-Vietnamese colonial elementary school, however, he dropped out of school at the age of 13 because of financial difficulties; '''Xi\u00eam''' had to work as a barber. At the age 15, he was influenced by a Communist movement.\n\nAt the age 18, Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i worked in a mine in [[H\u1ed3ng Gai]] in [[Qu\u1ea3ng Ninh Province]], he attended movements against the unfairness of the mine owners and returned to his hometown in 1936.\n\nIn 1938 he joined the [[Communist Party of Indochina]]. Trailed by the colonial authorities, he fled to the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]] in 1941. There, he was educated at a military academy in Guilin. In 1944 he returned to [[Vietnam]] where he was employed for propaganda and intelligence purposes of the forming [[Vi\u1ec7t Minh]]. In December 1945 he became Chief of Staff of the Vi\u1ec7t Minh forces. In 1948 he was promoted to major general. Hoang Van Thai was dismissed as Chief of Staff shortly before the beginning of the Battle of \u0110i\u1ec7n Bi\u00ean Ph\u1ee7. His successor was [[Van Tien Dung]].<ref>Christopher E. Goscha : ''Historical Dictionary of the Indochina War (1945\u20131954)'', Kopenhagen, 2011, S. 216</ref>\n\nIn January 1948 Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i was promoted to one of the first generals of Vietnam. On August 31, 1959, he was promoted to the rank of lieutenant general. In 1966 he was assigned as Commander and Political Commissar to the Military Region V. From 1967 to 1973, when he was assigned to the south, he was commander of the South Vietnamese Liberation Army and the deputy COSVN. At the Battle of Loc Ninh he was Commanding Officer (27 October 1967 \u2013 10 December 1967), also during the [[Tet Offensive]] in January 1968. In April 1974 he was promoted to the rank of colonel general. He was appointed Deputy Minister of Defense, First Deputy Chief of the General Staff and permanent member of the Central Military Committee. In January 1980 he was promoted to general. He was a member of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of Vietnam and delegate of the 7th Party Congress. On July 2, 1986, he died suddenly after a heart attack in Army Hospital 108.\n\nHe opened a music class to organise young men to participate in rebellious activities. After few months, students were numbered to 170 members with himself as a secretary. Through experiences gained from secret activities, he spread leaflets on the sly in order to encourage people to get involved against high taxes, struggling for democratic freedom.\n\n== Early service in military ==\nIn 1941, [[Vi\u1ec7t Minh]] was founded, he became  a commander of the squad [[Vietnamese People's National Salvation Army|National Salvation Army]] [[B\u1eafc S\u01a1n District|B\u1eafc S\u01a1n]] ([[L\u1ea1ng S\u01a1n]]). Under the name of '''Quoc Binh''', meaning \"peaceful country\", several comrades and he left for military training in [[Liuzhou]], China.\n\nIn late 1943, he met with [[Ho Chi Minh]], then released by the [[Chiang Kai-shek]] government. After military school he returned to Vietnam with a new assumed name '''Hoang Van Thai''' (Thai stems from his hometown [[Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province|Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh]], also meaning \"peaceful\"), joined the resistance against Japan and then joined the [[August Revolution]] against France in 1945.  He also was one of 34 soldiers led by [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]] that met on 22 December 1944 to found the Armed Propaganda Unit for National Liberation that later became the [[Vietnam People's Army]]. Thai was assigned to be in charge of propaganda and agitation of the newly organisation. \n[[File:Vietnam People's Army date establishment.gif|left|thumb|200px|The PAVN's establishment in 1944.  Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i wearing a pith helmet and holding the flag.]]\n\nIn March 1945, he commanded a group of 100 members to advance to [[Cho Don District]] to form a foundation in the area. In the meantime, the Japanese led a coup d'\u00e9tat against the French authority. French units dispersed and fled to China later on. [[Vi\u1ec7t Minh]] cadres with the help of the PAVN quickly formed a new authority and established training. Thai, subsequently, took order from [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]] to hand over the area to the local Vi\u1ec7t Minh cadres and continued to lead members down to [[Cho Chu]], [[Tuy\u00ean Quang]], supporting as well as training self-defence units and political cadre groups.\n\nIn April 1945, the Northern Military Meeting determined the merging of several groups, including the Vietnam People's Army, into the ''Vietnam Liberation Army''  (Vi\u1ec7t Nam Gi\u1ea3i Ph\u00f3ng Qu\u00e2n). Vietnam Liberation Army was considered as the main force of Vi\u1ec7t Minh. At the same time, the ''Political-Military Japanese Resistance school'' (Tr\u01b0\u1eddng Qu\u00e2n ch\u00ednh kh\u00e1ng Nh\u1eadt) was established in [[Tan Trao]]. Thai was assigned as the principal in charge of educating army staffs for the Vietnam Liberation Army.\n\n== The First Indochina War ==\nOn 7 September 1945, The President of the Provisional Government of Democratic Republic of Vietnam, [[Ho Chi Minh]] mandated the foundation of a [[General Staff of the Vietnam People's Army|General Staff]] and appointed Thai as the Chief of General Staff. Under this mandate,  Thai was assigned as the first Chief of General Staff of the Vietnam People's Army. (1945\u20131953), by President [[Ho Chi Minh]] of the [[Government of Vietnam|Provisional Government]] at the age of 30.\n\nOn 22 May 1946, the [[Vietnamese National Guard|National Guard]] was renamed as [[Vietnamese National Army]], officially becoming a regular army placed under the control of the [[General Staff of the Vietnam People's Army|General Staff]]. In the meantime, although [[Ho\u2013Sainteny agreement]] and Provisional 14 September agreement were signed and being active, but the French put pressure by force on the newly government to reattain [[French Indochina]]. As the Chief of General Staff of the Vietnamese National Army, Thai organised the army personnel and established armed forces as well as paramilitaries in countrysides and defence forces in cities. By the end of 1946, approximately 1 million militias were organised and trained in preparation for war while every diplomatic means failed.\n\nWhen French troops provoked in [[Hai Phong]], Thai directly commanded the front in Hai Phong from the 20th to 27th in November 1947. [[Vietnamese Nationwide Resistance]] broke out in [[Hanoi]], Thai and [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]] were the ones that approved operational plans of the Hanoi front leader [[Vuong Thua Vu]]. The plans proposed a firm deployment restraining the French from moving forward as well as decreasing the number of French troops in the city within 2 months.\n\nAfter baffling the French attempt, on 26 August 1947, a major [[Division (military)|Division]] regarded as [[Independence Division]] was created. Chief of General Staff Hoang Van Thai was assigned as a commander. However, on 7 October, the French launched the [[Operation Lea]] attacking [[Vi\u1ec7t B\u1eafc]] base. Units that had been organised to form Division previously had to disperse into small fronts. Thai was assigned to play a role as the commander of the Route Coloniale 3 front. Eventually, the Operation Lea resulted in French limited success and Vietnamese strategic victory.\n\nIn January 1948, he was promoted as one of the first Generals of Vietnam, along with: [[General]] [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]], Lieutenant General [[Nguy\u1ec5n B\u00ecnh]], and [[Major General]]s: [[Nguyen Son]], [[Chu V\u0103n T\u1ea5n]], [[Hoang Sam]], [[Tr\u1ea7n \u0110\u1ea1i Ngh\u0129a]], [[Le Hien Mai]], [[V\u0103n Ti\u1ebfn D\u0169ng]], [[Tr\u1ea7n T\u1eed B\u00ecnh]], [[Le Thiet Hung]], [[Duong Van Duong]] (died in 1946).\n\nIn 1950, he was Chief of Staff of [[Battle of Route Coloniale 4|Borders campaign]] and the Commanding Officer in the [[Battle of \u0110\u00f4ng Kh\u00ea]], which opened the campaign.\n\n=== Campaign in First Indochina War ===\nCampaigns that Thai participated in as the Chief of General Staff (with [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]] playing the role of a commander) in the [[First Indochina War]]:\n# [[Operation Lea]], autumn-winter 1947.\n# [[Battle of Route Coloniale 4]], September\u2013October 1950.\n# [[Battle of V\u0129nh Y\u00ean]], December 1950.\n# [[Battle of Hoang Hoa Tham]], 1951.\n# [[Battle of H\u00e0 Nam Ninh]], May 1951.\n# [[Battle of H\u00f2a B\u00ecnh]], December 1951.\n# [[Battle of Northwest]], September 1952.\n# [[Battle of Upper Laos]], April 1953.\n# [[Battle of Dien Bien Phu]], March to May 1954.\n\n=== Battle of Dien Bien Phu ===\nIn 1953, Major General [[Van Tien Dung]], then Commander of [[320th Division (Vietnam)|320th Division]], was recalled to [[Vi\u1ec7t B\u1eafc]] to assume the [[General Staff of the Vietnam People's Army|Chief of General Staff]] position. Thai was assigned as Deputy Chief of General Staff. In fact, he was appointed as Special Campaign Chief of Staff [[Battle of Dien Bien Phu|\u0110i\u1ec7n Bi\u00ean Ph\u1ee7]], assistant to the Commander in Chief [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]]. On 26 November 1953, he led a group of General Staff cadres to [[T\u00e2y B\u1eafc]].\n\nOn 30 November 1953, the group arrived in [[Battle of N\u00e0 S\u1ea3n|N\u00e0 S\u1ea3n]], he ordered the group to halt to investigate entrenched fortifications that the French had left earlier in August. The group began making operational plans in a bit later on. On 12 January 1954, V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p's group arrived.\n\nFollowing the victory of [[Vi\u1ec7t Minh]] in Dien Bien Phu, [[Geneva Conference (1954)|Geneva Conference]] was signed, ending 80 years of French presence in Vietnam.\n\n== In Vietnam War ==\n\nOn 31 August 1959, he was one of four people to be proposed for [[Colonel General]] rank, but he refused. He eventually was promoted to the rank of [[Lieutenant General]].\n\nIn 1960 to 1965, he held the position of chairman of the Committee for Physical Training and Sports of the Government, which was involved in military training.\n<ref>Ronald B. Frankum Jr. Historical Dictionary of the War in Vietnam. p. 206.</ref>\n\nIn March 1965, the first US troops were sent to [[\u0110\u00e0 N\u1eb5ng]], marked the official appearance of the Americans in [[South Vietnam]]. [[North Vietnam]] decided to send one of its most important seniors to the south, trying to balance the difficulty. Thai was assigned as Commander and Political Commissar of the [[5th Military Region (Vietnam People's Army)|5th Military Region]] in 1966.\n\nFrom 1967 to 1973, he was assigned to the South, made Commander of the [[Viet Cong|People's Liberation Armed Forces]] and Deputy Secretary of [[COSVN]]. The US army called him as a \"3 legged tiger\", the highest Northern commander in the South during the war years under the name of '''Muoi Khang'''.<ref>The Vietnam War, edited by Peter Lowe 1998, p.70</ref>\n\nDuring the time, he was the leader of [[First Battle of Loc Ninh]] Commanding Officer (27 October 1967 \u2013 10 December 1967). Also on 30 January 1968, he was the main commander of events during the Tet offensive throughout South Vietnam under instructions from the North.\n\n=== After the war ===\nIn 1974, he was promoted to the rank of [[colonel general]] and was appointed Deputy Minister of Defense, and First Deputy Chief of the General Staff, Standing member of the Central Military Committee. After 1975, he was also proposed to be a member of the [[Politburo of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Politburo]]; however, he refused.\n\nIn January 1980, he was promoted to full Army General.\n\nHe was a member of III, IV, and V Central Committee of the Communist Party of Vietnam, and a member of the VII Congress.\n\nOn 2 July 1986, he died suddenly of a heart attack at the Army Medical Institute 108 before he would have been promoted as the Minister of Defense, the first chairman of the Vietnam National Security Council (responsible for national security, home affair, and foreign policy matters. However, the position was rejected and has never been active since his death), some considered this event as an assassination as well as general [[L\u00ea Tr\u1ecdng T\u1ea5n]]'s death in the same year of 1986.<ref name=\"Bee\">{{cite web\n |author     = Tran Kien Quoc\n |url        = http://bee.net.vn/channel/1988/200912/Tuong-Hoang-Van-Thai-co-duyen-voi-la-Quoc-ky-1732603/\n |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091218080849/http://bee.net.vn/channel/1988/200912/Tuong-Hoang-Van-Thai-co-duyen-voi-la-Quoc-ky-1732603/\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 18 December 2009\n |title      = General Hoang Van Thai coast with a national flag\n |publisher  = Life Science News Online\n |date       = 15 December 2009\n |accessdate = 4 February 2011\n}}\n</ref><ref name=\"PLXH\">{{cite web\n |author      = Col: Bui Dinh Nguyen\n |url         = http://phapluatxahoi.vn/20100907102045416p1004c1028/dai-tuong-hoang-van-thai-vi-tong-tham-muu-truong-dau-tien-cua-quan-doi.htm\n |title       = Senior General Hoang Van Thai: The first Chief of General Staff of the army\n |publisher   = News Electronic Law and Society\n |date        = 7 September 2010\n |accessdate  = 4 February 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110824091423/http://phapluatxahoi.vn/20100907102045416p1004c1028/dai-tuong-hoang-van-thai-vi-tong-tham-muu-truong-dau-tien-cua-quan-doi.htm\n |archivedate = 24 August 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref> Although he did not officially become the 7th minister of defence,  Thai, in fact had been the acting minister before the transition of power that should have occurred in December 1986.\n\n== Awards and honours ==\nStreets that are named after Hoang Van Thai are in\n* [[Thanh Xu\u00e2n District|Thanh Xu\u00e2n District, Hanoi]]\n* [[\u0110i\u1ec7n Bi\u00ean Ph\u1ee7|\u0110i\u1ec7n Bi\u00ean Ph\u1ee7, \u0110i\u1ec7n Bi\u00ean Province]]\n* [[Ph\u00fa Th\u1ecd Province]]\n* [[Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh|Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh, Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province]]\n* [[Ti\u1ec1n H\u1ea3i District|Ti\u1ec1n H\u1ea3i District, Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province]]\n* [[Li\u00ean Chi\u1ec3u District|Li\u00ean Chi\u1ec3u District, Da Nang]]\n* [[Nha Trang|Nha Trang, Kh\u00e1nh H\u00f2a Province]]\n* [[Pleiku|Pleiku, Gia Lai Province]]\n* [[\u0110\u1ed3ng Xo\u00e0i|\u0110\u1ed3ng Xo\u00e0i, B\u00ecnh Ph\u01b0\u1edbc Province]]\n* [[T\u00e2n Ch\u00e2u District, T\u00e2y Ninh|T\u00e2n Ch\u00e2u District, T\u00e2y Ninh Province]]\n* [[District 7, Ho Chi Minh City]]\n\n=== Vietnam Orders and Decorations ===\n[[File:Vietnam Gold Star ribbon.png|50px]] [[Gold Star Order (Vietnam)|Gold Star Order]] (posthumously)<br>\n[[File:Vietnam Hochiminh Order ribbon.png|50px]] [[Ho Chi Minh Order]]<br>\n[[File:Vietnam Military Exploit Order ribbon.png|50px]] [[Military Exploit Order]] (2)<br>\n[[File:Resolution for Victory Order ribbon.png|50px]] [[Resolution for Victory Order]]<br>\n[[File:Resistance Order ribbon.png|50px]] [[Resistance Order]] (2)<br>\n[[File:Liberation Order ribbon.png|50px]] [[Liberation Order]] (3)<br>\n[[File:Vietnam Hochiminh Order ribbon.png|50px]] [[Glorious Fighter Medal]] (3)<br>\n[[File:Vietnam Friendship Order ribbon.png|50px]] [[Determined-to-Win Military Flag Medal]]\n\n=== Vietnam Badges ===\n* 40 Years Communist Party Membership Medal (1938\u20131978)\n* \"Dien Bien soldiers\" badges\n\n=== Foreign Orders and Decorations ===\n[[File:Order of Red Banner ribbon bar.png|50px]] [[Order of the Red Banner]]<br>\n[[File:CombatCooperationRibbon.png|50px]] [[Medal \"For Strengthening of Brotherhood in Arms\"|USSR Brotherhood in Arms Medal]]<br>\n[[File:40 years of victory rib.png|50px]] [[Jubilee Medal \"Forty Years of Victory in the Great Patriotic War 1941\u20131945\"|USSR Jubilee Medal]]<br>\n[[File:Order of merits for the people with silver star RIB.gif|50px]] [[Czechoslovak Meritorious Fighters against Fascism Medal]]<br>\n[[File:Brotherhood in Arms, Gr\u00fcnwald-Berlin.gif|50px]] [[Polish Brotherhood in Arms Medal]]<br>\n[[File:Order of merits for the people with silver star RIB.gif|50px]] [[Laos Freedom Medal]]\n\n=== Foreign Badges ===\n* [[Badges and decorations of the Soviet Union#Military badges|50th Anniversary Of The D.O.S.A.A.F.]]\n* USSR 40 years of the Great Victory on 9 May\n* [[60 Years of the Armed Forces of the Mongolian People's Republic]]\n* [[People's Republic of Kampuchea]]'s [[Fifth Anniversary of the Seventh of January Badge]]\n\n== Personal life ==\nHo\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i's first wife was L\u01b0\u01a1ng Th\u1ecb Thanh B\u00ecnh, a native of [[Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province]], who was involved in revolutionary activities with Thai. They were married in 1939. In the middle of 1940, Thai was captured and taken into custody. He escaped later on with helps from his wife, he then fled to [[B\u1eafc Giang]] and used an assumed name to conceal himself. They lost touch with each other until 1946. They had 2 children.\n\nHis second wife was [[\u0110\u00e0m Th\u1ecb Loan]], a former [[Tay people|Tay]] Lieutenant Colonel in the People's Army of Vietnam. She was one of three female soldiers in the original Vietnam Armed Propaganda Unit for National Liberation and was in the honour guard hoisting the flag of the new independent country in the Independence ceremony held at  Ba Dinh Square on 2 September 1945.<ref name=\"Bee\"/> They married on 15 September 1945. They had 6 children.\n\nThai was fluent in Mandarin, as well as proficient in writing [[Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m|N\u00f4m]], and was known to have a good command of  [[T\u00e0y language|T\u00e0y]], and [[Nung language (Tai)|N\u00f9ng]]. He knew a little French, Russian and English.\n\nThai's height was 1.75 meters (approx. 5&nbsp;ft 9), higher than the average height of Vietnamese people in the 20th century.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = No\n| title = [[Chief of General Staff of Vietnam People's Army]]\n| years = 1945\u20131953\n| after = [[Major General]] [[V\u0103n Ti\u1ebfn D\u0169ng]]}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = [[Major General]] [[V\u0103n Ti\u1ebfn D\u0169ng]]\n| title = [[Chief of General Staff of Vietnam People's Army]]\n| years = 1954\n| after = [[Major General]] [[V\u0103n Ti\u1ebfn D\u0169ng]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Vietnam People's Army Generals}}\n{{Vietnam People's Army Chief of Staff}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoang Van Thai}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of Vietnam politicians]]\n[[Category:Generals of the People's Army of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Guerrilla warfare theorists]]\n[[Category:North Vietnamese military personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:People from Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province]]\n[[Category:People from Qu\u1ea3ng B\u00ecnh Province]]\n[[Category:People of the First Indochina War]]\n[[Category:Viet Minh members]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese people of World War II]]\n[[Category:World War II resistance members]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Ho Chi Minh]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese nationalists]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Red Banner]]\n", "name_user": "Crsini", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ho%C3%A0ng_V%C4%83n_Th%C3%A1i"}
{"title_page": "Hugh O'Reilly (Archbishop of Armagh)", "text_new": "{{For|other people with the same name|Hugh O'Reilly (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox archbishop styles\n| archbishop name = Hugh O'Reilly \n| dipstyle   = The [[Most Reverend]]\n| offstyle   = [[Grace (style)|Your Grace]] or [[Archbishop]]\n| image      = \n}}\n{{Portal|Catholicism}}\n\n'''Hugh O'Reilly''' ({{lang-ga|Aodh \u00d3 Raghallaigh}}; c.1580\u20131653)<ref>[http://www.askaboutireland.ie/aai-files/assets/ebooks/184-Diocese%20of%20Kilmore/184-Diocese%20of%20Kilmore.pdf page 405]</ref> was an [[Irish people|Irish]] [[prelate]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]]. He served as [[Bishop of Kilmore]] from 1625 to 1628 and [[Archbishop of Armagh]] from 1628 to 1653.\n\nHe was the son of Honora and Mulmore O'Reilly, who was the grandson of the chief of the [[O'Reilly]] clan, Fearghal macSea\u00e1n, who ruled [[East Breifne]] from 1526\u20131534. Hugh O'Reilly was thus eligible for election to the chieftainship under the system of [[deirbhfhine]].<ref name=ODNB/> Hugh O'Reilly's genealogy is ''Aodh son of Maol M\u00f3rdha son of Aodh son of Fearghal son of Sea\u00e1n son of Cathal son of E\u00f3ghan na F\u00e9s\u00f3ige''.<ref>''A Genealogical History of the O\u2019Reillys'' by Eoghan O\u2019Raghallaigh, Section 18, p. 89</ref> Mulmore O'Reilly had four sons by his wife Honora- \u00c9monn, Hugh O'Reilly (Archbishop of Armagh), Fearghal and Domhnall. He also had an illegitimate son, Cathaoir. In the [[Plantation of Ulster]] by grant dated 29 April 1611, King [[James VI and I]] granted ''the town and lands of Gortatowill containing 6 polls, comprising a total of 300 acres at an annual rent of \u00a33-4s., to Mulmore McHugh McFarrall O'Rely, gent''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XD5JAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA212&lpg=PA212&dq=gortatowill&source=bl&ots=sGQavYggyh&sig=1un18sPzryyj1ZXIMJOYnxFeAU4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjI-MX8pcbZAhXDYlAKHYlcCbwQ6AEIMDAA#v=onepage&q=gortatowill&f=false|title=Calendar of the Patent Rolls of the Chancery of Ireland. - (Dublin 1800.) (angl.) 372 S.|last=|first=|date=1800|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=212}}</ref> Gortatowill now comprises the townlands of Prospect and [[Tawnagh]] in [[Corlough]] parish. Mulmore died sometime between 1611 and 1637.<ref name=ODNB>Bernadette Cunningham, 'O'Reilly, Hugh (c.1581\u20131653)', Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/20822, accessed 16 March 2008] Hugh O'Reilly (c.1581\u20131653): {{doi|10.1093/ref:odnb/20822}}. {{dead link|date=December 2011}}</ref> \n\n==Career==\n\nHugh O'Reilly was born in the townland of Aghaweely Lower in the parish of Ballintemple and was educated by the local Franciscan Order.<ref>'The Diocese of Kilmore' by Liam Kelly, 2017, p. 267</ref> He was ordained a priest in 1618 and pursued further studies in [[Rouen]] College. \nHe was appointed [[Bishop of Kilmore]] on 9 June 1625,<ref name=boreilh>{{Catholic-hierarchy|bishop|boreilh|Archbishop Hugh O'Reilly |11 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=brady1p282>{{Harvnb|Brady|1876}}, ''The Episcopal Succession in England, Scotland and Ireland, volume 1'', p. 282.</ref><ref name=handbook436>{{Harvnb|Fryde|Greenway|Porter|Roy|1986}}, ''Handbook of British Chronology'', p. 436.</ref> and [[Bishop (Catholic Church)|consecrated]] at St Peter's Church, [[Drogheda]] by Archbishop [[Thomas Fleming (archbishop)|Thomas Fleming]] of Dublin in July 1625.<ref name=brady1p282/><ref name=handbook415>{{Harvnb|Fryde|Greenway|Porter|Roy|1986}}, ''Handbook of British Chronology'', p. 415.</ref> Three years later, he was [[Translation (ecclesiastical)|translated]] to the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Armagh|Metropolitan see of Armagh]] as archbishop and primate by three consistorial acts: dated 5 May, 31 July, and 31 August 1628.<ref name=brady1p224>{{Harvnb|Brady|1876}}, ''The Episcopal Succession in England, Scotland and Ireland, volume 1'', p. 224.</ref>\n\nO'Reilly in perhaps most famous for calling a [[synod]] of bishops at [[Kells, County Meath]] in March 1642 to discuss the ongoing [[Irish Rebellion of 1641]]. The synod called for an end to the killing of unarmed civilians and robberies, and most considered that the aims of the conflict in support of Catholic rights and [[Charles I of England|King Charles]] amounted to a [[Just war theory|just war]].<ref>http://www.catholicity.com/encyclopedia/o/o'reilly,hugh.html</ref> A smaller group of clergy met with the Catholic nobility at [[Kilkenny]] from May 1642, resulting in the founding of the Irish [[Confederate Ireland|Confederacy]] later that year, which O'Reilly supported for the rest of his life.\n\nHe died in office in February 1653, aged 72, and was buried on Trinity Island in [[Lough Oughter]], the southern part of the [[Lough Erne]] complex.<ref name=boreilh/><ref name=brady1p226>{{Harvnb|Brady|1876}}, ''The Episcopal Succession in England, Scotland and Ireland, volume 1'', p. 226.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Brady |first=W. Maziere |authorlink=William Maziere Brady |title=The Episcopal Succession in England, Scotland and Ireland, A.D. 1400 to 1875 |url=https://archive.org/details/a548648301braduoft |year=1876 |publisher=Tipografia Della Pace |location=Rome |volume=Volume 1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Fryde |editor1-first=E. B. |editor2-last=Greenway |editor2-first=D. E. |editor3-last=Porter |editor3-first=S. |editor4-last=Roy |editor4-first=I. |title=Handbook of British Chronology |edition=3rd, reprinted 2003 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge |year=1986 |isbn=0-521-56350-X |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-rel|ca}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Richard Brady]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Kilmore]] |years=1625\u20131628}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Eugene Sweeney]]}}\n{{S-vac|last=[[Aodh Mac Cathmhaoil|Hugh McCaughwell]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Archbishop of Armagh]] <br/>and [[Primacy of Ireland|Primate of All Ireland]] |years=1628\u20131653}}\n{{S-vac|next=[[Edmund O'Reilly (archbishop)|Edmund O'Reilly]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oreilly, Hugh}}\n[[Category:1580s births]]\n[[Category:1653 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:17th-century Roman Catholic archbishops]]\n[[Category:People from County Cavan]]\n[[Category:People of Elizabethan Ireland]]\n[[Category:People of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic archbishops of Armagh]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic bishops of Kilmore]]\n\n\n{{Ireland-RC-bishop-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{For|other people with the same name|Hugh O'Reilly (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox archbishop styles\n| archbishop name = Hugh O'Reilly \n| dipstyle   = The [[Most Reverend]]\n| offstyle   = [[Grace (style)|Your Grace]] or [[Archbishop]]\n| image      = \n}}\n{{Portal|Catholicism}}\n\n'''Hugh O'Reilly''' ({{lang-ga|Aodh \u00d3 Raghallaigh}}; c.1580\u20131653)<ref>[http://www.askaboutireland.ie/aai-files/assets/ebooks/184-Diocese%20of%20Kilmore/184-Diocese%20of%20Kilmore.pdf page 405]</ref> was an [[Irish people|Irish]] [[prelate]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]]. He served as [[Bishop of Kilmore]] from 1625 to 1628 and [[Archbishop of Armagh]] from 1628 to 1653.\n\nHe was the son of Honora and Mulmore O'Reilly, who was the grandson of the chief of the [[O'Reilly]] clan, Fearghal macSea\u00e1n, who ruled [[East Breifne]] from 1526\u20131534. Hugh O'Reilly was thus eligible for election to the chieftainship under the system of [[deirbhfhine]].<ref name=ODNB/> Hugh O'Reilly's genealogy is ''Aodh son of Maol M\u00f3rdha son of Aodh son of Fearghal son of Sea\u00e1n son of Cathal son of E\u00f3ghan na F\u00e9s\u00f3ige''.<ref>''A Genealogical History of the O\u2019Reillys'' by Eoghan O\u2019Raghallaigh, Section 18, p. 89</ref> Mulmore O'Reilly had four sons by his wife Honora- \u00c9monn, Hugh O'Reilly (Archbishop of Armagh), Fearghal and Domhnall. He also had an illegitimate son, Cathaoir. In the [[Plantation of Ulster]] by grant dated 29 April 1611, King [[James VI and I]] granted ''the town and lands of Gortatowill containing 6 polls, comprising a total of 300 acres at an annual rent of \u00a33-4s., to Mulmore McHugh McFarrall O'Rely, gent''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XD5JAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA212&lpg=PA212&dq=gortatowill&source=bl&ots=sGQavYggyh&sig=1un18sPzryyj1ZXIMJOYnxFeAU4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjI-MX8pcbZAhXDYlAKHYlcCbwQ6AEIMDAA#v=onepage&q=gortatowill&f=false|title=Calendar of the Patent Rolls of the Chancery of Ireland. - (Dublin 1800.) (angl.) 372 S.|last=|first=|date=1800|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=212}}</ref> Gortatowill now comprises the townlands of Prospect and [[Tawnagh]] in [[Corlough]] parish. Mulmore died sometime between 1611 and 1637.<ref name=ODNB>Bernadette Cunningham, 'O'Reilly, Hugh (c.1581\u20131653)', Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/20822, accessed 16 March 2008] Hugh O'Reilly (c.1581\u20131653): {{doi|10.1093/ref:odnb/20822}}. {{dead link|date=December 2011}}</ref> \n\n==Career==\n\nHugh O'Reilly was born in the townland of Aghaweely lower in the parish of Ballintemple and was educated by the local Franciscan Order.<ref>['The Diocese of Kilmore' by Liam Kelly, 2017, p. 267]</ref> He was ordained a priest in 1618 and pursued further studies in [[Rouen]] College. \nHe was appointed [[Bishop of Kilmore]] on 9 June 1625,<ref name=boreilh>{{Catholic-hierarchy|bishop|boreilh|Archbishop Hugh O'Reilly |11 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=brady1p282>{{Harvnb|Brady|1876}}, ''The Episcopal Succession in England, Scotland and Ireland, volume 1'', p. 282.</ref><ref name=handbook436>{{Harvnb|Fryde|Greenway|Porter|Roy|1986}}, ''Handbook of British Chronology'', p. 436.</ref> and [[Bishop (Catholic Church)|consecrated]] at St Peter's Church, [[Drogheda]] by Archbishop [[Thomas Fleming (archbishop)|Thomas Fleming]] of Dublin in July 1625.<ref name=brady1p282/><ref name=handbook415>{{Harvnb|Fryde|Greenway|Porter|Roy|1986}}, ''Handbook of British Chronology'', p. 415.</ref> Three years later, he was [[Translation (ecclesiastical)|translated]] to the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Armagh|Metropolitan see of Armagh]] as archbishop and primate by three consistorial acts: dated 5 May, 31 July, and 31 August 1628.<ref name=brady1p224>{{Harvnb|Brady|1876}}, ''The Episcopal Succession in England, Scotland and Ireland, volume 1'', p. 224.</ref>\n\nO'Reilly in perhaps most famous for calling a [[synod]] of bishops at [[Kells, County Meath]] in March 1642 to discuss the ongoing [[Irish Rebellion of 1641]]. The synod called for an end to the killing of unarmed civilians and robberies, and most considered that the aims of the conflict in support of Catholic rights and [[Charles I of England|King Charles]] amounted to a [[Just war theory|just war]].<ref>http://www.catholicity.com/encyclopedia/o/o'reilly,hugh.html</ref> A smaller group of clergy met with the Catholic nobility at [[Kilkenny]] from May 1642, resulting in the founding of the Irish [[Confederate Ireland|Confederacy]] later that year, which O'Reilly supported for the rest of his life.\n\nHe died in office in February 1653, aged 72, and was buried on Trinity Island in [[Lough Oughter]], the southern part of the [[Lough Erne]] complex.<ref name=boreilh/><ref name=brady1p226>{{Harvnb|Brady|1876}}, ''The Episcopal Succession in England, Scotland and Ireland, volume 1'', p. 226.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Brady |first=W. Maziere |authorlink=William Maziere Brady |title=The Episcopal Succession in England, Scotland and Ireland, A.D. 1400 to 1875 |url=https://archive.org/details/a548648301braduoft |year=1876 |publisher=Tipografia Della Pace |location=Rome |volume=Volume 1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Fryde |editor1-first=E. B. |editor2-last=Greenway |editor2-first=D. E. |editor3-last=Porter |editor3-first=S. |editor4-last=Roy |editor4-first=I. |title=Handbook of British Chronology |edition=3rd, reprinted 2003 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge |year=1986 |isbn=0-521-56350-X |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-rel|ca}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Richard Brady]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Kilmore]] |years=1625\u20131628}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Eugene Sweeney]]}}\n{{S-vac|last=[[Aodh Mac Cathmhaoil|Hugh McCaughwell]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Archbishop of Armagh]] <br/>and [[Primacy of Ireland|Primate of All Ireland]] |years=1628\u20131653}}\n{{S-vac|next=[[Edmund O'Reilly (archbishop)|Edmund O'Reilly]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oreilly, Hugh}}\n[[Category:1580s births]]\n[[Category:1653 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:17th-century Roman Catholic archbishops]]\n[[Category:People from County Cavan]]\n[[Category:People of Elizabethan Ireland]]\n[[Category:People of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic archbishops of Armagh]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic bishops of Kilmore]]\n\n\n{{Ireland-RC-bishop-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cormac1cormac1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugh_O%27Reilly_(Archbishop_of_Armagh)"}
{"title_page": "Francis Kean", "text_new": "'''Francis Frederick Kean''' (born 1966) <ref name=ft20070120>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55543 |title=Navy chief faces murder charge, in custody |date=20 January 2007 |publisher=The Fiji Times |accessdate=6 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207205006/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55543 |archive-date=7 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=ft20070122>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55647 |date=22 January 2007 |publisher=The Fiji Times |title=Fisher to act as Navy commander |accessdate=6 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207205014/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55647 |archive-date=7 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> was the Commander of the [[Fiji]]an [[Republic of Fiji Military Forces|Navy]] when, in 2006, he was charged with [[murder]]. He was convicted of manslaughter the following year.\n\nKean, whose brother-in-law, [[Commodore (rank)|Commodore]] [[Frank Bainimarama]], was the Commander of the [[Republic of Fiji Military Forces]] and Interim [[Prime Minister of Fiji|Prime Minister]] at the time of these events, was arrested on 6 January 2006 and charged with the murder of salesman [[John Whippy]] at the [[Royal Suva Yacht Club]], after a wedding reception for Whippy's nephew [[Samuel Whippy]] and his bride, [[Ateca Bainimarama]], the Prime Minister's daughter, on 31 December 2006, the [[Fiji Sun]] reported. Kean had punched and kicked John Whippy following the latter's drunken insults against him. The attack resulted in Whippy's death.<ref name=\"rnz\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=36042 |title=Former Fiji navy commander Kean jailed for 18 months for manslaughter |publisher=Radio New Zealand International |date=26 October 2007 |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared in [[Suva]] [[Magistrate's Court (Fiji)|Magistrate's Court]] on 19 January and was remanded in custody at [[Korovou]] Prison till 2 February.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55529 |title=Navy Commander on murder charge |date=19 January 2007 |publisher=The Fiji Times |accessdate=6 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207205023/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55529 |archive-date=7 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Magistrate [[John Semesi]] refused a request from Kean's lawyer, [[Abhay Singh]], for [[bail]], after Assistant [[Director of Public Prosecutions (Fiji)|Director of Public Prosecutions]] [[Raymond Gibson]] said that Kean would be in a position to interfere with witnesses.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitv.com.fj/index.cfm?go=tv.resources&cmd=forumview&cbegin=0&uid=fijionenews&cid=11680 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928004601/http://www.fijitv.com.fj/index.cfm?go=tv.resources&cmd=forumview&cbegin=0&uid=fijionenews&cid=11680 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2007-09-28 |title=? |publisher=Fiji One Online }} </ref> (An Indo-Fijian student witnessed the murder and was eventually murdered.) He also refused a request for Kean to be detained at a military barracks.<ref name=ft20070122/> Lawyer Singh had claimed that Kean's life could be endangered if he were to be detained at [[Korovou]], as [[Counter Revolutionary Warfare Unit]] soldiers, whom Kean had helped prosecute for [[Mutinies of the 2000 Fijian coup d'\u00e9tat|an army mutiny]] in 2000, were imprisoned there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fijilive.com/news/show/news/2007/01/19/Fijilive15.html |title=? |publisher=Fijilive.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070120152453/http://www.fijilive.com/news/show/news/2007/01/19/Fijilive15.html |archivedate=20 January 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55587 |title=Military mum on top job |date=21 January 2007 |publisher=The Fiji Times |accessdate=6 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207205028/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55587 |archive-date=7 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nKean's second-in-command, [[Lieutenant Commander]] [[James Fisher (military)|James Fisher]], was named on 22 January to act in his stead.<ref name=ft20070122/> Kean, meanwhile, remained on full pay, military spokesman [[Major]] [[Neumi Leweni]] revealed on 23 January.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijivillage.com/artman/publish/article_35329.shtml |title=? |date= |publisher=Fiji Village |accessdate=}} {{Dead link|date=February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijivillage.com/artman/publish/article_35317.shtml |title=? |date= |publisher=Fiji Village |accessdate=}} {{Dead link|date=February 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 January, Justice [[Gerald Winter (judge)|Gerald Winter]] granted bail to Kean in the [[Suva]] [[High Court of Fiji|High Court]].  In granting bail over the objections of the investigating officer, Inspector [[Alelia Volau]] (who had claimed in his affidavits that there was a considerable possibility that Kean would abscond if bailed), Winter imposed strict conditions, including the payment of [[Fijian dollar|F$1000]] in surety (which two of his relatives paid)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55883 |title=Court bails navy chief |date=26 January 2007 |publisher=The Fiji Times |accessdate=6 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207205040/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55883 |archive-date=7 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and the surrender of his passport.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijivillage.com/artman/publish/article_35388.shtml |title=? |date= |publisher=Fiji Village |accessdate=}} {{Dead link|date=February 2011}}</ref>  In addition, he was not to interfere with prosecution witnesses, had to be on good behaviour, and had to inform the State if he changed his home address. He had to report to the [[Nabua, Fiji|Nabua]] Police Station each Wednesday and Friday, and a 9 pm \u2212 7 am [[curfew]] was imposed on him. He was also banned from visiting the military camp. Breach of the bail conditions would lead to imprisonment.\n\nOn 2 February Kean again appeared in court. The case was adjourned until 14 February, to be heard by Magistrate [[Aminiasi Katonivualiku]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitv.com.fj/index.cfm?go=tv.resources&cmd=forumview&cbegin=0&uid=fijionenews&cid=11973 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928003940/http://www.fijitv.com.fj/index.cfm?go=tv.resources&cmd=forumview&cbegin=0&uid=fijionenews&cid=11973 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2007-09-28 |title=? |publisher=Fiji One Online }} </ref> after state lawyer [[Wilisoni Kurisaqila]] asked for more time to prepare full disclosures.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=56322 |title=Kean's case adjourned |date=2 February 2007 |publisher=The Fiji Times |accessdate=6 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213111941/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=56322 |archive-date=13 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2007 he was sentenced to eighteen months imprisonment for manslaughter, after pleading guilty.<ref name=\"rnz\"/> He was released, however, after only one week. The charges were reduced from murder to manslaughter because the only witness had been murdered.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kean, Francis}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Fijian Naval Officers]]\n[[Category:Fijian people of British descent]]\n[[Category:Fijian people of I-Taukei Fijian descent]]\n[[Category:Fijian people convicted of manslaughter]]\n", "text_old": "'''Francis Frederick Kean''' (born 1966) <ref name=ft20070120>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55543 |title=Navy chief faces murder charge, in custody |date=20 January 2007 |publisher=The Fiji Times |accessdate=6 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207205006/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55543 |archive-date=7 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=ft20070122>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55647 |date=22 January 2007 |publisher=The Fiji Times |title=Fisher to act as Navy commander |accessdate=6 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207205014/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55647 |archive-date=7 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> was the Commander of the [[Fiji]]an [[Republic of Fiji Military Forces|Navy]] when, in 2006, he was charged with [[murder]]. He was convicted of manslaughter the following year.\n\nKean, whose brother-in-law, [[Commodore (rank)|Commodore]] [[Frank Bainimarama]], was the Commander of the [[Republic of Fiji Military Forces]] and Interim [[Prime Minister of Fiji|Prime Minister]] at the time of these events, was arrested on 6 January 2006 and charged with the murder of salesman [[John Whippy]] at the [[Royal Suva Yacht Club]], after a wedding reception for Whippy's nephew [[Samuel Whippy]] and his bride, [[Ateca Bainimarama]], the Prime Minister's daughter, on 31 December 2006, the [[Fiji Sun]] reported. Kean had punched and kicked John Whippy following the latter's drunken insults against him. The attack resulted in Whippy's death.<ref name=\"rnz\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=36042 |title=Former Fiji navy commander Kean jailed for 18 months for manslaughter |publisher=Radio New Zealand International |date=26 October 2007 |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared in [[Suva]] [[Magistrate's Court (Fiji)|Magistrate's Court]] on 19 January and was remanded in custody at [[Korovou]] Prison till 2 February.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55529 |title=Navy Commander on murder charge |date=19 January 2007 |publisher=The Fiji Times |accessdate=6 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207205023/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55529 |archive-date=7 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Magistrate [[John Semesi]] refused a request from Kean's lawyer, [[Abhay Singh]], for [[bail]], after Assistant [[Director of Public Prosecutions (Fiji)|Director of Public Prosecutions]] [[Raymond Gibson]] said that Kean would be in a position to interfere with witnesses.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitv.com.fj/index.cfm?go=tv.resources&cmd=forumview&cbegin=0&uid=fijionenews&cid=11680 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928004601/http://www.fijitv.com.fj/index.cfm?go=tv.resources&cmd=forumview&cbegin=0&uid=fijionenews&cid=11680 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2007-09-28 |title=? |publisher=Fiji One Online }} </ref> (An Indo-Fijian student witnessed the murder and was eventually murdered.) He also refused a request for Kean to be detained at a military barracks.<ref name=ft20070122/> Lawyer Singh had claimed that Kean's life could be endangered if he were to be detained at [[Korovou]], as [[Counter Revolutionary Warfare Unit]] soldiers, whom Kean had helped prosecute for [[Mutinies of the 2000 Fijian coup d'\u00e9tat|an army mutiny]] in 2000, were imprisoned there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fijilive.com/news/show/news/2007/01/19/Fijilive15.html |title=? |publisher=Fijilive.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070120152453/http://www.fijilive.com/news/show/news/2007/01/19/Fijilive15.html |archivedate=20 January 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55587 |title=Military mum on top job |date=21 January 2007 |publisher=The Fiji Times |accessdate=6 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207205028/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55587 |archive-date=7 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nKean's second-in-command, [[Lieutenant Commander]] [[James Fisher (military)|James Fisher]], was named on 22 January to act in his stead.<ref name=ft20070122/> Kean, meanwhile, remained on full pay, military spokesman [[Major]] [[Neumi Leweni]] revealed on 23 January.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijivillage.com/artman/publish/article_35329.shtml |title=? |date= |publisher=Fiji Village |accessdate=}} {{Dead link|date=February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijivillage.com/artman/publish/article_35317.shtml |title=? |date= |publisher=Fiji Village |accessdate=}} {{Dead link|date=February 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 January, Justice [[Gerald Winter (judge)|Gerald Winter]] granted bail to Kean in the [[Suva]] [[High Court of Fiji|High Court]].  In granting bail over the objections of the investigating officer, Inspector [[Alelia Volau]] (who had claimed in his affidavits that there was a considerable possibility that Kean would abscond if bailed), Winter imposed strict conditions, including the payment of [[Fijian dollar|F$1000]] in surety (which two of his relatives paid)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55883 |title=Court bails navby chief |date=26 January 2007 |publisher=The Fiji Times |accessdate=6 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207205040/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=55883 |archive-date=7 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and the surrender of his passport.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijivillage.com/artman/publish/article_35388.shtml |title=? |date= |publisher=Fiji Village |accessdate=}} {{Dead link|date=February 2011}}</ref>  In addition, he was not to interfere with prosecution witnesses, had to be on good behaviour, and had to inform the State if he changed his home address. He had to report to the [[Nabua, Fiji|Nabua]] Police Station each Wednesday and Friday, and a 9 pm \u2212 7 am [[curfew]] was imposed on him. He was also banned from visiting the military camp. Breach of the bail conditions would lead to imprisonment.\n\nOn 2 February Kean again appeared in court. The case was adjourned until 14 February, to be heard by Magistrate [[Aminiasi Katonivualiku]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitv.com.fj/index.cfm?go=tv.resources&cmd=forumview&cbegin=0&uid=fijionenews&cid=11973 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928003940/http://www.fijitv.com.fj/index.cfm?go=tv.resources&cmd=forumview&cbegin=0&uid=fijionenews&cid=11973 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2007-09-28 |title=? |publisher=Fiji One Online }} </ref> after state lawyer [[Wilisoni Kurisaqila]] asked for more time to prepare full disclosures.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=56322 |title=Kean's case adjourned |date=2 February 2007 |publisher=The Fiji Times |accessdate=6 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213111941/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=56322 |archive-date=13 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2007 he was sentenced to eighteen months imprisonment for manslaughter, after pleading guilty.<ref name=\"rnz\"/> He was released, however, after only one week. The charges were reduced from murder to manslaughter because the only witness had been murdered.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kean, Francis}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Fijian Naval Officers]]\n[[Category:Fijian people of British descent]]\n[[Category:Fijian people of I-Taukei Fijian descent]]\n[[Category:Fijian people convicted of manslaughter]]\n", "name_user": "Ender's Shadow Snr", "label": "safe", "comment": "Navy not navby!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Kean"}
{"title_page": "NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship", "text_new": "{{short description|Wrestling championship}}\n{{good article}}\n{{about|the current NWA welterweight title that CMLL introduced in 2010|the original NWA welterweight title created in 1946|NWA World Welterweight Championship}}\n{{Infobox pro wrestling championship\n|championshipname = NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship\n|image            = NWA World Historic Light Heavyweight Championship.jpg\n|caption          = The belt design of all three NWA Historic championships\n|alt              = A championship belt with a silver front plate\n|currentholder    = [[Volador Jr.]]\n|won              = August 4, 2018\n|promotion        = [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]]\n|created          = August 12, 2010<ref name=FirstHistoric/>\n|mostreigns       = [[Volador Jr.]] ([[#List of combined reigns|3 reigns]])\n|firstchamp       = [[Mephisto (wrestler)|Mephisto]]<ref name=FirstHistoric/>\n|longestreign     = [[Volador Jr.]] {{nobr|({{age in days nts|month1=08|day1=01|year1=2014}})}}<ref name=VoladorJr2/>\n|shortestreign    = [[La Sombra (wrestler)|La Sombra]] {{nobr|(56 days)}}<ref name=VoladorJr2/><ref name=LaSombra2/>\n|pastnames        = CMLL Historic Welterweight Championship<ref name=FirstHistoric/>\n|heaviest         = [[Matt Taven]] ({{convert|99|kg|lb|abbr=on}})<ref name=\"AlmanacStats\">{{cite news|title=Statistics for Professional wrestlers|work=PWI Presents: 2007 Wrestling Almanak and book of facts|publisher=Kappa Publications|id=2007 Edition|page=72}}</ref>\n|lightest=[[M\u00e1scara Dorada]] ({{convert|80|kg|lb|abbr=on}}){{efn|''NJPW'': \"\u4f53\u91cd 80kg\" (\"Weight 80 kg\")<ref name=NJPW>{{cite web | url= http://www.njpw.co.jp/data/detail_profile.php?f=595 | script-title=ja:\u30de\u30b9\u30ab\u30e9\u30fb\u30c9\u30e9\u30c0 | trans-title=Mascara Dorada| accessdate=January 19, 2015 | work=[[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] | language=Japanese | archivedate=April 13, 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413190155/http://www.njpw.co.jp/data/detail_profile.php?f=595}}</ref>}}\n|youngest         = [[La Sombra (wrestler)|La Sombra]] {{nobr|({{Age in years and days|November 3, 1989|March 13, 2011}})}}{{efn|''Fuego en el Ring\": \"Fecha de nacimiento: 03 de Noviembre de 1983\" (\"Date of Birth: November 3, 1983\")<ref name=FuegoSombra>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuegoenelring.com/wrestlers_full_tec.php?wrestlers_id=84|title=Tecnicos \u2013 La Sombra|accessdate=October 17, 2009|work=Fuego en el ring|language=Spanish| archivedate=July 11, 2011 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711053948/http://www.fuegoenelring.com/wrestlers_full_tec.php?wrestlers_id=84}}</ref>}}\n|oldest           = [[Negro Casas]] {{nobr|({{Age in years and days|January 10, 1960|February 13, 2012}})}}{{efn|''PWI Almanac'' p. 69: \"Date of birth: January 10, 1960\"<ref name=\"Almanac2008Stats\">{{cite news|title=Statistics for Professional wrestlers|work=PWI Presents: 2008 Wrestling Almanak and book of facts|publisher=Kappa Publications|id=2008 Edition|page=69}}</ref>}}\n|}}\n\nThe '''NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship''' (''Campeonato Mundial Historico de Peso Welter de la NWA'' in [[Spanish language|Spanish]]) is a [[professional wrestling]] championship governed by [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]] (CMLL). CMLL had held the [[NWA World Welterweight Championship]] for over 53 years even after leaving the NWA in 1989. In 2010 the [[National Wrestling Alliance]], represented by [[Blue Demon Jr.]], the president of NWA Mexico, sent letters to CMLL telling them to stop promoting NWA-branded championships since CMLL was not part of the NWA any longer. On August 12, 2010, CMLL debuted the new NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship belt and named Mephisto, the final CMLL-recognized NWA World Welterweight Champion, as the inaugural champion. The championship was initially announced as the CMLL Historic Welterweight Championship, but when the belt was unveiled, it was labelled the \"NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship\".\n\nIn Mexico, the ''lucha libre'' commission's definition of the [[Lucha Libre#Weight classes|welterweight weight class]] is between {{convert|70|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and {{convert|78|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. [[Volador Jr.]] is the current NWA World Historic Welterweight Champion, having defeated [[Matt Taven]] on August 3, 2018. This is Volador Jr.'s third reign with the title; he is the ninth overall champion. Volador Jr.'s second reign was the longest of any NWA World Historic Welterweight Champion, 1,337 days. All title matches take place under [[Professional wrestling match types#Series variations|best two-out-of-three falls]] rules when they take place in Mexico, but has been defended in single [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Fall|fall]] matches in Japan.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Mephisto CMLL.jpg|thumb|left|[[Mephisto (wrestler)|Mephisto]], the last [[NWA World Welterweight Championship|NWA World Welterweight Champion]]|alt=The masked wrestler Mephisto in the ring during a match.]]\nIn 1948 the Mexican ''[[lucha libre]]'' or [[professional wrestling promotion]] [[Empresa Mexicana de Lucha Libre]] (EMLL; Spanish for \"Mexican Wrestling Enterprise\") created the [[NWA World Welterweight Championship|World Welterweight Championship]].{{efn|name=NWAWelterBook|''Duncan & Will'' (2000) p. 390, Chapter name \"EMLL NWA Welterweight Title\"{{sfn|Duncan|Will|2000|p=390}}}} When EMLL became a member of the [[National Wrestling Alliance]] (NWA) in 1952 the championship was given the \"NWA\" prefix and became known as the NWA World Welterweight Championship. In the late 1980s, EMLL left the [[National Wrestling Alliance]] (NWA) to avoid the politics of the NWA.{{efn|name=Alliance|''Hornbakker'' (2006) p 305: \"EMLL was a member of the NWA from 1952 to 1986, and Lutteroth controlled the Alliance world light heavyweight, middleweight and welterweight titles.\"{{sfn|Hornbaker|2006|p=305}}}} While they left the NWA they did retain control of the NWA World Welterweight Championship as their main championship of the [[Lucha libre#Weight classes|welterweight division]]. They also promoted the [[Mexican National Welterweight Championship]] as a secondary title in the Welterweight division.{{efn|''Duncan & Will'' (2000) p. 392 chapter name \"Mexico: National Welterweight Title{{sfn|Duncan|Will|2000|p=392}}}} In 1992 EMLL changed their name and became known as ''Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre'' (CMLL; \"World Wrestling Council\") to rebrand themselves as a separate entity after leaving the NWA.{{efn|''Madigan'' \"in the late 1980s EMLL withdrew from the National Wrestling Alliance\"{{sfn|Madigan|2007|p=32}}}} They added a third welterweight championship to the promotion when they created the [[CMLL World Welterweight Championship]] on February 15, 1992.{{sfn|Duncan|Will|2000|p=396}}\n\nAfter the introduction of the CMLL championship, the then-reigning NWA World Welterweight Championship [[Misterioso (wrestler)|Misterioso]] left CMLL, vacating the championship.{{efn|''Duncan & Will'' (2000) p. 390 \"Vacant in 92/05 when Misterioso leaves EMLL.\"{{sfn|Duncan|Will|2000|p=390}}}} For the subsequent three years, CMLL did not promote the NWA World Welterweight Championship until bringing it back in the winter of 1995. [[Negro Casas]] won the championship, holding it until August 1996 where he lost it as part of a tournament to create the [[J-Crown]], eight championships unified as one.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=26&nr=1282 | title=J-Crown Tournament | work=Pro Wrestling History | accessdate=June 8, 2017}}</ref> from 1996 through 2007 the championship was promoted in Japan, but on November 27, 2007, [[La Sombra (wrestler)|La Sombra]] defeated [[Hajime Ohara]] to bring the championship back to CMLL.<ref name=WelterCage>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=5&nr=139&page=5&reign=57 | work=CageMatch | accessdate=June 5, 2017 | title=NWA World Welterweight Championship > Title Reigns > 27.11.2007 - 27.05.2009: La Sombra}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 the NWA, represented by NWA Mexico president [[Blue Demon Jr.]], reached out to CMLL and asked them to stop using the NWA-branded championships since they were not part of the NWA. Blue Demon Jr. was in the process of establishing NWA Mexico as a promotion and wanted to use the championship.{{efn|''S\u00faper Luchas'' (March 4, 2010): \"Blue Demon Jr. inform\u00f3 que NWA M\u00e9xico desconoce los t\u00edtulos mundiales que tienen los elementos del CMLL\" (\"Blue Demon Jr. Reported that NWA Mexico does not recognize the world championships controlled by CMLL\")<ref>{{cite web | url=http://superluchas.com/2010/03/04/blue-demon-jr-no-reconoce-los-titulos-de-nwa-que-estan-en-el-cmll-realizara-eliminatorias-para-sacar-a-los-nuevos-campeones/ | title=Blue Demon Jr. no reconoce los t\u00edtulos de NWA que est\u00e1n en el CMLL- Realizar\u00e1 eliminatorias para sacar a los nuevos campeones | trans-title=Blue Demon Jr. does not recognize the NWA titles held by CMLL- Will hold tournaments to determine new champions | date=March 4, 2010 | accessdate=June 25, 2015 | publisher=S\u00faper Luchas | language=Spanish | first=Alex | last=Ruiz}}</ref>}} There had been previous attempts by the NWA to gain back control of the three NWA-branded championships that CMLL used, the welterweight championship as well as the [[NWA World Light Heavyweight Championship]] and the [[NWA World Middleweight Championship]], but in those instances, CMLL had not responded to those requests at all. The promotion did not directly respond to the latest claim; the NWA Welterweight Champion, [[Mephisto (wrestler)|Mephisto]], commented instead, simply stating that the championships belonged to CMLL.{{efn|''S\u00faper Luchas'' (March 12, 2010): \"esos campeonatos siempre han estado en luchadores del CMLL\" (\"those championships have always belonged to CMLL wrestlers\")<ref>{{cite web|url=http://superluchas.com/2010/03/12/mephisto-responde-a-blue-demon-jr-no-tengo-que-entrar-a-ninguna-eliminatoria-porque-yo-soy-el-campeon/ |title=Mephisto responde a Blue Demon Jr.: \"No tengo que entrar a ninguna eliminatoria porque yo soy el campe\u00f3n...\" | trans-title=Mephisto responds to Blue Demon Jr .: \"I do not have to enter a tournament because I am the champion ...\"|author=Ruiz Glez, Alex|date=March 12, 2010|accessdate=March 14, 2010|work=S\u00faper Luchas|language=Spanish}}</ref>}} Finally, on August 12, 2010, CMLL debuted the new NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship belt and named Mephisto, the final CMLL-recognized NWA World Welterweight Champion, as the inaugural champion.<ref name=FirstHistoric/> The championship was initially announced as the CMLL Historic Welterweight Championship,<ref name=FirstHistoric/> but when the belt was unveiled, it was called the NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship.<ref name=FirstHistoric/>\n\n==Reigns==\n[[File:La Sombra.jpg|thumb|right|[[La Sombra (wrestler)|La Sombra]], the youngest wrestler to win the championship|alt=Masked wrestler La Sombra posing on the ropes during an outdoor wrestling event]]\n\n[[Matt Taven]] is the current NWA World Historic Welterweight Champion, having won the title on March 30, 2018, defeating [[Volador Jr.]] He is the eight overall champion and the first wrestler from the United States to hold the championship. Volador Jr. and [[La Sombra (wrestler)|La Sombra]] are the only two wrestlers to hold the championship twice. Volador Jr's second reign is the longest individual reign while La Sombra's 56-day reign in 2014 is the shortest of all championship reigns.<ref name=LaSombra2/><ref name=VoladorJr2/> On January 22, 2012, La Sombra became the first champion to defend the NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship outside of Mexico as he defeated Volador Jr. during the CMLL and [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW) co-promoted [[Fantastica Mania 2012]] in Tokyo, Japan.{{efn|''NJPW'' (January 22, 2012): \"\u30e1\u30a4\u30f3\u30a4\u30d9\u30f3\u30c8\u306f\u3001\u73fe\u5728\u306eCMLL\u3067\u30c8\u30c3\u30d72\u3068\u8a00\u308f\u308c\u308b\u30e9\u30fb\u30bd\u30f3\u30d6\u30e9\u3068\u30dc\u30e9\u30c9\u30fc\u30eb\u30fb\u30b8\u30e5\u30cb\u30a2\u304c\u3001NWA\u4e16\u754c\u30d2\u30b9\u30c8\u30ea\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30a6\u30a7\u30eb\u30bf\u30fc\u738b\u5ea7\u3092\u61f8\u3051\u3066\u6fc0\u7a81\u3002\" (\"In the main event, La Sombra and Volador Jr., who are said to currently be the top 2 in CMLL, met in a match for the NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship. \")<ref name=NJPWNight2>{{cite web | url= http://www.njpw.co.jp/tornament/12815?showResult=1 | title= NJPW Presents CMLL Fantastica Mania 2012 | date= January 22, 2012 | accessdate= January 22, 2012 | work=[[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] | language=Japanese | archivedate=January 25, 2012 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125074113/http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=491}}</ref>}}{{efn|''S\u00faper Luchas'' (January 22, 2012): \"NWA World Historic Welterweight Title: La Sombra (c) vence a Volador Jr. (21:47) con un Moonsault Press defendiendo el t\u00edtulo.\" (\"NWA World Historic Welterweight Title: La Sombra (c) defeated Volador Jr. (21:47) with a Moonsault Press defending the title.\")<ref name=SLNight2>{{cite web | url= http://superluchas.com/2012/01/22/njpw-cmll-resultados-fantasticamania-2012-dia-2/ | title= NJPW-CMLL: Resultados \"Fantasticaman\u00eda 2012\u2033 D\u00eda 2 | trans-title=NJPW-CMLL \"Fantasticamania 2012\" Results day 2 | author=Soy Rudo | date= January 22, 2012 | accessdate= January 22, 2012 | work=S\u00faper Luchas | language=Spanish}}</ref> }}\n\nAt the age of {{Age in years and days|November 3, 1989|March 13, 2011}} when he won the championship the first time, La Sombra is the youngest wrestler to win the championship.<ref name=FuegoSombra/> At {{Age in years and days|January 10, 1960|February 13, 2012}} at the time of his title win, [[Negro Casas]] is the oldest wrestler to win the championship.<ref name=\"Almanac2008Stats\"/>\n\n==Rules==\nAs a professional wrestling championship, it is not won legitimately; it is instead won via a predefined outcome of matches.{{efn|name=Hornbaker|''Hornbaker'' (2016) p. 550: \"Professional wrestling is a sport in which match finishes are predetermined. Thus, win/loss records are not indicative of a wrestler's genuine success based on their legitimate abilities - but on now much, or how little they were pushed by promoters\"{{sfn|Hornbaker|2016|p=550}}}} The Championship is designated as a welterweight title, which means that the championship can officially only be competed for by wrestlers weighing between {{convert|70|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and {{convert|78|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.{{efn|''Comisi\u00f3n de Box y Lucha Libre'' p. 42 \"Welter77 kilos\" (\"Welterweight 77 Kilos\")<ref name=\"BoxYLucha\">{{cite web| url= http://www.ordenjuridico.gob.mx/Estatal/ESTADO%20DE%20MEXICO/Reglamentos/MEXREG004.pdf | title= Reglamento de Boy Y Lucha Libre Professional del Estado de Mexico| author= Arturo Montiel Rojas | publisher= Comisi\u00f3n de Box y Lucha Libre Mexico D.F. | date= August 30, 2001 | accessdate= April 3, 2009 | language= Spanish |  archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061130181418/http://www.ordenjuridico.gob.mx/Estatal/ESTADO%20DE%20MEXICO/Reglamentos/MEXREG004.pdf|archivedate=November 30, 2006}}</ref>}} In the 20th century Mexican wrestling enforced the weight divisions more strictly, but in the 21st century the rules have occasionally been ignored for some of the weight divisions. The heaviest welterweight champion on record is [[Mephisto (wrestler)|Mephisto]] who was announced as weighing {{convert|90|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, {{convert|12|kg|lb|abbr=on}} above the official maximum weight limit.<ref name=\"AlmanacStats\"/> While the heavyweight championship is traditionally considered the most prestigious weight division in professional wrestling, CMLL places more emphasis on the lower weight divisions.{{efn|''Madigan'' (2007): \"Traditionally the heavyweight division was not considered the biggest draw, nor the most important division in Mexico\"{{sfn|Madigan|2007|p=115}}}} All title matches promoted in Mexico take place under [[Professional wrestling match types#Series variations|best two-out-of-three falls]] rules,{{efn|''Comisi\u00f3n de Box y Lucha Libre'' p. 44 \"ARTICULO 258.- Cada combate de lucha libre tendr\u00e1 como limite tres ca\u00eddas; cada ca\u00edda ser\u00e1 sin limite\nde tiempo, ganar\u00e1 quien obtenga dos ca\u00eddas de las tres en disputa\" (\"ARTICLE 258.- Each wrestling match shall have as limit three falls; Each fall will be without time limit. The winner will be the one to first obtain two of the three falls in the match,\")<ref name=\"BoxYLucha\"/>}} while championship matches promoted in Japan followed the local custom and were only one fall matches.<ref name=NJPWNight2/><ref name=SLNight2/>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Title history==\n{{Professional wrestling title history top|active=yes}}\n{{Professional wrestling title history middle\n|number =\u00a01\n|champion =\u00a0[[Mephisto (wrestler)|Mephisto]]\n|reign =\u00a01\n|date =\u00a0{{dts|2010|08|12}}\n|days =\u00a0{{age in days nts|month1=08|day1=12|year1=2010|month2=03|day2=13|year2=2011}}\n|location=[[Mexico City]]\n|event =\u00a0Press conference at [[Arena M\u00e9xico]]\n|notes =Mephisto was the final CMLL-recognized [[NWA World Welterweight Championship|NWA World Welterweight Champion]] and was thus named the first NWA World Historic Welterweight Champion.\n|ref =<ref name=FirstHistoric>{{cite web | url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1282333662 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100823021731/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1282333662 | title=Viva la Raza! Lucha Weekly | archivedate=August 23, 2010 | date=August 20, 2010 | accessdate=September 13, 2014 | first=Josh | last=Boutwell | work=Wrestleview}}</ref>\n}}{{Professional wrestling title history middle\n|number =\u00a02\n|champion =\u00a0{{sortname|La|Sombra|Andrade Cien Almas}}\n|reign =\u00a01\n|date =\u00a0{{dts|2011|03|13}}\n|days =\u00a0{{age in days nts|month1=03|day1=13|year1=2011|month2=02|day2=13|year2=2012}}\n|location=[[Mexico City]]\n|event =\u00a0''Domingo Familiar''\n|notes =\u00a0&nbsp;\n|ref ={{efn|''S\u00faper Luchas'' (March 14, 2011): \"5.- Campeonato mundial hist\u00f3rico NWA peso Welter: Sombra nuevo campe\u00f3n al vencer a Mephisto\" (\"5 NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship Sombra became the new champion with a victory over Mephisto\")<ref name=LaSombra>{{cite web | url= http://superluchas.com/2011/03/14/arena-mexico-resultados-13-de-marzo-la-sombra-nuevo-campeon-mundial-historico-nwa-de-peso-welter/ | title= Arena M\u00e9xico (resultados 13 de Marzo) \u00a1La Sombra nuevo campe\u00f3n mundial hist\u00f3rico NWA de peso Welter! | trans-title=Arena M\u00e9xico (results from March 13) \u00a1La Sombra is the new NWA World Historic Welterweight Champion | author=Ruiz Glez, Alex | date= March 14, 2011 | accessdate= June 26, 2011 | work= S\u00faper Luchas | language=Spanish}}</ref>}}\n}}{{Professional wrestling title history middle\n|number =\u00a03\n|champion =\u00a0{{sortname|Negro|Casas}}\n|reign =\u00a01\n|date =\u00a0{{dts|2012|02|13}}\n|days =\u00a0{{age in days nts|month1=02|day1=13|year1=2012|month2=06|day2=02|year2=2013}}\n|location=[[Puebla, Puebla]]\n|event =\u00a0[[House show|Live event]]\n|notes =\u00a0&nbsp;\n|ref ={{efn|''Cinco Radio'': \"obtuvo el hist\u00f3rico campeonato mundial welter de la NWA\" (\"he won the historic NWA welterweight championship \")<ref name=NegroCasas>{{cite web | url=http://www.cincoradio.com.mx/noticia/negro-casas-nuevo-campeon-mundial-welter/ | title=Negro Casas Nuevo Campe\u00f3n Mundial Welter | trans-title=Negro Casas is the new world welterweight champion | last=Blanco | first=Alejandro | date=February 14, 2012 | accessdate=February 14, 2012 | work=Cinco Radio | language=Spanish | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020071038/http://www.cincoradio.com.mx/noticia/negro-casas-nuevo-campeon-mundial-welter | archive-date=October 20, 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n}}{{Professional wrestling title history middle\n|number =\u00a04\n|champion =\u00a0{{sort|Mascara Dorada|[[M\u00e1scara Dorada]]}}\n|reign =\u00a01\n|date =\u00a0{{dts|2013|06|02}}\n|days =\u00a0{{age in days nts|month1=06|day1=02|year1=2013|month2=11|day2=19|year2=2013}}\n|location=[[Mexico City]]\n|event =\u00a0[[Sin Salida (2013)|''Sin Salida'']]\n|notes =\u00a0&nbsp;\n|ref ={{efn|''CMLL'' (June 3, 2013): \"El Campeonato Mundial Hist\u00f3rico NWA de Peso Welter tiene un nuevo due\u00f1o: M\u00e1scara Dorada.\" (\"The NWA Welterweight World Championship has a new owner: M\u00e1scara Dorada\")<ref name=MascaraDorada>{{cite web | url=http://cmll.com/02_resultados/dom_arena_mex/dom_arenamex.htm | archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6HQtwB92s?url=http://cmll.com/02_resultados/dom_arena_mex/dom_arenamex.htm | title=Resultados Arena M\u00e9xico Domingo 2 de Junio '13 | trans-title=Results from Arena M\u00e9xico Saturday June 2 '13 | last=Salazar L\u00f3pez | first=Alexis A. | date=June 3, 2013 | archivedate=June 17, 2013 | accessdate=June 3, 2013 | work=Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre | language=Spanish | url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n}}{{Professional wrestling title history middle\n|number =\u00a05\n|champion =\u00a0[[Volador Jr.]]\n|reign =\u00a01\n|date =\u00a0{{dts|2013|11|19}}\n|days =\u00a0{{age in days nts|month1=11|day1=19|year1=2013|month2=06|day2=06|year2=2014}}\n|location=[[Mexico City]]\n|event =\u00a0''Martes Popular''\n|notes =\u00a0&nbsp;\n|ref ={{efn|''CMLL'' (November 20, 2013): \"uego de haber transcurridos varios minutos y con una ca\u00edda por bando, M\u00e1scara Dorada no pudo soportar m\u00e1s y tras ser impactado de forma brutal con un Canadian Destroyer perdi\u00f3 el t\u00edtulo\" (\"After several minutes and with a fall by side, M\u00e1scara Dorada could not take any more and after being brutally hit with a Canadian Destroyer lost the title\")<ref name=VoladorJr>{{cite web | url=http://www.cmll.com/02_resultados/martes_arena_mex/martes_arenamex.htm | archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6LGm3fmWJ?url=http://www.cmll.com/02_resultados/martes_arena_mex/martes_arenamex.htm | title=Resultados Arena M\u00e9xico Martes 19 de Noviembre '13 | last=Salazar L\u00f3pez | trans-title=Results from Arena M\u00e9xico November 19 '13 | first=Alexis A. | date=November 20, 2013 | archivedate=November 20, 2013 | accessdate=November 20, 2013 | work=Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre | language=Spanish | url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n}}{{Professional wrestling title history middle\n|number =\u00a06\n|champion =\u00a0{{sortname|La|Sombra|Andrade Cien Almas}}\n|reign =\u00a02\n|date =\u00a0{{dts|2014|06|06}}\n|days =\u00a0{{age in days nts|month1=06|day1=06|year1=2014|month2=08|day2=01|year2=2014}}\n|location=[[Mexico City]]\n|event =\u00a0''[[CMLL Super Viernes|Super Viernes]]''\n|notes =This match was also for La Sombra's [[NWA World Historic Middleweight Championship]].\n|ref ={{efn|''CMLL'' (June 6, 2014): \"Pero al final con la ayuda de Rush y La M\u00e1scara; La Sombra se convierte en doble campe\u00f3n.\" (\"in the end with the help of Rush and La M\u00e1scara; La Sombra becomes a double champion\")<ref name=LaSombra2>{{cite web | url=http://cmll.com/02_resultados/super_viernes/super_viernes_cmll.htm | archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Q9rWeESO?url=http://cmll.com/02_resultados/super_viernes/super_viernes_cmll.htm | title=Resultados Arena M\u00e9xico Viernes 6 de Junio '14 | trans-title=Results from Arena M\u00e9xico June 6 '14 | last=Salazar L\u00f3pez | first=Alexis A. | date=June 6, 2014 | archivedate=June 7, 2014 | accessdate=June 6, 2014 | work=Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre | language=Spanish | url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n}}{{Professional wrestling title history middle\n|number =\u00a07\n|champion =\u00a0[[Volador Jr.]]\n|reign =\u00a02\n|