t=Tim | last=Hornbaker | publisher=Sports Publishing | isbn=978-1-61321-808-2 | location=New York, New York | chapter= Statistical notes | year= 2016 | edition=Revised | ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book | author= Madigan, Dan | title= Mondo Lucha a Go Go: the bizarre & honorable world of wild Mexican wrestling | publisher= HarperColins Publisher | year= 2007 | chapter = \"Okay... what is Lucha Libre?\" | page = 31 | quote=featuring clearly distinguished good guys and bad guys, or t\u00e9cnicos and rudos | isbn=978-0-06-085583-3|location=New York, New York| ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hornbaker | first=Tim|title= National Wrestling Alliance: the untold story of the monopoly that strangled pro wrestling|publisher=ECW Press|year=2007|chapter=International Expansion|isbn=978-1-55022-741-3| ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre championships}}\n{{NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nwa World Historic Welterweight Championship}}\n[[Category:Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre championships]]\n[[Category:Welterweight wrestling championships]]\n[[Category:World professional wrestling championships]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wrestling championship}}\n{{good article}}\n{{about|the current NWA welterweight title that CMLL introduced in 2010|the original NWA welterweight title created in 1946|NWA World Welterweight Championship}}\n{{Infobox pro wrestling championship\n|championshipname = NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship\n|image            = NWA World Historic Light Heavyweight Championship.jpg\n|caption          = The belt design of all three NWA Historic championships\n|alt              = A championship belt with a silver front plate\n|currentholder    = [[Volador Jr.]]\n|won              = August 4, 2018\n|promotion        = [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]]\n|created          = August 12, 2010<ref name=FirstHistoric/>\n|mostreigns       = [[Volador Jr.]] ([[#List of combined reigns|3 reigns]])\n|firstchamp       = [[Mephisto (wrestler)|Mephisto]]<ref name=FirstHistoric/>\n|longestreign     = [[Volador Jr.]] {{nobr|({{age in days nts|month1=08|day1=01|year1=2014}})}}<ref name=VoladorJr2/>\n|shortestreign    = [[La Sombra (wrestler)|La Sombra]] {{nobr|(56 days)}}<ref name=VoladorJr2/><ref name=LaSombra2/>\n|pastnames        = CMLL Historic Welterweight Championship<ref name=FirstHistoric/>\n|heaviest         = [[Matt Taven]] ({{convert|99|kg|lb|abbr=on}})<ref name=\"AlmanacStats\">{{cite news|title=Statistics for Professional wrestlers|work=PWI Presents: 2007 Wrestling Almanak and book of facts|publisher=Kappa Publications|id=2007 Edition|page=72}}</ref>\n|lightest=[[M\u00e1scara Dorada]] ({{convert|80|kg|lb|abbr=on}}){{efn|''NJPW'': \"\u4f53\u91cd 80kg\" (\"Weight 80 kg\")<ref name=NJPW>{{cite web | url= http://www.njpw.co.jp/data/detail_profile.php?f=595 | script-title=ja:\u30de\u30b9\u30ab\u30e9\u30fb\u30c9\u30e9\u30c0 | trans-title=Mascara Dorada| accessdate=January 19, 2015 | work=[[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] | language=Japanese | archivedate=April 13, 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413190155/http://www.njpw.co.jp/data/detail_profile.php?f=595}}</ref>}}\n|youngest         = [[La Sombra (wrestler)|La Sombra]] {{nobr|({{Age in years and days|November 3, 1989|March 13, 2011}})}}{{efn|''Fuego en el Ring\": \"Fecha de nacimiento: 03 de Noviembre de 1983\" (\"Date of Birth: November 3, 1983\")<ref name=FuegoSombra>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuegoenelring.com/wrestlers_full_tec.php?wrestlers_id=84|title=Tecnicos \u2013 La Sombra|accessdate=October 17, 2009|work=Fuego en el ring|language=Spanish| archivedate=July 11, 2011 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711053948/http://www.fuegoenelring.com/wrestlers_full_tec.php?wrestlers_id=84}}</ref>}}\n|oldest           = [[Negro Casas]] {{nobr|({{Age in years and days|January 10, 1960|February 13, 2012}})}}{{efn|''PWI Almanac'' p. 69: \"Date of birth: January 10, 1960\"<ref name=\"Almanac2008Stats\">{{cite news|title=Statistics for Professional wrestlers|work=PWI Presents: 2008 Wrestling Almanak and book of facts|publisher=Kappa Publications|id=2008 Edition|page=69}}</ref>}}\n|}}\n\nThe '''NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship''' (''Campeonato Mundial Historico de Peso Welter de la NWA'' in [[Spanish language|Spanish]]) is a [[professional wrestling]] championship governed by [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]] (CMLL). CMLL had held the [[NWA World Welterweight Championship]] for over 53 years even after leaving the NWA in 1989. In 2010 the [[National Wrestling Alliance]], represented by [[Blue Demon Jr.]], the president of NWA Mexico, sent letters to CMLL telling them to stop promoting NWA-branded championships since CMLL was not part of the NWA any longer. On August 12, 2010, CMLL debuted the new NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship belt and named Mephisto, the final CMLL-recognized NWA World Welterweight Champion, as the inaugural champion. The championship was initially announced as the CMLL Historic Welterweight Championship, but when the belt was unveiled, it was labelled the \"NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship\".\n\nIn Mexico, the ''lucha libre'' commission's definition of the [[Lucha Libre#Weight classes|welterweight weight class]] is between {{convert|70|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and {{convert|78|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. [[Volador Jr.]] is the current NWA World Historic Welterweight Champion, having defeated [[Matt Taven]] on August 3, 2018. This is Volador Jr.'s third reign with the title; he is the ninth overall champion. Volador Jr.'s second reign was the longest of any NWA World Historic Welterweight Champion, 1,337 days. All title matches take place under [[Professional wrestling match types#Series variations|best two-out-of-three falls]] rules when they take place in Mexico, but has been defended in single [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Fall|fall]] matches in Japan.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Mephisto CMLL.jpg|thumb|left|[[Mephisto (wrestler)|Mephisto]], the last [[NWA World Welterweight Championship|NWA World Welterweight Champion]]|alt=The masked wrestler Mephisto in the ring during a match.]]\nIn 1948 the Mexican ''[[lucha libre]]'' or [[professional wrestling promotion]] [[Empresa Mexicana de Lucha Libre]] (EMLL; Spanish for \"Mexican Wrestling Enterprise\") created the [[NWA World Welterweight Championship|World Welterweight Championship]].{{efn|name=NWAWelterBook|''Duncan & Will'' (2000) p. 390, Chapter name \"EMLL NWA Welterweight Title\"{{sfn|Duncan|Will|2000|p=390}}}} When EMLL became a member of the [[National Wrestling Alliance]] (NWA) in 1952 the championship was given the \"NWA\" prefix and became known as the NWA World Welterweight Championship. In the late 1980s, EMLL left the [[National Wrestling Alliance]] (NWA) to avoid the politics of the NWA.{{efn|name=Alliance|''Hornbakker'' (2006) p 305: \"EMLL was a member of the NWA from 1952 to 1986, and Lutteroth controlled the Alliance world light heavyweight, middleweight and welterweight titles.\"{{sfn|Hornbaker|2006|p=305}}}} While they left the NWA they did retain control of the NWA World Welterweight Championship as their main championship of the [[Lucha libre#Weight classes|welterweight division]]. They also promoted the [[Mexican National Welterweight Championship]] as a secondary title in the Welterweight division.{{efn|''Duncan & Will'' (2000) p. 392 chapter name \"Mexico: National Welterweight Title{{sfn|Duncan|Will|2000|p=392}}}} In 1992 EMLL changed their name and became known as ''Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre'' (CMLL; \"World Wrestling Council\") to rebrand themselves as a separate entity after leaving the NWA.{{efn|''Madigan'' \"in the late 1980s EMLL withdrew from the National Wrestling Alliance\"{{sfn|Madigan|2007|p=32}}}} They added a third welterweight championship to the promotion when they created the [[CMLL World Welterweight Championship]] on February 15, 1992.{{sfn|Duncan|Will|2000|p=396}}\n\nAfter the introduction of the CMLL championship, the then-reigning NWA World Welterweight Championship [[Misterioso (wrestler)|Misterioso]] left CMLL, vacating the championship.{{efn|''Duncan & Will'' (2000) p. 390 \"Vacant in 92/05 when Misterioso leaves EMLL.\"{{sfn|Duncan|Will|2000|p=390}}}} For the subsequent three years, CMLL did not promote the NWA World Welterweight Championship until bringing it back in the winter of 1995. [[Negro Casas]] won the championship, holding it until August 1996 where he lost it as part of a tournament to create the [[J-Crown]], eight championships unified as one.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=26&nr=1282 | title=J-Crown Tournament | work=Pro Wrestling History | accessdate=June 8, 2017}}</ref> from 1996 through 2007 the championship was promoted in Japan, but on November 27, 2007, [[La Sombra (wrestler)|La Sombra]] defeated [[Hajime Ohara]] to bring the championship back to CMLL.<ref name=WelterCage>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=5&nr=139&page=5&reign=57 | work=CageMatch | accessdate=June 5, 2017 | title=NWA World Welterweight Championship > Title Reigns > 27.11.2007 - 27.05.2009: La Sombra}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 the NWA, represented by NWA Mexico president [[Blue Demon Jr.]], reached out to CMLL and asked them to stop using the NWA-branded championships since they were not part of the NWA. Blue Demon Jr. was in the process of establishing NWA Mexico as a promotion and wanted to use the championship.{{efn|''S\u00faper Luchas'' (March 4, 2010): \"Blue Demon Jr. inform\u00f3 que NWA M\u00e9xico desconoce los t\u00edtulos mundiales que tienen los elementos del CMLL\" (\"Blue Demon Jr. Reported that NWA Mexico does not recognize the world championships controlled by CMLL\")<ref>{{cite web | url=http://superluchas.com/2010/03/04/blue-demon-jr-no-reconoce-los-titulos-de-nwa-que-estan-en-el-cmll-realizara-eliminatorias-para-sacar-a-los-nuevos-campeones/ | title=Blue Demon Jr. no reconoce los t\u00edtulos de NWA que est\u00e1n en el CMLL- Realizar\u00e1 eliminatorias para sacar a los nuevos campeones | trans-title=Blue Demon Jr. does not recognize the NWA titles held by CMLL- Will hold tournaments to determine new champions | date=March 4, 2010 | accessdate=June 25, 2015 | publisher=S\u00faper Luchas | language=Spanish | first=Alex | last=Ruiz}}</ref>}} There had been previous attempts by the NWA to gain back control of the three NWA-branded championships that CMLL used, the welterweight championship as well as the [[NWA World Light Heavyweight Championship]] and the [[NWA World Middleweight Championship]], but in those instances, CMLL had not responded to those requests at all. The promotion did not directly respond to the latest claim; the NWA Welterweight Champion, [[Mephisto (wrestler)|Mephisto]], commented instead, simply stating that the championships belonged to CMLL.{{efn|''S\u00faper Luchas'' (March 12, 2010): \"esos campeonatos siempre han estado en luchadores del CMLL\" (\"those championships have always belonged to CMLL wrestlers\")<ref>{{cite web|url=http://superluchas.com/2010/03/12/mephisto-responde-a-blue-demon-jr-no-tengo-que-entrar-a-ninguna-eliminatoria-porque-yo-soy-el-campeon/ |title=Mephisto responde a Blue Demon Jr.: \"No tengo que entrar a ninguna eliminatoria porque yo soy el campe\u00f3n...\" | trans-title=Mephisto responds to Blue Demon Jr .: \"I do not have to enter a tournamnent because I am the champion ...\"|author=Ruiz Glez, Alex|date=March 12, 2010|accessdate=March 14, 2010|work=S\u00faper Luchas|language=Spanish}}</ref>}} Finally, on August 12, 2010, CMLL debuted the new NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship belt and named Mephisto, the final CMLL-recognized NWA World Welterweight Champion, as the inaugural champion.<ref name=FirstHistoric/> The championship was initially announced as the CMLL Historic Welterweight Championship,<ref name=FirstHistoric/> but when the belt was unveiled, it was called the NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship.<ref name=FirstHistoric/>\n\n==Reigns==\n[[File:La Sombra.jpg|thumb|right|[[La Sombra (wrestler)|La Sombra]], the youngest wrestler to win the championship|alt=Masked wrestler La Sombra posing on the ropes during an outdoor wrestling event]]\n\n[[Matt Taven]] is the current NWA World Historic Welterweight Champion, having won the title on March 30, 2018, defeating [[Volador Jr.]] He is the eight overall champion and the first wrestler from the United States to hold the championship. Volador Jr. and [[La Sombra (wrestler)|La Sombra]] are the only two wrestlers to hold the championship twice. Volador Jr's second reign is the longest individual reign while La Sombra's 56-day reign in 2014 is the shortest of all championship reigns.<ref name=LaSombra2/><ref name=VoladorJr2/> On January 22, 2012, La Sombra became the first champion to defend the NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship outside of Mexico as he defeated Volador Jr. during the CMLL and [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW) co-promoted [[Fantastica Mania 2012]] in Tokyo, Japan.{{efn|''NJPW'' (January 22, 2012): \"\u30e1\u30a4\u30f3\u30a4\u30d9\u30f3\u30c8\u306f\u3001\u73fe\u5728\u306eCMLL\u3067\u30c8\u30c3\u30d72\u3068\u8a00\u308f\u308c\u308b\u30e9\u30fb\u30bd\u30f3\u30d6\u30e9\u3068\u30dc\u30e9\u30c9\u30fc\u30eb\u30fb\u30b8\u30e5\u30cb\u30a2\u304c\u3001NWA\u4e16\u754c\u30d2\u30b9\u30c8\u30ea\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30a6\u30a7\u30eb\u30bf\u30fc\u738b\u5ea7\u3092\u61f8\u3051\u3066\u6fc0\u7a81\u3002\" (\"In the main event, La Sombra and Volador Jr., who are said to currently be the top 2 in CMLL, met in a match for the NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship. \")<ref name=NJPWNight2>{{cite web | url= http://www.njpw.co.jp/tornament/12815?showResult=1 | title= NJPW Presents CMLL Fantastica Mania 2012 | date= January 22, 2012 | accessdate= January 22, 2012 | work=[[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] | language=Japanese | archivedate=January 25, 2012 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125074113/http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=491}}</ref>}}{{efn|''S\u00faper Luchas'' (January 22, 2012): \"NWA World Historic Welterweight Title: La Sombra (c) vence a Volador Jr. (21:47) con un Moonsault Press defendiendo el t\u00edtulo.\" (\"NWA World Historic Welterweight Title: La Sombra (c) defeated Volador Jr. (21:47) with a Moonsault Press defending the title.\")<ref name=SLNight2>{{cite web | url= http://superluchas.com/2012/01/22/njpw-cmll-resultados-fantasticamania-2012-dia-2/ | title= NJPW-CMLL: Resultados \"Fantasticaman\u00eda 2012\u2033 D\u00eda 2 | trans-title=NJPW-CMLL \"Fantasticamania 2012\" Results day 2 | author=Soy Rudo | date= January 22, 2012 | accessdate= January 22, 2012 | work=S\u00faper Luchas | language=Spanish}}</ref> }}\n\nAt the age of {{Age in years and days|November 3, 1989|March 13, 2011}} when he won the championship the first time, La Sombra is the youngest wrestler to win the championship.<ref name=FuegoSombra/> At {{Age in years and days|January 10, 1960|February 13, 2012}} at the time of his title win, [[Negro Casas]] is the oldest wrestler to win the championship.<ref name=\"Almanac2008Stats\"/>\n\n==Rules==\nAs a professional wrestling championship, it is not won legitimately; it is instead won via a predefined outcome of matches.{{efn|name=Hornbaker|''Hornbaker'' (2016) p. 550: \"Professional wrestling is a sport in which match finishes are predetermined. Thus, win/loss records are not indicative of a wrestler's genuine success based on their legitimate abilities - but on now much, or how little they were pushed by promoters\"{{sfn|Hornbaker|2016|p=550}}}} The Championship is designated as a welterweight title, which means that the championship can officially only be competed for by wrestlers weighing between {{convert|70|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and {{convert|78|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.{{efn|''Comisi\u00f3n de Box y Lucha Libre'' p. 42 \"Welter77 kilos\" (\"Welterweight 77 Kilos\")<ref name=\"BoxYLucha\">{{cite web| url= http://www.ordenjuridico.gob.mx/Estatal/ESTADO%20DE%20MEXICO/Reglamentos/MEXREG004.pdf | title= Reglamento de Boy Y Lucha Libre Professional del Estado de Mexico| author= Arturo Montiel Rojas | publisher= Comisi\u00f3n de Box y Lucha Libre Mexico D.F. | date= August 30, 2001 | accessdate= April 3, 2009 | language= Spanish |  archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061130181418/http://www.ordenjuridico.gob.mx/Estatal/ESTADO%20DE%20MEXICO/Reglamentos/MEXREG004.pdf|archivedate=November 30, 2006}}</ref>}} In the 20th century Mexican wrestling enforced the weight divisions more strictly, but in the 21st century the rules have occasionally been ignored for some of the weight divisions. The heaviest welterweight champion on record is [[Mephisto (wrestler)|Mephisto]] who was announced as weighing {{convert|90|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, {{convert|12|kg|lb|abbr=on}} above the official maximum weight limit.<ref name=\"AlmanacStats\"/> While the heavyweight championship is traditionally considered the most prestigious weight division in professional wrestling, CMLL places more emphasis on the lower weight divisions.{{efn|''Madigan'' (2007): \"Traditionally the heavyweight division was not considered the biggest draw, nor the most important division in Mexico\"{{sfn|Madigan|2007|p=115}}}} All title matches promoted in Mexico take place under [[Professional wrestling match types#Series variations|best two-out-of-three falls]] rules,{{efn|''Comisi\u00f3n de Box y Lucha Libre'' p. 44 \"ARTICULO 258.- Cada combate de lucha libre tendr\u00e1 como limite tres ca\u00eddas; cada ca\u00edda ser\u00e1 sin limite\nde tiempo, ganar\u00e1 quien obtenga dos ca\u00eddas de las tres en disputa\" (\"ARTICLE 258.- Each wrestling match shall have as limit three falls; Each fall will be without time limit. The winner will be the one to first obtain two of the three falls in the match,\")<ref name=\"BoxYLucha\"/>}} while championship matches promoted in Japan followed the local custom and were only one fall matches.<ref name=NJPWNight2/><ref name=SLNight2/>\n{{clear}}\n==Title history==\n{{Professional wrestling title history top|active=yes}}\n{{Professional wrestling title history middle\n|number =\u00a01\n|champion =\u00a0[[Mephisto (wrestler)|Mephisto]]\n|reign =\u00a01\n|date =\u00a0{{dts|2010|08|12}}\n|days =\u00a0{{age in days nts|month1=08|day1=12|year1=2010|month2=03|day2=13|year2=2011}}\n|location=[[Mexico City]]\n|event =\u00a0Press conference at [[Arena M\u00e9xico]]\n|notes =Mephisto was the final CMLL-recognized [[NWA World Welterweight Championship|NWA World Welterweight Champion]] and was thus named the first NWA World Historic Welterweight Champion.\n|ref =<ref name=FirstHistoric>{{cite web | url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1282333662 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100823021731/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1282333662 | title=Viva la Raza! Lucha Weekly | archivedate=August 23, 2010 | date=August 20, 2010 | accessdate=September 13, 2014 | first=Josh | last=Boutwell | work=Wrestleview}}</ref>\n}}{{Professional wrestling title history middle\n|number =\u00a02\n|champion =\u00a0{{sortname|La|Sombra|Andrade Cien Almas}}\n|reign =\u00a01\n|date =\u00a0{{dts|2011|03|13}}\n|days =\u00a0{{age in days nts|month1=03|day1=13|year1=2011|month2=02|day2=13|year2=2012}}\n|location=[[Mexico City]]\n|event =\u00a0''Domingo Familiar''\n|notes =\u00a0&nbsp;\n|ref ={{efn|''S\u00faper Luchas'' (March 14, 2011): \"5.- Campeonato mundial hist\u00f3rico NWA peso Welter: Sombra nuevo campe\u00f3n al vencer a Mephisto\" (\"5 NWA World Historic Welterweight Championship Sombra became the new champion with a victory over Mephisto\")<ref name=LaSombra>{{cite web | url= http://superluchas.com/2011/03/14/arena-mexico-resultados-13-de-marzo-la-sombra-nuevo-campeon-mundial-historico-nwa-de-peso-welter/ | title= Arena M\u00e9xico (resultados 13 de Marzo) \u00a1La Sombra nuevo campe\u00f3n mundial hist\u00f3rico NWA de peso Welter! | trans-title=Arena M\u00e9xico (results from March 13) \u00a1La Sombra is the new NWA World Historic Welterweight Champion | author=Ruiz Glez, Alex | date= March 14, 2011 | accessdate= June 26, 2011 | work= S\u00faper Luchas | language=Spanish}}</ref>}}\n}}{{Professional wrestling title history middle\n|number =\u00a03\n|champion =\u00a0{{sortname|Negro|Casas}}\n|reign =\u00a01\n|date =\u00a0{{dts|2012|02|13}}\n|days =\u00a0{{age in days nts|month1=02|day1=13|year1=2012|month2=06|day2=02|year2=2013}}\n|location=[[Puebla, Puebla]]\n|event =\u00a0[[House show|Live event]]\n|notes =\u00a0&nbsp;\n|ref ={{efn|''Cinco Radio'': \"obtuvo el hist\u00f3rico campeonato mundial welter de la NWA\" (\"he won the historic NWA welterweight championship \")<ref name=NegroCasas>{{cite web | url=http://www.cincoradio.com.mx/noticia/negro-casas-nuevo-campeon-mundial-welter/ | title=Negro Casas Nuevo Campe\u00f3n Mundial Welter | trans-title=Negro Casas is the new world welterweight champion | last=Blanco | first=Alejandro | date=February 14, 2012 | accessdate=February 14, 2012 | work=Cinco Radio | language=Spanish | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020071038/http://www.cincoradio.com.mx/noticia/negro-casas-nuevo-campeon-mundial-welter | archive-date=October 20, 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n}}{{Professional wrestling title history middle\n|number =\u00a04\n|champion =\u00a0{{sort|Mascara Dorada|[[M\u00e1scara Dorada]]}}\n|reign =\u00a01\n|date =\u00a0{{dts|2013|06|02}}\n|days =\u00a0{{age in days nts|month1=06|day1=02|year1=2013|month2=11|day2=19|year2=2013}}\n|location=[[Mexico City]]\n|event =\u00a0[[Sin Salida (2013)|''Sin Salida'']]\n|notes =\u00a0&nbsp;\n|ref ={{efn|''CMLL'' (June 3, 2013): \"El Campeonato Mundial Hist\u00f3rico NWA de Peso Welter tiene un nuevo due\u00f1o: M\u00e1scara Dorada.\" (\"The NWA Welterweight World Championship has a new owner: M\u00e1scara Dorada\")<ref name=MascaraDorada>{{cite web | url=http://cmll.com/02_resultados/dom_arena_mex/dom_arenamex.htm | archiveurl=htt